            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"margin:0in 0in 0.0001pt\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">From Ovid's playful claim that Cupid stole a foot away from his hexameter, transforming his poetry from epic to elegiac, to Dante's employment of Vergil as his guide through the underworld, authors have found many strategies to express the ways in which their works, and the forms in which they write, arise from earlier forms of literature. This course takes up the question of literary transformation, with special attention intertextuality, allusion, and adaptation across time and culture. Units will include creative translation as a form of adaptation, as in Maria Dahvana Headley's <i>Beowulf,</i> the reception and adaptation of Latin epic in Dante's <i>Inferno,</i> Japanese ghost stories from Noh drama to contemporary feminist fiction, the rise of the Gothic novel, the literary creativity of the Bengali Renaissance, and fragmentation and reuse from the cento to modernist poetry to create new forms from old texts. Along the way, we will be practicing how to read closely and deeply, ask probing questions, analyze literary evidence, and arrive at strong arguments. There will also be opportunities for creative work at various points during the semester.</span></span></p></div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>TBA</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>TBA</p></div></div>",
