            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This course introduces psychology as an empirical, behavioral science. It considers the approaches different psychologists take to describe and explain behavior. It covers a broad range of topics, including how animals learn, how personality develops and influences functioning, how the nervous system is structured and how knowledge of neuroscience may inform an understanding of mental disorders, how people acquire, remember and process information, how psychopathology is diagnosed and treated, how children and adults develop, and how people behave in groups and think about social environments. This course also challenges claims made about human behavior and the ways in which we can address those claims that reflect misinformation. </p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:0in; text-align:left\"><span style=\"font-family:Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size:12px;\"><span style=\"unicode-bidi:embed\"><span style=\"word-break:normal\"><span style=\"font-weight:bold\">Differentiate, explain, and evaluate the basic methodologies used in psychological research.</span></span></span></span></span></p><p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:0in; text-align:left\"><span style=\"font-family:Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size:12px;\"><span style=\"unicode-bidi:embed\"><span style=\"word-break:normal\"><span style=\"font-weight:bold\">Use a critical analysis of the scientific method as a basis for evaluating psychological information.</span></span></span></span></span></p><p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:0in; text-align:left\"><span style=\"font-family:Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size:12px;\"><span style=\"unicode-bidi:embed\"><span style=\"word-break:normal\"><span style=\"font-weight:bold\">Describe and explain the processes and principles of the major theoretical perspectives in psychology.</span></span></span></span></span></p><p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:0in; text-align:left\"><span style=\"font-family:Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size:12px;\"><span style=\"unicode-bidi:embed\"><span style=\"word-break:normal\"><span style=\"font-weight:bold\">Apply major concepts, theoretical ideas, and </span></span></span></span></span><span style=\"font-family:Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size:12px;\"><span style=\"unicode-bidi:embed\"><span style=\"word-break:normal\"><span style=\"font-weight:bold\">principles of psychology to personal and </span></span></span></span></span><span style=\"font-family:Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size:12px;\"><span style=\"unicode-bidi:embed\"><span style=\"word-break:normal\"><span style=\"font-weight:bold\">social issues.</span></span></span></span></span></p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>There is no specific text. I have collected readings for you that will be in the LMS. Please make sure to check the online readings for the week on our course website. Please make sure to do this every week! </p><p>There will be two categories of readings: Required readings which are approximately equivalent to a standard textbook chapter and recommended readings that support the required readings. They are not mandatory but might help you understand the finer points. There will also be videos and podcasts in the supplemental folders. </p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Reading quizzes\u201410% total grade; Homeworkts\u201410% of grade; Thinking Assignments\u201420% of grade Exam 1- 15% of total grade Exam 2- 15% of total grade Exam 3- 15% of total grade Final Exam - 15% of total grade.</p><p> </p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This is a synchronous course and it will be very important to attend all class sessions.</p></div></div>",
