            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><h2>How this class will work</h2><p>In this class we will \u201cdo\u201d some number theory. There is no lecturing and no textbook, rather, there is a set of problems that are designed to allow you to walk through the theory yourselves. In the process you will also learn how to think and write mathematically. The problem set is shared with you right at the beginning and you work on it throughout the semester. You work on it before class, with the goal of having something new ready to present in our upcoming meeting. (A new problem is one that has not been presented before.) You must work on these problems independently -- the idea is to produce your solution -- that\u2019s the heart of the process, and also the fun of it. This isn\u2019t groupwork. Don\u2019t look up anything. However feel free to come and consult us if you are stuck. This option is always open to you. </p><p dir=\"ltr\">As we go along, there might be some weeks when the problems are harder than before, and you don't end up with  anything to present. That's okay. Your work may not result in completed solutions but will still enable you to make the most of the presentations of others. </p><h2>In-class presentations</h2><p dir=\"ltr\">Before the class you will upload your solutions to problems (whatever you have ready) on Moodle. The cut-off time is 7am (this allows us a little time to prepare for the class.) We will go through the problems sequentially. If the next problem to be presented is say problem 6, and several people have it ready, it will go to the person who has had the fewest presentations so far. </p><h2 dir=\"ltr\">Weekly turn-in problems</h2><p dir=\"ltr\">Every week you will have a turn-in assignment which will usually consist of one or two problems. This will be turned in on Thursdays. For the first few weeks you will have a weekly appointment with one of us to go over a draft of your assignment. If your assignment has more than one problem, you may just bring one problem to this appointment. The idea is that you get some feedback on what the finished proof needs to look like.  </p><p dir=\"ltr\">IMPORTANT: The turn in is supposed to be a proof written for an audience of your peers. It should be both correct and clear, and the reader should be able to follow your argument without having to guess or fill in anything by themselves. </p><p dir=\"ltr\">The purpose of the TURN IN assignments is to train you to prove theorems. It is not expected that you started the class with this skill. Hence some low grades are to be expected. Do not be upset. Just come see us. The assignments in the first few weeks will have half the weight of later assignments. </p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>The whole purpose of this course is to get you used to thinking and writing mathematically. It will serve you well not just in future math courses, but any place you need to make and present a rigorous argument. You will also learn some number theory. (In th second half of the semester, we may go on to a topic other than number theory.)</p></div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p dir=\"ltr\">Your overall grade will have these components:</p><ol><li dir=\"ltr\"><p dir=\"ltr\">presentations  (35%)</p></li><li dir=\"ltr\"><p dir=\"ltr\">participation (15%)</p></li><li dir=\"ltr\"><p dir=\"ltr\">written turn-ins (35%)</p></li><li dir=\"ltr\"><p dir=\"ltr\">in class exercises/ quizzes (15%)</p></li></ol><p> </p><p dir=\"ltr\">Grading for presentations will be based on this scale. This will be done privately and you will only be able to see your own points. </p><p dir=\"ltr\">4 = Your proof was accepted as correct by the class</p><p dir=\"ltr\">3 or 2 = There were some issues that came up but you were able to resolve it</p><p dir=\"ltr\">1 = The proof was left unfinished</p><p dir=\"ltr\">(If you have reserved a problem you will only get the points next time.)</p><p> </p><p dir=\"ltr\">Grading for TURN IN assignments will be based on this scale.</p><p dir=\"ltr\">4 = You turned in a correct proof.</p><p dir=\"ltr\">3 = You know how to prove the theorem but some of what you have written is not correct.</p><p dir=\"ltr\">2 = You have a mistake in your work or I do not understand what you have written, but I believe that you have a good idea.</p><p dir=\"ltr\">1 = There is at least one major flaw in your argument.</p><p> </p><p dir=\"ltr\">The participation part of the grade will be based on:</p><ul><li dir=\"ltr\"><p dir=\"ltr\">attendance, </p></li><li dir=\"ltr\"><p dir=\"ltr\">preparedness (this is a way for you to get credit for problems you had ready to present but didn\u2019t get a chance to present)</p></li><li dir=\"ltr\"><p dir=\"ltr\">contributions to discussions that are positive in both spirit and content. This includes contributions you make in writing on Moodle. </p></li></ul><p> </p><p dir=\"ltr\"><b>Basis of final course grade: </b></p><p dir=\"ltr\">The meanings of the course grades are:</p><p> </p><table><colgroup><col width=\"390\"></colgroup><tbody><tr><td><p dir=\"ltr\">A: excellent</p></td></tr><tr><td><p dir=\"ltr\">B: good</p></td></tr><tr><td><p dir=\"ltr\">C: satisfactory</p></td></tr><tr><td><p dir=\"ltr\">D: learnt enough to pass</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p dir=\"ltr\">To determine the letter grades, I will use the following scale. Plus /minus and borderline cases will be at my discretion. </p><p> </p><table><colgroup><col width=\"390\"></colgroup><tbody><tr><td><p dir=\"ltr\">A: 90+</p></td></tr><tr><td><p dir=\"ltr\">B: 80+</p></td></tr><tr><td><p dir=\"ltr\">C: 70+</p></td></tr><tr><td><p dir=\"ltr\">D: 50+</p></td></tr><tr><td><p dir=\"ltr\">F: &lt;50</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><h2>Attendance: </h2><p dir=\"ltr\">I expect you to be there for every class but of course there may be times when you are unable to attend. In such a case you should inform us as soon as you realize you won\u2019t be able to attend. </p></div></div>",
