            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"line-height:115%\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\" lang=\"EN-US\">This course is an undergraduate level course that introduces students to basics of International Relations (IR). It aims to familiarize students with major theoretical approaches to the discipline, as well as the major debates in IR Theory. We will be studying frameworks such as realism, liberalism, and constructivism as well as critical approaches to IR; understand questions of positionality and levels of analysis; examine contemporary problems through the lens of IR and discuss future challenges and directions for the discipline. </span></span></span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"> </p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"line-height:115%\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\" lang=\"EN-US\">The course will equip students with fundamental concepts guiding the discipline \u2013 the international order and anarchy, sovereignty and nation states, conflict and cooperation within the system, and the motivations that guide the actors to make these decisions. </span></span></span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"> </p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"line-height:115%\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\" lang=\"EN-US\">As the global political order undergoes significant transformation, this course offers multiple lenses to make this world intelligible. It demonstrates how concepts and theories may be employed to improve our understanding of historical and contemporary issues. By the end of the semester, students will be equipped to critically think and write about key events in international politics, and familiar with the strengths and weaknesses of the various disciplinary paradigms in explaining, understanding, and evaluating key global events. </span></span></span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"> </p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"><em><strong>This course will be taught by Dr Deep Pal. For any questions/clarifications, please email him at</strong> </em><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\" lang=\"EN-US\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\">deep.pal@ashoka.edu.in</span></span></p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\" lang=\"EN-US\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\">Classes will be held twice a week, on Mondays and Thursdays, from 4:50 p.m. to 6:20 p.m. Students are expected to come for class having read the assigned material for the week (including for the first week) and prepared to actively contribute to the discussion in class. </span></span></p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Please see attached syllabus</p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><ul><li style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 0cm 36pt\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"line-height:115%\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><b><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\" lang=\"EN-US\">Active participation (10%): </span></b><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\" lang=\"EN-US\">\u201cActive participation\u201d does not necessarily mean talking the most - but contributing meaningfully to the collective reflection and debate in class. This may be in the form of questions, observations, or interventions based on the readings for the week. The quality of participation will be evaluated by the instructor and assigned a grade. </span></span></span></span></li><li style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 0cm 36pt\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"line-height:115%\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><b><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\" lang=\"EN-US\">Departmental lecture Series (10%) </span></b><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\" lang=\"EN-US\">The IR department will be organizing weekly lecture series and the students are expected to attend at least eight of the sessions. Attendance will be maintained separately for the same.</span></span></span></span></li><li style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 0cm 36pt\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"line-height:115%\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><b><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\" lang=\"EN-US\">Midterm exam (30%) </span></b><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\" lang=\"EN-US\">After the end of the first part of the course an \u2018in-class\u2019 mid-term exam will be set. The exam will consist of questions relating to the readings covered up to that date. Participation in this exam is compulsory.</span></span></span></span></li><li style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 0cm 36pt\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"line-height:115%\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><b><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\" lang=\"EN-US\">End Semester Submission (50%)</span></b><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\" lang=\"EN-US\"> A 2500-word analytical essay. Details will be announced in class.</span></span></span></span></li></ul> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"line-height:115%\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\" lang=\"EN-US\">Attendance in this class is compulsory and will be monitored. After the first three absences, the final grade will be reduced by one point (from an A- to a B+), and by a further point for every two additional absences.</span></span></span></span></p></div></div><div><strong>Attachment</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><table><tbody><tr><td><a style=\"color:blue\" href=\"https://ams.ashoka.edu.in/UploadFiles/CourseCatalogueFiles/c0b3be2c-33b0-4e0c-8516-17d8dfb554dc.pdf\" download=\"Deep Pal IR 1001 - Spring 2022- V2.pdf\">Deep Pal IR 1001 - Spring 2022- V2.pdf</a></td></tr></tbody></table></div></div>",
