            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This is an introductory course to symbolic logic. Generally speaking, logic is the study of correct reasoning. Informal logic studies correct patterns of inference, in a relatively informal way. Formal logic, on the other hand, studies correct patterns of inference, in a relatively formal way. By \"formal\", we just mean the way a mathematician might do it. Symbolic logic is formal logic, where correct patterns of inference are symbolized into an artificial language. This class will cover both informal and formal logic, and so will contain a mixture of symbolic and non-symbolic representations of arguments. The aim is to introduce students to basic logical concepts, different logical systems, various paradoxes and other conundrums central to the development of formal logic, and perhaps most importantly, to learn how to reason better, primarily through learning how to diagram and evaluate arguments, not only those found \"in the wild\", but also one's own arguments. Topics will include: logical notations, diagramming arguments, quantification, formal proofs, paradox, classical logic, modal logic, various non-classical logics, inductive logic, computer logic, metalogic, and some (light) set theory.</p></div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>standard scale (see the syllabus)</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>attendance is mandatory</p></div></div>",
