            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p class=\"Body\" style=\"border:none; margin-bottom:0cm; margin:0cm 0cm 10pt\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"line-height:normal\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\" lang=\"EN-US\"><span style=\"font-family:Times\"><span style=\"color:black\">Do women talk more than men? Are Indians </span></span></span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\" lang=\"EN-US\"><span style=\"font-family:Times\">more interdependent than Americans? Does nutrition improve IQ? The answers to these questions and related ones are not absolute but statistical \u2013 they involve gathering data from a sample and then synthesizing the information using a relevant statistic to reach a conclusion. In this course, you will learn how to use statistical tools (central tendency, variability, probability, hypothesis testing, <i>t</i>-tests, ANOVA, regression, etc.) to answer questions of psychological interest. The emphasis is on understanding statistical concepts and performing basic statistical analyses, not on mathematical formulas and derivations.</span></span></span></span></span></span></p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p class=\"Body\" style=\"border:none; margin-bottom:0cm; margin:0cm 0cm 10pt\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"line-height:normal\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\" lang=\"EN-US\"><span style=\"font-family:Times\">By the end of this course, you will be able to:</span></span></span></span></span></span></p><ul><li style=\"border:none; margin-bottom:0cm; margin:0cm 0cm 10pt 36pt\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"line-height:normal\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\" lang=\"EN-US\"><span style=\"font-family:Times\">Appreciate why data triumphs anecdotes.</span></span></span></span></span></span></li><li style=\"border:none; margin-bottom:0cm; margin:0cm 0cm 10pt 36pt\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"line-height:normal\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\" lang=\"EN-US\"><span style=\"font-family:Times\">Read research reports critically using basic statistical methods.</span></span></span></span></span></span></li><li style=\"border:none; margin-bottom:0cm; margin:0cm 0cm 10pt 36pt\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"line-height:normal\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\" lang=\"EN-US\"><span style=\"font-family:Times\">Perform basic statistical techniques in your work.</span></span></span></span></span></span></li><li style=\"border:none; margin-bottom:0cm; margin:0cm 0cm 10pt 36pt\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"line-height:normal\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\" lang=\"EN-US\"><span style=\"font-family:Times\">Interpret complex statistical findings and graphs in the context of their level of statistical significance, including the influence of effect size, and explain these findings using simple language.</span></span></span></span></span></span></li><li style=\"border:none; margin-bottom:0cm; margin:0cm 0cm 10pt 36pt\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"line-height:normal\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\" lang=\"EN-US\"><span style=\"font-family:Times\">Communicate quantitative data in statistics, graphs, and tables.</span></span></span></span></span></span></li></ul></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"line-height:normal\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\"><b><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\" lang=\"EN-US\"><span style=\"font-family:Times\">Prerequisites: </span></span></b><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\" lang=\"EN-US\"><span style=\"font-family:Times\">None.</span></span></span></span></span></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"line-height:normal\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\"><b><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\" lang=\"EN-US\"><span style=\"font-family:Times\">Study Materials: </span></span></b></span></span></span></span></p><ul><li style=\"border:none; margin-bottom:0cm; margin:0cm 0cm 10pt 36pt\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"line-height:normal\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\" lang=\"EN-US\"><span style=\"font-family:Times\">Book: Argyrous, G. (2012). <i>Statistics for research</i> (3<sup>rd</sup> edition). Delhi: Sage. - Readings have been posted on Canvas.</span></span></span></span></span></span></li><li style=\"border:none; margin-bottom:0cm; margin:0cm 0cm 10pt 36pt\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"line-height:normal\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\" lang=\"EN-US\"><span style=\"font-family:Times\">Calculator \u2013 the most advanced functions you will use is the square root function</span></span></span></span></span></span></li><li style=\"border:none; margin-bottom:0cm; margin:0cm 0cm 10pt 36pt\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"line-height:normal\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\" lang=\"EN-US\"><span style=\"font-family:Times\">JASP (https://jasp-stats.org/) </span></span></span></span></span></span></li></ul> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Students will vote between an absolute or relative grading rubric.</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"border:none; margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Attendance will be taken within the first five minutes of every class.<b> </b>I expect students to attend all </span></span><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">lectures<span style=\"color:black\">, </span>workshops<span style=\"color:black\">, and discussion sessions. The following rules will apply for absences: </span></span></span></span></p><ul><li style=\"border:none; margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Missing 4 classes: Excused (no grade cut)</span></span></span></span></li><li style=\"border:none; margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Missing 5 classes: One grade cut on the final grade for the course </span></span></span></span></li><li style=\"border:none; margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Missing 7 classes: Two grade cuts on the final grade for the course </span></span></span></span></li><li style=\"border:none; margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Missing 9 or more classes: A \u2018Fail\u2019 grade for the course </span></span></span></span></li></ul></div></div>",
