            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">This course will cover the role of government in modern economies. We will dig deep into the study of various instruments used to generate government revenue and analyze efficient ways to spend government monies. You will also be exposed to microeconomic models that are used to study the reaction of agents to government policies.  This course will serve as a comprehensive introduction to various empirical tools used in modern public economics. Government expenditure, externalities, public goods, taxation, social security programs,  are some of the topics that will be covered in this course. Abstract concepts will be mapped to real-world examples to develop your public economics intuition.</span></span></p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>The prerequisite for this course is Microeconomic Theory I and Econometrics I. </p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><span style=\"font-family:Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif;\"><em><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\" lang=\"EN-US\">There will be 3 homeworks during the semester. Together, they will constitute 30% of the grade. Students have to write a term paper which would constitute 60% of the grade. The paper can be written in groups of 3 or lower. Each group will present the paper towards the end of the semester . The presentation would constitute 10% of the grade. </span></em></span></p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><span style=\"font-family:Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif;\">There is no attendance policy. </span></p></div></div>",
