            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This course will serve as an introduction to the theory of differential geometry. Topics which will be covered include:</p><p>Topic 1) (1 week) Review of multivariable Calculus , Directional derivatives, Jacobians, Inverse function theorem, Local study of immersion and submersion, Smooth functions with compact support, Existence of solutions of ODE.</p><p>Topic 2) (4 weeks) Theory of curves - Smooth curves, tangents, curvature, torsion, planar curves, Frennet frame.</p><p>Topic 3) (5 weeks) Theory of surfaces - Manifold structure, First and second fundamental forms, Curvatures, Gauss' excellent theorem, Parallel transport and geodesics</p><p>Topic 4) (3 weeks)  Gauss-Bonnet and other miscelleneous topics. </p><p>approximately one assignment every alternate week. Exam questions will closely resemble assignment problems and other examples and problems we do in the class. </p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Requirements: Real analysis, MVC, Linear algebra</p><p>Textbooks: As suggested in department webpage. </p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Assignments: 40% </p><p>Midsem : 30 %</p><p>Final: 30 %</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>not mandatory but strongly ecouraged. </p></div></div>",
