            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>In this course, we will try to understand the very nature of computation. We will study how it can be formally defined, what the different models of computation are, how they differ in their computational power, and so on. We will also see that oftentimes there are limits to the computational power of a machine. Please find below an indicative (but not exhaustive) list of topics that will be covered:</p><p>Regular languages, finite automata, context-free languages, PDA, Turing machines, complexity classes, etc.</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Introduction to the Theory of Computation (Third Edition) by Michael Sipser.</p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Mid-term Exam: 15%</p><p>Final Exam: 25%</p><p>Programming Assignments: 20%</p><p>Theoretical Assignments: 40%</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>None.</p></div></div><div><strong>Attachment</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><table><tbody><tr><td><a style=\"color:blue\" href=\"https://ams.ashoka.edu.in/UploadFiles/CourseCatalogueFiles/2d24a64e-5d90-47a2-b070-25badfd42880.pdf\" download=\"CS_2349_Spring_2022_Handout.pdf\">CS_2349_Spring_2022_Handout.pdf</a></td></tr></tbody></table></div></div>",
