            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>One of the ways in which mathematics grows is by solving tough problems.   In 2000, the Clay institute listed the so-called millennium problems, and announced a prize money of one million dollars each for their solution. The objective of our course is to learn about and understand one of these problems, namely the Birch-Swinnerton-Dyer Conjecture. We will do this by reading (as a group) an expository account of this conjecture beginning with the mathematics one learns in high school. The book is Elliptic Tales by Avner Ash and Robert Gross.  No background knowledge of mathematics is required. We will use the computer algebra package SAGE and graphing calculators in order to explore the intuitive side of mathematical ideas required to understand the conjecture. We will learn in groups with each other\u2019s help.</p><p>No prior knowledge of mathematics (other than what is covered in middle school) is required. No prior knowledge of programming is required. It is expected that students who are comfortable with mathematics will help others who are not so comfortable with math. </p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Students will become aware of some important mathematical ideas and their history and learn what mathematicians do. In addition, students should be able to do various tasks such as solve equations, plot graphs, describe them in technical terms, and be able to show the intuitive side of mathematics. </p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>1. Book: Elliptic Tales by Avner Ash and Robert Gross.</p><p>The objective of the lectures will be to present the math in this book so that you can read it along with me. We will try to understand the entire book. </p><p>2. Group Assignment:</p><p>A book will be assigned to a group. Read on own own, discuss with each other and write a book review; and present to the rest of the class. </p><p>3. Please download and install the computer algebra system Sage (www.sagemath.org). </p><p>4. Graphing calculator: We will use the one at www.desmos.com</p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>1. Weekly quizzes (most weeks). Weightage: 50%. 10 best will be used for determining grades. The topics will be on the basis of what was done in the previous week.</p><p>2. Group project: Book presentation and Book Review. Weightage: 50%. </p><p>Every group will have to make 2 presentations during the semester about the topic of their book and write a book review. The groups will be made by the faculty team and a book assigned to you in the beginning of the semester. </p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Attendance is mandatory but not enforced strictly. You miss at your own risk. No makeup quizzes will be given. </p></div></div>",
