            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>I plan to base the course on observations of the world around us as well as data regarding the world, on reasoning about these observations and using mathematical arguments to advance this reasoning.</p><p>I will stress estimation and approximation techniques, including order-of-magnitude arguments, the ability to understand graphs and plots, an understanding of geometeric arguments, a feeling for how different functions \u201cshould\u201d behave, probability and statistics including Bayesian methods and related questions. There will be some discussion of mathematical concepts, including the idea of numbers, functions, computability, the Cantor argument and so on. I'll stress interesting applications, such as the prosecutors fallacy in a real-life context, fractals and fractal landscapes, how to tell if a list of numbers is being faked or represents real data and so on.</p><p>Some part of the course will describe models, how to construct them and how to interpret them. I will choose a range of examples, from across the sciences, mathematics and every-day life and show how to reason quantitatively about them.</p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>An understanding of the  importance of quantitative thinking in real life.</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>No prerequisites</p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>30% Midsem, 30% assignments and quizzes, 40% Endsem</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>I expect students to attend all classes. If, for unavoidable circumstances, a student cannot attend, they are expected to email me and the TFs in advance of the class, with a reason.</p></div></div>",
