            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This course centers on the daily lives and experiences of people living in South Asia. Inspired by the focus on practice and everyday life in the work of scholars such as Pierre Bourdieu (1977a), Michel de Certeau (1984), Lila Abu-Lughod (1993), Michael Jackson (1996), and Sherry Ortner (2006).one can learn much about social-cultural worlds by examining the daily acts performed by ordinary people as they go through their lives. This course explores the ways people live, make, and experience their worlds through practices such as growing up and aging, arranging marriages, exploring sexuality, going to school, negotiating caste distinctions, practicing religion, participating in democracy, watching television, enduring violence as nations are built, and moving abroad for work. By focusing on the everyday life practices and experiences of particular people, we will explore dimensions of social-cultural life in South Asia that could not be imparted solely via abstract theoretical accounts or generalities.</p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>TBD</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>TBD</p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>TBD</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>TBD</p></div></div>",
