            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This course is based on MIT's 6.006 and covers the same topics at the same level of difficulty.</p><p>Introduction to mathematical modeling and programming of computational problems, as well as common algorithms, algorithmic paradigms, and data structures used to solve these problems. Emphasizes the relationship between algorithms and programming, and introduces basic performance measures and analysis techniques for these problems.</p><p>Broad areas: Algorithmic Thinking, Sorting, Hashing, Graphs, Dynamic Programming, Numerics, Complexity. Some advanced topics, e.g., Geometry, Compression.</p><p>A strong understanding of programming in Python and a solid background in discrete mathematics are necessary prerequisites to this course. We will use Python (version 3) programming extensively, particularly in the homework. We will also make use of basic discrete mathematics, combinatorics, graph theory, basic logic and proofs, and invariants. We are leaving it up to each individual student to decide whether to take the class without one or both of these prerequisites, but caution that the semester could be much more difficult for such students. Some students have other experience in their background that covers such background material, and others manage to learn it on their own in time. Seeking online materials related to discrete mathematics, such as lecture notes or other reading, might be helpful in this regard. If you want to speak in detail about your case, it would be good to discuss it with your TAs.</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>CLRS, class notes.</p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Problem sets 40% + two in-class exams, each worth 30%.</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>None. This is a fast-paced class with a lot of stuff to cover; people who skip class tend to fail.</p></div></div>",
