            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>India will celebrate its 75th year of independence in August 2022. The goal of this course is to trace independent India's journey using various concepts such as the state and its institutions, centre-state relations, political parties, social groups, political economy, foreign policy, among others. </p><p>The course will be divided into three parts. The first part will focus on India's transition from a British colony to an independent nation-state. The second part will make an attempt to understand the structure and processes that shaped Indian politics between India's first prime minister and the current PM - Jawaharlal Nehru and Narendra Modi. The final part of the course will reflect on India's future by narrowing the gaze on contemporary politics.   </p><p>There are no prerequisites for this course. However, you should be prepared to read at least 75 pages per week. Subrata K Mitra's \"Politics in India: Structure, Process and Policy (Routledge, 2017)\" will be the required text-book for the course along with a few selected readings every week. The final grades in the course will be based on a continuous assessment system, i.e., participation in the class (including attendance), a few short assignments, and a final paper (or exam).</p></div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>The final grades in the course will be based on a continuous assessment system, i.e., participation in the class (including attendance), a few short assignments, and a final paper (or exam).</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>The course material requires students to attend lectures and Discussion Section regularly. A percentage of your final grade is based on attendance/participation in the lectures/DS. Please send an email to the Teaching Fellow if you are missing any lecture/DS. </p></div></div>",
