            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This course is designed to introduce students to some of the foundational ideas and theories in financial economics. It has two broad components. The first component develops the core ideas of modern portfolio theory. The second component focuses on asset pricing. The course covers some of the most vital and influential concepts in financial economics: the Markowitz Portfolio Selection Model, Index Models, the Capital Asset Pricing Model (CAPM) and its variants, Arbitrage Pricing Theory, the Efficient Market Hypothesis and the Black-Scholes option pricing formula.</p></div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><strong>There will be no curving. </strong>Your total numerical score on the course will be based on class quizzes (10%), two midterms (25% each), and the final exam (40%). The final exam will be <strong>cumulative</strong>, i.e. everything taught in the course will be included in its syllabus. There will be no make-up class quizzes.</p><table style=\"width:500px;\" cellspacing=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" border=\"1\"><tbody><tr><td>Your numerical score on the course (in %)</td><td>Letter Grade</td></tr><tr><td>90 - 100</td><td>A</td></tr><tr><td>85 - 89</td><td>A-</td></tr><tr><td>80 - 84</td><td>B+</td></tr><tr><td>75 - 79</td><td>B</td></tr><tr><td>70 - 74</td><td>B-</td></tr><tr><td>65 - 69</td><td>C+</td></tr><tr><td>60 - 64</td><td>C</td></tr><tr><td>55 - 59</td><td>C-</td></tr><tr><td>50 - 54</td><td>D+</td></tr><tr><td>45 - 49</td><td>D</td></tr><tr><td>40 - 44</td><td>D-</td></tr><tr><td>0 - 39</td><td>F</td></tr></tbody></table> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>There is no attendance policy, i.e. there won't be any direct (adverse) consequence from not attending classes regularly. However, I cannot rule out indirect consequences. For example, in the past, it has been observed that students who do not attend lectures regularly tend to fare poorly in this course. Therefore, I strongly recommend that you attend the overwhelming majority of lectures.</p></div></div>",
