            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This is a second-year masters-level research-focused elective course. The main objective of this course is to introduce you to cutting-edge research in behavioral economics. In the first part of the course, we will explore the three major ways economic agents\u2019 behavior deviate from rationality, namely, non-standard preferences (e.g. present bias), non-standard beliefs (e.g., the law of small numbers), non-standard decision-making (e.g., inattention). We will discuss experimental findings and theoretical modeling in the context of these three types of decision problems. In the second half of the course, we will explore the application of behavioral economics in several sub-disciplines, namely, game theory, development economics, household finance, finance, industrial organization, public economics, etc. The goal is to study a select few topics from each sub-discipline in substantial detail. The exact choice of papers will be decided by the mutual preference of the students and the faculty. Time permitting we will also discuss the recent developments in neuroeconomics.</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Econometrics </p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><ul><li> Problem Sets (20%)</li><li>Class presentation (20%)</li><li>Referee report (20% )</li><li> Research Proposal: part 1 and 2 (40%)</li></ul><p>This is a tentative rubric and can be adjusted later. </p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>None. Feel free to drop by if you think classes are useful. But participation is highly recommended. </p></div></div>",
