            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">In this laboratory course, students will learn to employ biochemical, cell biological and microscopy techniques to isolate and visualize subcellular organelles of mammalian and plant cells.</span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">The following experiments will be performed:</span></span></p><ol><li style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 0cm 36pt\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">Cell counting using hemocytometer</span></span></li><li style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 0cm 36pt\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">Isolation of nuclear, mitochondrial and cytosolic fractions from mammalian tissues</span></span></li><li style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 0cm 36pt\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">Protein estimation by SDS PAGE gels and western blotting</span></span></li><li style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 0cm 36pt\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">Isolation of chloroplasts</span></span></li><li style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 0cm 36pt\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">Visualizing tubulin and actin in mammalian cells by immunofluorescence </span></span></li><li style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 0cm 36pt\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">Image quantification with ImageJ</span></span></li></ol></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>At the end of the course, the students will develop a working knowledge of commonly used cell biology techniques along with light microscopy and basic image analysis skills.</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Background reading materials and experimental protocols will be shared with students via emails. Office hours can be arranged by appointment</p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">Students will be evaluated on lab note-books, viva and quizzes through continuous assessment. There will be no midterm or a final. Final letter grade will be determined on a curve.  </span></span></p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">Attendance is mandatory. </span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm\">Experiments will not be repeated if a student is absents himself/herself from the laboratory</p></div></div>",
