            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\" lang=\"EN-GB\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">This course is mainly an introduction to strategic issues in Microeconomics. </span></span></p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">The main textbook used will be :</span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">Joel Watson, <i>Strategy : An Introduction to Game Theory</i>.</span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">A supplementary textbook will be </span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">Nicholson and Snyder : Microeconomic Theory (Section 8 only).</span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">I will also distribute lecture notes from time to time.  </span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"> </p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"> </p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><b>Outline of Syllabus ( </b><i>Chapter numbers refer to chapters in Watson\u2019s book. )</i></span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"> </p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><b>Part I : Introduction (Chapters 1-5)</b></span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"> </p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"> What is game theory; the notion of strategic interaction; representation of games.</span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">Strategies, Beliefs, Expected Utility</span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"> </p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><b>Part II : Behaviour in Static Settings (Chapters 6-11)</b></span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><b>        </b></span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">Dominance and Best response</span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">Nash equilibrium in Pure and Mixed Strategies</span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">Applications : Cournot, Bertrand, Hotelling</span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"> </p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><b>Part III : Behaviour in Dynamic Settings  (Chapters 14-16) </b></span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"> </p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">Backward Induction and Subgame perfection.</span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">Topics in Industrial Organisation</span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"> </p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><b>Part IV: Further Topics in Dynamic Settings (Chapters  21-23)</b></span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"> </p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">More Applications</span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"> </p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><b>Part V: Incomplete Information (Chapters 24-29)</b></span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"> </p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">Bayesian Games and Bayes Nash equilibrium</span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">Applications: Market for lemons; Auctions; Information Aggregation</span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"> </p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"> </p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><b>Part VI : Market Failure (Nicholson&amp;Snyder, Section 8)</b></span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"> </p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><b>Part VII Dynamic Incomplete Information (Chapters 28-29)*</b></span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><b>  </b>Perfect Bayesian equilibrium</span></span></p><ol><li style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 0cm 36pt\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">Application: Job market signalling; Reputatio</span></span></li></ol><p style=\"margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><b>* Part VII will be covered only if time permits.</b></span></span></p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">There will be a midterm and final examination. Each will have weight of 50%.</span></span></p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">Until further notice,  we will have in-person lectures on Monday, and online lectures on Wednesdays.  I will not have any formal attendance requirement.</span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm\">But it is essential to attend the lectures regularly and  to solve the problem sets that will be distributed from time to time.  </p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"> </p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"> </p></div></div>",
