            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Unlike quantitative research methods that are aimed at hypothesis-testing and generalization, qualitative methods aim to understand a phenomenon in a context-sensitive manner and help generate hypotheses. Here are just a handful of questions that you can answer using qualitative methods: How do Ashoka University students perceive their experiences in relation to Delhi University students? </span></span></span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">How are<span style=\"color:black\"> memories of collective violence in the past transmitted across generations? What was the psychological impact of COVID on migrant workers? How do employees </span>in corporate<span style=\"color:black\"> organizations feel about their bosses? <span style=\"background:white\">This course equips students with the theoretical as well as practical aspects of qualitative research in psychology. Further, students will learn about communicating qualitative research</span>.</span></span></span><br><br> </p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\"> By the end of the term, you will be able to:</span></span></span></span></p><ul><li style=\"border:none; margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Understand </span></span><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">the different components of the qualitative research cycle and <span style=\"color:black\">the theoretical assumptions underlying qualitative research.</span></span></span></span></li><li style=\"border:none; margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Identify, conceptualize, and plan a qualitative research project includin</span></span><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">g choosing appropriate sampling strategies<span style=\"color:black\">.</span></span></span></span></li><li style=\"margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Plan and undertake thematic analysis of qualitative data.</span></span></span></li><li style=\"margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Communicate the results of a qualitative study in the form of a scientific poster.</span></span></span></li><li style=\"border:none; margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Understand what makes for scientifically-sound and high-quality qualitative work.</span></span></span></li><li style=\"border:none; margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Critically examine your role in shaping the research process.</span></span></span></span></li></ul></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"background:white\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Pre-Requisites: Statistics and Research Methods II; completed at least 3 out of 5 core domains</span></span></span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Reading List: All books and readings have been posted on Canvas </span></span></span></span></p><ul><li style=\"border:none; margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><i><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Required Reading: </span></span></i><span style=\"background:white\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Braun, V. and Clarke, V. (2013) Successful qualitative research: A practical guide for beginners. Sage Publications. </span></span></span></span></span></li><li style=\"border:none; margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><i><span style=\"background:white\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Optional Reading:</span></span></span></i><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\"> Silverman, D. (2007) A Very Short, Fairly Interesting, Reasonably Cheap Book about Qualitative Research. Sage<span style=\"background:white\"> Publications</span>.</span></span></span></span></li></ul> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Students will be able to vote between Absolute or Relative Grading. </p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"border:none; margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Attendance will be taken within the first five minutes of every class.<b> </b>I expect students to attend all </span></span><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">lectures<span style=\"color:black\">, </span>workshops<span style=\"color:black\">, and discussion sessions. The following rules will apply for absences: </span></span></span></span></p><ul><li style=\"border:none; margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Missing 4 classes: Excused (no grade cut)</span></span></span></span></li><li style=\"border:none; margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Missing 5 classes: One grade cut on the final grade for the course </span></span></span></span></li><li style=\"border:none; margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Missing 7 classes: Two grade cuts on the final grade for the course </span></span></span></span></li><li style=\"border:none; margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Missing 9 or more classes: A \u2018Fail\u2019 grade for the course </span></span></span></span></li></ul></div></div>",
