            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This course explores the history of India between ca. 800 and 1800 CE from multiple dimensions. After a short overview of major historiographical trends and political entities, the course moves from the usual centers of political and economic narratives into the perceptions of ordinary people. Once seen from their eyes, instead of political and administrative frames, what did constitute the place called India in a millennium? How can we think of its history at a time when numerous languages, unformidable borders, insufficient technologies of communication and travel hardly connected the north with the south, east with the west? <br>We shall explore this history of an India that did or did not exist in the eyes of people, languages, texts and objects. With a combination of lectures, a close reading of secondary and primary sources, we shall study \u201cmedieval Indian history\u201d in our own ways by keeping to the foundational rules of history: evidence, descriptions and analyses. We will focus on people such as peasants, artisans, traders, travelers, mystics, dancers, beggars, slaves, servants, soldiers, smugglers, thieves, pilgrims, prostitutes, eunuchs and transvestites, but a similar approach can also be taken for languages (such as Sanskrit, Tamil, Bengali, Kannada, Persian, Assamese, Telugu, Persian, Braj, and Hindi/Urdu) and regions (varying from Kashmir to Kanyakumari, Gujarat to Bengal, Bihar to Malabar, Indore to Lahore, Assam to Andhra, Delhi to Dhaka) through simultaneous frameworks of micro-history and macro-history. The lectures will focus on the people while discussions will focus on languages and regions.<br> </p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>The successful completion of this course helps you <br>o    To acquire a better knowledge of the Indian history between ca. 800 and 1800 CE.<br>o    To read primary and secondary sources, to conduct basic historic research, and to present one\u2019s arguments on the basis of primary sources.<br>o    To understand historical practices and methodologies in dealing with the premodern period. <br>o    To think about the past critically and to comprehend scholarly arguments while keeping integrity in the responsible use of historical materials.  <br> </p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>All students must read Catherine Asher and Cynthia Talbot\u2019s <em>India before Europe</em> (Cambridge and New York: Cambridge University Press, 2006) and Manan Ahmed Asif\u2019s <em>The Loss of Hindustan: The Invention of India </em>(Cambridge, MA: Harvard University Press, 2020) in addition to the readings assigned for each class. Questions of the final exam will require you to use ideas and information contained in the readings. Likewise, demonstrating in classroom discussions that you have done the listed readings carefully and critically will constitute one-fifth of your grade. If you are not prepared to read extensively and participate in the discussions actively, this course will be a rough ride.</p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Final Exam: 50 %<br>Participation in the class discussions: 20 %<br>Essay of 1500 words: 20 %<br>Mid-term exam: 10 %<br> </p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Up to 4 unnotified or notified absences are allowed for the entire course. </p></div></div>",
