            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This class is an introduction to the field of Philosophy, and in particular Western Philosophy. Philosophers ask questions like the following: What do we know and how can we know that? What is the world really like? What exists? How is language connected to thought, and how are these connected to the world? Does God exist? Are we free to make choices? How should I act? Philosophers propose answers to these sorts of questions by developing clear, concise, and (hopefully) persuasive arguments. The purpose of this course is to introduce students to philosophical argumentation and theorizing, along with some of the most historically significant writings in Western scholarship. We will begin by briefly outlining Philosophy as a field, along with a primer on arguments and argumentation. The rest of the course is divided roughly into seven \"units\", each corresponding to a particular sub-field of Philosophy. We will read some of the most famous and influential writings within these sub-fields, addressing the most substantial, longstanding questions within them. By the end of the course, students should not only be familiar with what Philosophy is all about, they should also be better suited to think more clearly and informatively about questions of central importance to their own lives.</p></div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>standard scale (see the syllabus)</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>attendance is mandatory</p></div></div>",
