            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"background:white\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Open Sans&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#333333\">In what ways does power translate and transform through art practice? Why and how are democratic states so invested in promoting, but also censoring the arts? How do categories in art appear? What role do states, markets and artists play in producing these categories? What is the role of the market in making art and artists matter? How does an audience develop a relationship with specific artists, and acquire a taste for the arts? With a central question \u00ab what can art practice tell us about social and political institutions and relationships? \u00bb this course explores the deeply fraught yet critical alliance between political practice and the art world. To address this issue, the course begins with answering why, in the first place, should social scientists be concerned about the arts? The course will not only entail a study of important theoretical texts, alongside focusing on empirical research and literature emerging in field, but we will also critically engage with the arts and reflect on methodological strategies that are applied to study the relationship between art and politics. </span></span></span></span></span></span></p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>.</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"margin-bottom:7.5pt; margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"background:white\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Open Sans&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#333333\">Lectures: Students are expected to attend all lectures and to have completed the reading assigned for that day before class. Students are expected to be able to participate in colloquies conducted by the professor. \u2022</span></span></span></span></span></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom:7.5pt; margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"background:white\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Open Sans&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#333333\">Readings: All the mandatory readings would be made available to the students electronically at least a week before the lectures on the said topic. Note: you encouraged to read the text entirely but the essential pages are marked below.</span></span></span></span></span></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom:7.5pt; margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"background:white\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Open Sans&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#333333\">\u2022 Speak up: If you don\u2019t understand something, please just ASK. The TA will announce their office hours; mine are posted above. Please do take advantage of them. I am also willing to meet with groups of students during office hours for tutorial seminars, and to make appointments to meet with students who cannot make it to my posted office hours (within reason).</span></span></span></span></span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"background:white\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Open Sans&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#333333\">\u2022 Cheating: Cheating includes any form of plagiarism, including from any web resources, or collaborating with and/or copying from other students in your graded work. Copying a fellow student\u2019s lecture notes if you miss a class due to illness is accepted; copying lecture notes because you didn\u2019t feel like coming to class is lame. The grade for plagiarism is a straight F. </span></span></span></span></span></span></p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"margin-bottom:7.5pt; margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"background:white\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Open Sans&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#333333\">Grading: Final grade consists of three components: a mid term essay + final take home essay + class participation. The details of each are as follows:</span></span></span></span></span></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom:7.5pt; margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"background:white\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Open Sans&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#333333\">\u2022 Mid term essay: This short essay will be written on a question framed by students themselves, drawn from the assigned readings. I usually prefer this write up to be the roadmap of the final essay. The length of the essays is 2000 words. There will be penalties for late submission and extensions will be granted only in documented cases of illness or family emergency. The essay is worth 25% of final grade.</span></span></span></span></span></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom:7.5pt; margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"background:white\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Open Sans&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#333333\">\u2022 Final examination: The final examination will also be a take home essay, also on questions framed by students. The length of the essay is 4000 words. There will be penalties for late submission and extensions will be granted only in documented cases of illness or family emergency. The essay is worth 50% of final grade.</span></span></span></span></span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"background:white\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Open Sans&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#333333\">\u2022 Class participation: Apart from the two essays, students will be graded on their class participation, which includes their attendance (15%) and participation through the semesterboth in lectures and discussion sections (10%). The grade on class participation is thus worth 25% of final grade. Students are not allowed more than 5 absences through the term (which includes absences due to participation in university events, and common illnesses. For any long term medical assistance and absence (more than three absences in a row), please do submit medical certificates to the OAA. </span></span></span></span></span></span></p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"background:white\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Open Sans&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#333333\">Students are not allowed more than 5 absences through the term (which includes absences due to participation in university events, and common illnesses. For any long term medical assistance and absence (more than three absences in a row), please do submit medical certificates to the OAA. </span></span></span></span></span></span></p><p> </p></div></div>",
