            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><span style=\"font-size:18px;\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;\">SOA 1101: SOCIOLOGY AND THE MAKING OF CONCEPTS</span></span></p><p> </p><p><span style=\"font-size:18px;\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;\">Rather than ask, \u2018what is a concept?\u2019 this course is concerned with showing how concepts are made in sociology and anthropology, how they are played out or performed in local contexts and the analytic dividend that is associated with such performances. Put simply, we will ask what is the work done by concepts and whether they enrich or impoverish our understanding of social relationships. In a second move, the course will pick up forms of inquiry, such as definitions and factual descriptions to show how concepts appear. Do they point us to some abstract essence, or are they central to how we live our everyday lives? In negotiating with the above and in consultation with students of the class the course will address any three the following questions.</span></span></p><ol><li><span style=\"font-size:18px;\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;\">How do we establish proof? What is the value of the archive and the library in arriving at verity.</span></span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:18px;\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;\">Are there rules for the study of social facts?</span></span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:18px;\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;\">How do we delimit the rationality of science and politics?</span></span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:18px;\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;\">Are commodities bundles of social relatedness?</span></span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:18px;\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;\">How are distinctions established in society, and what is the significance of hierarchy in establishing social privilege?</span></span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:18px;\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;\">Is social power a relationship and what is its link to order and disorder?</span></span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:18px;\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;\">Can the secular be separated from the sacred?</span></span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:18px;\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;\">What is the force of visual images? Do they have any relationship to our sense of well-being?</span></span></li></ol><p><span style=\"font-size:18px;\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;\">The course will involve a selected reading of classical and contemporary texts in sociology and anthropology. Rather than provide an exhaustive list of readings, students will be asked to analyze no more than seven texts in the course of the semester.</span></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:18px;\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif;\">There will be a mid-semester and end-of-term appraisal of 50 marks each. </span></span></p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>A basic familiarity with major sociological concepts and their ethnographic elaboration</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>To be communicated.</p><p>We will begin our classes with a reading of</p><p>Emile Durkheim: Rules of the Sociological Method</p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>As above</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>We will follow university guidelines</p></div></div>",
