            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,serif\">How did armies fight in medieval and early modern South Asia? Who were the warrior ascetics and the armed peasants? What was the role of animals in warfare? How did issues of gender, body, environment, and culture relate to violence? These are some of the questions we will address in this course. It unravels military processes in South Asia between c. 1000 and c. 1800, in relation with broader social, political, and cultural processes. We will also study military matters related to technology, tactics, strategy, fortification, logistics, and military personnel. We will begin our journey in the early-11th century with the Chola kings of South India invading Southeast Asia and the Turks invading North India. We will stop in the mid-18th century, with the English East India Company poised to become the dominant military power of the subcontinent. </span></span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"> </p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,serif\">By the end of the semester, students will have a sound understanding of the workings of the complex yet fascinating world of war in medieval and early modern South Asia.</span></span></span></p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><ul><li><span style=\"font-size:16px;\"><span style=\"font-family:Georgia,serif;\">Class Participation (25%)</span></span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:16px;\"><span style=\"font-family:Georgia,serif;\">Mid-Term Presentation (35%)</span></span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:16px;\"><span style=\"font-family:Georgia,serif;\">Term Paper (40%)</span></span></li></ul> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><span style=\"font-family:Georgia,serif;\">TBD</span></p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><span style=\"font-family:Georgia,serif;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\">Out of the 26 classes of this course, students are required to attend at least 20.; they can be absent in up to 6 classes without having to explain themselves. They can be absent in more classes only for medical and/or other serious reasons.</span></span></p></div></div>",
