            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><span style=\"font-size:14px;\">Syllabus: Real vector spaces, subspaces, spanning sets, basis sets, dimension of a vector space.  Solution of a system of linear equations. Row space and column space of a matrix, rank of a matrix, elementary row and column operations of a matrix. Inversion of square matrices, rank factorization of a matrix. Properties of determinants. Linear transformations, range and null space of a linear transformation, rank-nullity theorem. Matrix representation of a linear transformation. Inner product spaces, normed linear spaces, examples of different normed linear spaces, orthonormal basis sets. Eigenvalues, eigenvectors, characteristic polynomials. Spectral theorem for real symmetric matrices. Singular value decompositions.</span></p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><strong>NOTE CHANGE:</strong> Our textbook will be David Lay's book Linear Algebra and its Applications. I will be sharing a pdf of the book, which is of the updated third edition. You may use a different edition, however the exercises and readings I will assign will refer to this pdf. </p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><strong>NOTE CHANGES:</strong></p><p>This course will have no midterm or final exam. Evaluation in this course will be as follows:</p><p><b>40% HW.</b> There will be four assignments. No HW will be dropped from the total. </p><p><b>50% Quizzes.</b> These will be regular quizzes held in class, every Thursday.  Each one will have 5 questions: 4 from the recent material (say from the previous three sessions) and 1 from anything covered earlier. We understand that sometimes you are not able to attend, for this reason we will drop the four lowest or missing quizzes. So if you miss a class or a quiz, please do not worry --  there's no need to start sending emails -- we are accounting for some misses already.  Of course it's best for you and your grade if you don't miss, so don't miss quizzes casually. (If you need to miss classes for an extended period, for whatever reason, then of course you should inform us.)</p><p><b>10% weekly question. </b>There will be weekly readings, recordings and exercises. Based on these, you will ask one question every week. If you really have not a single question, you may post a remark. Ten percent of the grade is reserved for having posted a meaningful question every week. If you miss one or two weeks, do not worry, but do not miss more. </p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>I expect that you attend all Thursday sessions.</p></div></div>",
