            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Literary journalism sits at a happy intersection of literary and journalistic writing. It brings in all the rigour, depth and understanding of a subject that literary writing demands, and then presents in the form of journalistic writing for a wider, non-academic readership through mass and niche media. The course will explore several different forms that exist at this confluence. We will both read and practise forms that include book criticism, long-form essays, critical interviews, in-depth profiles, informed commentary, argumentative opinion and literary juries. We will work not just with text but also videos, podcasts, and social media posts. The course will involve extensive reading of up to a dozen works of fiction.<br><br>This course will work as an alternative to Forms of Literature as a mandatory requirement for a Creative Writing minor.</p></div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Students will submit the following assignments, and individual grades for each will be combined into a final grade,</p><p>- 2 single book reviews<br>- 1 multiple book review<br>- 1 reading list<br>- 1 literary essay<br>- 1 podcast (group)<br>- 1 video (group)<br>- 1 literary jury presentation (group)</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Three absences will be allowed without grade cuts.<br>Attendance for presentations is mandatory.<br>Further absences will need to be explained.</p></div></div>",
