            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Open Sans&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#333333\">In what ways might we understand politics and various aspects of the political system by studying psychoanalytic theory? In its inverse sense, how might political theory or activity contribute to psychoanalytic reasoning? This course aims to explore intellectual ideas and conversations between primarily these two perspectives, including the disciplinary anxieties and methodologies through which these perspectives are shielded and made relevant. In this course \u2013 of thirteen weeks, and twenty sessions \u2013 we shall aim to study in depth six broad but critical political phenomenon that have not just shaped contemporary psycho-social dynamics, but have also remained central to the sense of the political at the level of the personal and the public. These themes are: (i) colonialism and racism, (ii) narcissism and political leadership, (iii) sexuality and psychopathology, (iv) violence: individual and communal, (v) hysteria, trauma and guilt, (vi) visuality and psychoanalysis. </span></span></span></span></span></p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>.</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"margin-bottom:7.5pt; margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Open Sans&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#333333\">Lectures: Students are expected to attend all lectures and to have completed the reading assigned for that day before class. Students are expected to be able to participate in colloquies conducted by the professor.</span></span></span></span></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom:7.5pt; margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Open Sans&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#333333\">\u2022 Readings: All the mandatory readings would be made available to the students electronically at least a week before the lectures on the said topic. Note: you encouraged to read the text entirely but the essential pages will be marked in the syllabus.</span></span></span></span></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom:7.5pt; margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Open Sans&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#333333\">\u2022 Speak up: If you don\u2019t understand something, please just ASK. The TA will announce their office hours; mine are posted above. Please do take advantage of them. I am also willing to meet with groups of students during office hours for tutorial seminars, and to make appointments to meet with students who cannot make it to my posted office hours (within reason).</span></span></span></span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Open Sans&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#333333\">\u2022 Cheating: Cheating includes any form of plagiarism, including from any web resources, or collaborating with and/or copying from other students in your graded work. Copying a fellow student\u2019s lecture notes if you miss a class due to illness is accepted; copying lecture notes because you didn\u2019t feel like coming to class is lame. The grade for plagiarism is a straight F. </span></span></span></span></span></p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"margin-bottom:7.5pt; margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Open Sans&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#333333\">Final grade consists of three components: a mid term essay + final take home essay + class participation. The details of each are as follows:</span></span></span></span></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom:7.5pt; margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Open Sans&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#333333\">\u2022 Mid term essay: This short essay will be written on a question framed by students themselves, drawn from the assigned readings. I usually prefer this write up to be the roadmap of the final essay. The length of the essays is 2000 words. There will be penalties for late submission and extensions will be granted only in documented cases of illness or family emergency. The essay is worth 25% of final grade.</span></span></span></span></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom:7.5pt; margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Open Sans&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#333333\">\u2022 Final examination: The final examination will also be a take home essay, also on questions framed by students. The length of the essay is 4000 words. There will be penalties for late submission and extensions will be granted only in documented cases of illness or family emergency. The essay is worth 50% of final grade.</span></span></span></span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Open Sans&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#333333\">\u2022 Class participation: Apart from the two essays, students will be graded on their class participation, which includes their attendance (15%) and participation through the semesterboth in lectures and discussion sections (10%). The grade on class participation is thus worth 25% of final grade. Students are not allowed more than 5 absences through the term (which includes absences due to participation in university events, and common illnesses. For any long term medical assistance and absence (more than three absences in a row), please do submit medical certificates to the OAA. </span></span></span></span></span></p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Open Sans&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#333333\">Students are not allowed more than 5 absences through the term (which includes absences due to participation in university events, and common illnesses. For any long term medical assistance and absence (more than three absences in a row), please do submit medical certificates to the OAA. </span></span></span></span></span></p></div></div>",
