            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This course is intended as an application of game theory. The choice of topics may vary with instructor and year. For Spring 2021, I will focus on applications of game theory towards understanding problems of economic development. Game theory is the study of strategic decision making by individual agents. One of the most important insights of game theory is that self interested behaviour by economic agents can lead to suboptimal social outcomes. Problems of economic development may themselves be viewed as situations where the society is trapped in inferior outcomes despite individuals striving for better outcomes. Economic development is, therefore, a very fruitful field for application of game theory. This is what this course will focus on. Some of the topics we will study are development traps, environmental problems, land tenure arrangements in agriculture, problems of savings and credit in developing societies, social learning, institutions and property rights, conflict and violence and problems of establishing trust in society. In every topic, the focus will on how game theoretic modeling can help us understand these problems better and allow us to look for solutions. </p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>1. Understand how simple games can be a very powerful tool to model problems of economic development.</p><p>2. Applying game theory to various problems of economic development like coordination problems, environmental degradation, economic and social institutions, financial contracts, social learning, social trust etc.</p><p>3. Understanding how such problems in economic development result for being trapped into inferior social outcomes even as individuals strive for their self-interest.</p><p>4. Developing an appreciation of how game theory can help us understand and solve wider social problems.</p><p>5. Developing a familiarity with the literature on game theory and economic development.</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>1. The main textbook is \"Games in Economic Development\" by Bruce Wydick.</p><p>2. In addition, the students should have with them a standard undergraduate game theory textbook like \"Strategy\" by Joel Watson to serve as a refresher for important game theoretic concepts.</p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>There will be three in-class exams. Each exam will count for one-third of the total grade.</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>No attendance requirement. But attendance is higly recommended in order to keep up with the class.</p></div></div>",
