            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"text-align:justify; margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size:14px;\"><span lang=\"EN-US\">Matters are all around us and we get frequent encounter with them. Some very common questions come to mind, i.e. why they behave in certain specific manner? A simple example, not everything shines but metal does. What makes glass transparent etc. </span></span></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify; margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size:14px;\"><span lang=\"EN-US\">\u201cPhysics of matter\u201d describes this world around us.  And this knowledge is used to engineer new materials and exploit their properties to change our word, semiconductor technology (whole electronic industry), is one such example of it. This course will also be the laboratory for the fundamental course of Physics you studied in last two year.</span></span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt\"> </p><p style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt\"><span style=\"font-size:16px;\"><span style=\"font-family:Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif;\">Contents:</span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size:14px;\">Free electron theory of metals, specific heat of solid.  Lattice vibrations, phonons.  Crystal structure, reciprocal lattice.  Electrical properties of matarial, <span lang=\"EN-US\">Magnetic and Dielectric Properties of Matter, Superconductivity,</span></span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size:14px;\"><span lang=\"EN-US\">Soft Matters</span></span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt\"> </p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt\">Reference books:</p><p style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Cambria\"><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt\"><span style=\"background:white\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Open Sans&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;\"><span style=\"color:#333333\">C. Kittel, Introduction to Solid State Physics</span></span></span></span><br><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Open Sans&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;\"><span style=\"color:#333333\"><span style=\"background:white\">N W Ashcroft and N D Mermin, Solid State Physics</span></span></span></span></span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Cambria\"><span style=\"font-size:10.0pt\"><span style=\"background:white\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Open Sans&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;\"><span style=\"color:#333333\">M Doi, Soft Matter Physics</span></span></span></span></span></span><br> </p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Cambria\"><span style=\"font-size:9.0pt\" lang=\"EN-US\"><span style=\"font-family:Arial\"><span style=\"font-size:14px;\"><span style=\"font-family:Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif;\">Assessment of performance will be based on quizzes(20%), assignments(20%), mid-sem exam (20%),end-sem exam(40%).</span></span></span></span></span></span></p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Cambria\"><span style=\"font-size:9.0pt\"><span style=\"background:white\"><span style=\"font-family:Arial\"><span style=\"color:#333333\">Attendance is mandatory. </span></span></span></span></span></span></p></div></div>",
