            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This course is a follow-up on <i>Quantum Mechanics I</i>, and thus knowledge of the basic ideas of quantum mechanics will be assumed. The topics expected to be covered are: (i) identical particles, (ii) angular momentum, (iii) approximation methods, including the variational method, the WKB method, and time-independent and time-dependent perturbation theory, and (iv) scattering theory. If time permits, an introduction to relativistic quantum mechanics will be provided. Students will be expected to be comfortable with partial differential equations and linear algebra; knowledge of computational methods at the level of <i>Computational Physics</i> would help but is not mandatory. </p></div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Will be informed in class.</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Will be informed in class.</p></div></div>",
