            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"margin:0in\"><span style=\"font-family:Georgia,serif;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Are there any standards or norms of justice that apply worldwide? If so, what are they? These are the central questions concerning global justice. In both political philosophy and ordinary discourse, it has often been taken for granted that on the global level a just system is a collection of independent states that respect international borders and do not attack each other without provocation. Yet, there are serious challenges to this view. </span></span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0in\"> </p><p style=\"margin:0in\"><span style=\"font-family:Georgia,serif;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">One set of challenges arises from common intuitions about justice and human rights. Is it just for some states to uphold equal rights for all while others treat minority groups as second-class citizens? Is it acceptable for some states to suppress rights and freedoms considered by many to be basic entitlements for all human beings? If we are tempted to answer \u201cno\u201d to these questions, then we must hold that political communities should not be wholly independent. </span></span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0in\"> </p><p style=\"margin:0in\"><span style=\"font-family:Georgia,serif;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Another set of challenges arises from the difficulty of resolving challenges facing the entire globe. How can climate change be slowed and how can its effects be managed? How should resources used by many different states (e.g. seas and oceans) be regulated? Should there be regulations on how communities trade with one another and on what they can trade (for example, should they be able to trade in endangered animals or nuclear weapons)? </span></span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0in\"> </p><p style=\"margin:0in\"><span style=\"font-family:Georgia,serif;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Some philosophers have concluded that we should resolve these challenges through voluntary international agreements, others have argued that independent states should be dissolved completely, and others have argued for a diverse range of positions between these two extremes. In this course, we will examine approaches to global justice and consider how they address some of the specific global challenges facing us.</span></span></span></p></div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><span style=\"font-family:Georgia,serif;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">tba</span></span></span></p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><span style=\"font-family:Georgia,serif;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">tba</span></span></span></p></div></div>",
