            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>The course shall develop and rehearse the habits that are essential to the development of a critical mind: reading, writing, speaking, listening and - obviously  - thinking. Over the semester, the course shall endeavour to demonstrate that while these are habits that are distinct and can be developed independently, they need to work in concert for thought to be meaningful in a scholarly setting.</p><p>For that purpose, the course shall employ a variety of source materials from Literature, Sociology/Anthropology and the History of Law to understand and generate concepts. The source material shall serve as occasion to learn how to ask questions that extend and enrich one's understanding -- of situations, texts, institutions and people. Students will explore the distinctness of academic research and writing, and participate in an active knowledge-community constituted by one's peers. By the end of the semester, a student will have a clearer understanding of what it means to be a scholar in an academic setting, and a keener sense of their own processes of learning, thinking and writing. </p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><div style=\"text-align:start; -webkit-text-stroke-width:0px\"><span style=\"font-size:12.8px\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-style: normal;\"><span style=\"font-variant-ligatures: normal;\"><span style=\"font-variant-caps: normal;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"letter-spacing: normal;\"><span style=\"orphans: 2;\"><span style=\"text-transform: none;\"><span style=\"white-space: normal;\"><span style=\"widows: 2;\"><span style=\"word-spacing: 0px;\"><span style=\"text-decoration-thickness: initial;\"><span style=\"text-decoration-style: initial;\"><span style=\"text-decoration-color: initial;\"><font style=\"color: rgb(34, 34, 34); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);\" color=\"#000000\"><font face=\"arial, sans-serif\">Students can expect to do regular reading (of academic texts and wider materials) over the semester. The reading list will be </font></font><span style=\"font-family: arial, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(34, 34, 34); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);\">communicated to you directly in the first few weeks of the semester, and will be included in a tentatice course </span><font color=\"#222222\"><span style=\"background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);\">outline as well. Additionally, students shall be expected to write consistently, participate in giving and taking feedback, and work on medium-term projects both individually and in collaboration with their classmates.</span></font></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></div><div style=\"text-align:start; -webkit-text-stroke-width:0px\"><br> </div> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>The ICT will be graded on a broad rubric, listed below. The weightage of the elements, their exact definition, and the decision to add new elements, will be at the discretion of the ICT instructor, using student input from the particular ICT section. </p><p>1. Participation (in classes, meetings and peer work)<br>2. Research paper (a longform argumentative paper with citations, written in academic style)<br>3. Ability to understand and implement instructions<br>3. Small summative assignments (including homework, and shorter assignments such as outlines and drafts) <br>4. Improvement over the Semester.</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>For this ICT, you are allowed <strong>three unexcused absences</strong> (for which you <strong>do not need permission</strong> from the instructor) and <strong>two excused absences</strong> (for which you <strong>do need permission</strong> from the instructor).</p><p>The penalty for any absence beyond these five will be decided by the instructor on a case-by-case basis. Please note that a consistent pattern of non-attendance may include penalties such as grade cuts, at the ICT instructor's discretion</p></div></div>",
