            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><span style=\"font-family:Georgia,serif;\">Taught by Anshika Varma</span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 8pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Georgia,serif;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"line-height:107%\">Story Telling lies at the core of human communication, it has held our histories of being and often helped create fantastical worlds we learn to give birth to. The power of images to cross barriers of language, geography, and culture is greater today than ever before. And in an era of profound change in the way images are made and interpreted, this course on photography looks at the evolution and place of The Photo Story today. Regular assignments will be given to help students move out of their comfort zones, engage with new perspectives and self realizations by reaching for higher levels of creative awareness. Over a period of 13 sessions, The Photo Story looks to delve in to a student centered curriculum with emphasis on learning through observation and practical hands-on experience in Photography and Story Telling. Students of the program explore the history of photography and it\u2019s development as a unique voice in the region, the role of photography in story-telling and the relationship between photography and its evidentiary power, the current emerging contemporary practices of the medium and its growing engagement as a language. The program looks to emphasize on a supportive learning atmosphere with regular photography projects, discussions and critique sessions. All modules mentioned will have a theory as well as a practical engagement to support the development of technical skills for those interested to pursue this field further.</span></span></span></p></div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 8pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Georgia,serif;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"line-height:107%\">The majority of the course work will take place in class. Hence, attendance and participation in class are the main criteria for grading. </span></span></span></p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><span style=\"font-family:Georgia,serif;\">Students can take up to 2 unexcused absences.</span></p></div></div>",
