            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Psychotherapy: Theoretical Foundations and Research.</p><p>Course Description<br>This course is an introduction to the prominent theoretical approaches to psychotherapy (e.g, analytic, psychodynamic, behavioural, cognitive, humanistic) and their clinical application in addressing mental health, relational and existential concerns. In surveying the major psychotherapy systems, this course will place special emphasis on research and address general issues and controversies related evidenced-based practice. We will explore ethical and multicultural considerations related to the study, theory, and practice of psychotherapy. Example case studies and videos will be used to illustrate the principles of therapeutic change.</p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>1.Introduce the history and evolution of psychotherapy<br>2.Explore the ethical issues associated with psychotherapy practice and research<br>3.Understand the principles of psychotherapeutic change and the role of thetherapeutic relationship<br>4.Critically evaluate psychotherapy research, as well as current controversiessurrounding the integration of science and practice.<br>5.Reflect on the role of cultural diversity, privilege and oppression, andmulticultural issues with respect to the practice and study of psychotherapy<br>6.Explore contemporary approaches to psychotherapy and the integration of theoriesinto practice</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 10pt;\">All lectures and office hours will be online so a working internet connection with audio and video capability will be necessary.</p><p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 10pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:12px;\"><span style=\"line-height:115%\"><b><span lang=\"EN-US\"><span style=\"line-height:115%\">Required Readings:</span></span></b></span></span></p><p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 10pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:12px;\"><span style=\"line-height:normal\">Corey, G. (2017) Theory and Practice of Counseling and Psychotherapy, Cengage., 10th edition, Boston, MA: Cengage Learning.</span></span></p><p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 10pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:12px;\"><span style=\"line-height:115%\"><b><span lang=\"EN-US\"><span style=\"line-height:115%\">Recommended Readings:</span></span></b></span></span></p><p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 10pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:12px;\"><span style=\"line-height:115%\"><span lang=\"EN-US\"><span style=\"line-height:115%\">American Psychological Association (2019). Publication manual of the American Psychological Association (7<sup>th</sup> ed.). Washington, DC: APA. </span></span></span></span></p><p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 10pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:12px;\"><span style=\"line-height:115%\"><span lang=\"EN-US\"><span style=\"line-height:115%\">Capuzzi, D. &amp; Stauffer, M.D. (2016), Counseling and psychotherapy: Theories and Interventions (6th ed.) Alexandria, VA: American</span></span></span></span></p><p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 10pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:12px;\"><span style=\"line-height:normal\"><span style=\"background:white\"><span style=\"color:#222222\">Yalom, I.D. (2009), </span></span><span style=\"color:#222222\">The Gift of Therapy<span style=\"background:white\">: an Open Letter to a New Generation of </span>Therapists<span style=\"background:white\"> and Their Patients</span></span><span style=\"background:white\"><span style=\"color:#222222\">. 1st Harper Perennial ed. New York: Harper Perennial.</span></span></span></span></p><p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 10pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:12px;\"><span style=\"line-height:115%\"><span lang=\"EN-US\"><span style=\"line-height:115%\">**Please note that I may change/add readings to those mentioned in the syllabus. I will announce changes in readings (if any) during our class at least one week prior to when I expect you to read the articles**</span></span></span></span></p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Grading:<br>\u2022Attendance and Participation - 5% of final grade</p><p>\u2022Research Paper - 20 %</p><p>\u2022Exam 1- 25% of final grade</p><p>\u2022Reflection paper - 30 % of final grade</p><p>\u2022Final paper - 20% of final grade</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Ideally, I would like students to actively participate in class and have at least 80% attendance.<br>Research has shown that students who attend class regularly tend to receive better grades than students with sporadic attendance. This is likely to also be true in this class, as class participation will account for 5% of your final grade. The evaluation of class participation will rest primarily on (a) attendance, and (b) the synthesis of the readings and the presented material, as communicated during classroom discussion. Attendance therefore is strongly encouraged and students who cannot attend a class meeting(s) for any reason are responsible for the material covered those days.</p></div></div>",
