            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Familes shape us. They provide refuge from the world, but they also send us into the world somewhat secure, and somewhat damaged. From the Mahabharat to the present moment, the South Asian family has captured the imagination of writers and chroniclers, film makers and artists. What makes the institution of the family so complex, and its imagination so potent so as to inspire nations to also use this metaphor? This course will examine how the world of literature has dealt with the family and contained or interrogated questions of caste and gender, marriage and alienation. The course will have a range of literary texts - novels, short stories, poetry and cinema clips from different parts of the world. Some of the main texts include Gacher Gocher (by Vivek Shangbag); Persipolis (Marjani Satrapi), Fun Home (by Alison Bechdel), Cobalt Blue (Sachin Kundalkar) etc. Students are expected to read the texts and interact in class, that is the non negotiable requirement of the course. The rest will be made clearer once the syllabus is shared. Please contact the instructor for further details. </p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Please see the above </p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>The syllabus will be sent to you if you reach out to rita.kothari@ashoka.edu.in </p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Please see the above. </p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Three absences excused. </p></div></div>",
