            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"margin:0cm; -webkit-text-stroke-width:0px; text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:medium\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri, sans-serif\"><span style=\"caret-color:#000000\"><span style=\"color:#000000\"><span style=\"font-style:normal\"><span style=\"font-variant-caps:normal\"><span style=\"font-weight:normal\"><span style=\"letter-spacing:normal\"><span style=\"orphans:auto\"><span style=\"text-transform:none\"><span style=\"white-space:normal\"><span style=\"widows:auto\"><span style=\"word-spacing:0px\"><span style=\"-webkit-text-size-adjust:auto\"><span style=\"text-decoration:none\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Cambria, serif\">The purpose of this course is to examine critically various forms of political violence through a qualitative lens. We will engage with literatures drawn from various regions of the world and discuss various approaches adopted by social scientists to describe, analyse, understand and interpret violence, as a phenomenon inescapably enmeshed with both politics and society. We will start by examining the intimate relation between violence and state formation, and then explore various forms of political violence, including communal and caste violence, state repression and police brutality, vigilantism, organized crime and criminal political economies, warlord politics, massacres and genocide. </span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm; -webkit-text-stroke-width:0px; text-align:justify\"> </p><p style=\"margin:0cm; -webkit-text-stroke-width:0px; text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:medium\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri, sans-serif\"><span style=\"caret-color:#000000\"><span style=\"color:#000000\"><span style=\"font-style:normal\"><span style=\"font-variant-caps:normal\"><span style=\"font-weight:normal\"><span style=\"letter-spacing:normal\"><span style=\"orphans:auto\"><span style=\"text-transform:none\"><span style=\"white-space:normal\"><span style=\"widows:auto\"><span style=\"word-spacing:0px\"><span style=\"-webkit-text-size-adjust:auto\"><span style=\"text-decoration:none\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Cambria, serif\">The course will be reading intensive, with regular short written submissions. Most sessions will start with oral presentations on the basis of the readings of the day. There will be a final paper on a topic of students\u2019 choosing. </span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This course is an opportunity to both explore questions related to political violence but also to expand your knowledge of qualitative methods in political science and political anthropology. </p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>You are required to have taken Introduction to Qualitative Research Methods in Political Sciences to enrol for this course. </p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>to be defined</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>As long as we are offline, no more than three absences. Attendance is otherwise mandatory. </p></div></div>",
