            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 8pt\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"line-height:107%\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Century&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;\" lang=\"EN-US\">We are living in a time of amazing technological advances. Effects of these emerging technologies are everywhere. From the Google search that you do to the things, you buy on Amazon or Flipkart to the recommended shows that you watch on Netflix. Even in Grammarly's editorial suggestions as I type this description up!</span></span></span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 8pt\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"line-height:107%\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Century&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;\" lang=\"EN-US\">What will the impact of Artificial Intelligence (AI) or Machine Learning (ML) on our economy and society be? Technology giants like Amazon, today have hundreds of economists working for them. What is it that these economists do? These are some of the questions that this course will try to answer. </span></span></span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 8pt\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"line-height:107%\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Century&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;\" lang=\"EN-US\">We will begin the course by understanding what technology and innovation mean to an economist and why are they important. Then tools learned in earlier courses in macro and microeconomics will be used to develop an understanding of the economics of automation and emerging technologies such as AI. In doing so we will also focus on aspects of the data and digital economy including privacy. This understanding will then be used to study the effect of such technologies on a range of topics such as employment and the future of jobs, economic growth, organisation of businesses, etc. </span></span></span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 8pt\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"line-height:107%\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Century&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;\" lang=\"EN-US\">The students should have completed courses in microeconomics, game theory, and growth theory. Knowledge of differential calculus and the basics of integration will also be required. Some knowledge of regression analysis will be useful.</span></span></span></span></p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 8pt\"><font face=\"Century, serif\"><span style=\"font-size: 14.6667px;\"><i>There is no textbook for this course. I will circulate the slides that I use to teach after each lecture. There will also be readings taken from both academic papers and popular articles that I will share from time to time.</i></span></font></p><p style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 8pt\"> </p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><span style=\"font-size:11.0pt\" lang=\"EN-US\"><span style=\"line-height:107%\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Century&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;\">20% assignments, 25% mid-term exam, 40% for a term paper, and 15% for class participation.</span></span></span></p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><span style=\"font-size:11.0pt\" lang=\"EN-US\"><span style=\"line-height:107%\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Century&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;\">The course has a 15% class participation component out of which 8% will be awarded on the basis of attendance in class. Grades for attendance will not be linear. You will lose 0.5% of the grade for every class you miss for the first five classes. Absence beyond that will mean you lose the entire grade for attendance. As is clear I would prefer you not miss classes! I like a lively discussion in class and for that we need you there.</span></span></span></p></div></div>",
