            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>A novelist may begin to feel that realist fiction, or even fiction itself, is no longer an adequate<br>means to represent reality. A critic might feel one day that the footnoted academic essay closes<br>down certain ways of thinking. One might begin to wonder, confronted with certain works, if<br>criticism is an imaginative act and poetry a form of critical thinking. It's this alternative tradition<br>that this course will aim to explore.</p></div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Grades will be given on the basis of two short essays to be written by each student over the term, plus class contributions. Essays should be shared with the tutor and other students at least four days prior to each class.</p><p>The essays would be a mix of critical and creative writing - that is, they would ideally be essayistic, intellectually exploratory, and non-academic.</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>TBA</p></div></div>",
