            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p> </p><p><meta charset=\"utf-8\"></p><p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-e19abf64-7fff-8c79-74bd-b24aa0726613\">The study of large or infinite classes of objects interacting with each other, there is a need to impose various structures to understand their properties better. The common notions of objects being nearby or close to each other need to be mathematically formulated in order to get at a more quantitative as well as qualitative understanding of such large classes. The subject of mathematical analysis grew out of the study of considerations such as convergence, continuity, rate of change, etc. </b></p><p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-e19abf64-7fff-8c79-74bd-b24aa0726613\">Our course will give an introduction to the basic concepts and tools of mathematical analysis. The notion of distance gets axiomatized by that of a metric space. To get the sense of continuity and plug holes needs the concept of completion, and so on. </b></p><p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-e19abf64-7fff-8c79-74bd-b24aa0726613\">We will try to illustrate these concepts by examples and the applications will point out the usefulness of these concepts. Thus the course will be based on examples and applications of the theory that will be developed during the course. </b></p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p> </p><p><meta charset=\"utf-8\"></p><p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-bcb12f61-7fff-32a9-3051-1f4fc98cb9e5\">The various concepts and methods of mathematical analysis and their applications: convergence, metric spaces, completion, compactness, topological spaces, and continuity, connectedness, etc. </b></p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><meta charset=\"utf-8\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-5fb5fdf9-7fff-88f1-9cd9-1deca4428170\">W. Rudin, Principles of Mathematical analysis. </b></p><p><b>James R. Munkres: Topology, a first course</b></p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><meta charset=\"utf-8\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-4351e62e-7fff-02c7-239a-9e3fd8ba9b68\">Will be announced in class</b></p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><meta charset=\"utf-8\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-4351e62e-7fff-02c7-239a-9e3fd8ba9b68\">Will be announced in class</b></p></div></div>",
