            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><span style=\"font-family:Georgia,serif;\">Taught by Peggy Mohan</span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 8pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Georgia,serif;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"line-height:107%\">This is a course about migrations into the Indian subcontinent, and how they gave shape to new languages, primarily across the north and down the western coast, and what this tells us about a people\u2019s history of this region. </span></span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 8pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Georgia,serif;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"line-height:107%\">What we will focus on is how the languages spoken all across the north of the subcontinent emerged. We start millennia ago with Sanskrit and the different Prakrits, searching out the backstories of the modern North Indian languages spoken today. This will give a picture of how early Indians met and mixed with mostly male explorers who came and settled in this land, a fusion that is still visible in the sounds, grammars and words of the languages they made. We will see how, often, the languages of the \u2018little people\u2019 shaped the grammars of the modern languages, while the migrating men contributed the superficial layer of vocabulary. We will see why the languages of the northwest, as far east as Hindi and down to Konkani, constitute a single sub-family, while the languages of the east, from the dialects of eastern Uttar Pradesh to Bengal, Odisha, Assam form a different sub-family which is still expanding, and how that goes back to the two regions having different linguistic substrata on account of the differences in the early local people and the early migrants who settled there.</span></span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 8pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Georgia,serif;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"line-height:107%\">We will examine different models of how languages mix, going on to look at different situations in the subcontinent where, over the ages, local elites and \u2018little people\u2019 came to terms in different ways with new power structures which called for adjustments, creating Prakrits as well as more radically mixed varieties. This will mean stretching our minds back to imagine how things might have been before the early empires appeared, spreading Prakrits across the north of this land. We will also see how that gave way to the connected web of languages we have today, with the influence of those early Prakrits continuing to spread into India like slowly cooling lava. We will then go on to think about English, the newest player in Indian language power structure. And we will end our journey by looking at the other end of the life cycle: Indian languages that are threatened as their speaker communities move on.</span></span></span></p></div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 8pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Georgia,serif;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"line-height:107%\">The majority of the course work will take place in class. Hence, attendance and participation in class are the main criteria for grading. </span></span></span></p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><span style=\"font-family:Georgia,serif;\">Students can take up to 2 unexcused absences.</span></p></div></div>",
