            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><span style=\"font-family:Georgia,serif;\">Taught by Amrith Lal</span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 8pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Georgia,serif;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"line-height:107%\">This course will focus on the history and evolution, sounds and images of Malayalam poetry. It is designed in a way that a person who is new to Malayalam can appreciate poetry in this language. With this aim, I have decided to focus on one particular characteristic of Malayalam poetry, which is its oral heritage and inheritance. Most of Malayalam poetry of the past was written to be memorised and sung/chanted/recited, like in most Indian languages. However, this tradition continues to dominate in Malayalam to this day. And, it is also a poetic tradition, where genres have emerged with distinct links to performance. This ranges from poetic forms written for the stage such as Kathakali and Ottan Thullal, to be sung by oarsmen (Vanchi Pattu), and in the modern age, for public recitals (Chol Kazhcha). </span></span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 8pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Georgia,serif;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"line-height:107%\">The course will introduce students to poets, poems, movements, who/that have an organic link to this musical and performance inheritance, over 12 lectures. Poems taken up for discussion are those available in English translation. I will also use audio recordings, documentaries and may even have a couple of poets recite their work for students on Zoom. The intent of the course is to enable a person to appreciate Malayalam poetry, particularly through its rhymes and rhythms, rather than impose a theoretical take on its history and aesthetics. </span></span></span></p></div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 8pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Georgia,serif;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"line-height:107%\">The majority of the course work will take place in class. Hence, attendance and participation in class are the main criteria for grading. </span></span></span></p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><span style=\"font-family:Georgia,serif;\">Students can take up to 2 unexcused absences.</span></p></div></div>",
