            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><span style=\"font-family:Georgia,serif;\">Taught by Punita Singh</span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm; text-align:start; -webkit-text-stroke-width:0px\"><span style=\"font-family:Georgia,serif;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"color:#222222\"><span style=\"font-style:normal\"><span style=\"font-variant-ligatures:normal\"><span style=\"font-variant-caps:normal\"><span style=\"font-weight:400\"><span style=\"letter-spacing:normal\"><span style=\"orphans:2\"><span style=\"text-transform:none\"><span style=\"white-space:normal\"><span style=\"widows:2\"><span style=\"word-spacing:0px\"><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"text-decoration-thickness:initial\"><span style=\"text-decoration-style:initial\"><span style=\"text-decoration-color:initial\">Bridging the Medieval and Baroque periods, the Renaissance brought in seminal innovations in the canon of western vocal music.  From one voice to many, from simple homophony to complex polyphony, from unaccompanied <i>a capella</i> singing to the gradual use of instruments, from liturgical texts to vernacular lyrics<span style=\"font-size:12pt\" lang=\"EN-US\">\u2014</span>varied singing styles flourished in the 15<sup>th</sup> and 16<sup>th</sup> centuries. A major song form that evolved in parallel with the sacred motet was the secular madrigal. In this course we will explore the context in which some of these song forms developed and sing them in diverse languages. Familiarity with western music notation would be helpful but is not essential.</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm; text-align:start; -webkit-text-stroke-width:0px\"><span style=\"font-family:Georgia,serif;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"color:#222222\"><span style=\"font-style:normal\"><span style=\"font-variant-ligatures:normal\"><span style=\"font-variant-caps:normal\"><span style=\"font-weight:400\"><span style=\"letter-spacing:normal\"><span style=\"orphans:2\"><span style=\"text-transform:none\"><span style=\"white-space:normal\"><span style=\"widows:2\"><span style=\"word-spacing:0px\"><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"text-decoration-thickness:initial\"><span style=\"text-decoration-style:initial\"><span style=\"text-decoration-color:initial\"> </span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p></div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 8pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Georgia,serif;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"line-height:107%\">The majority of the course work will take place in class. Hence, attendance and participation in class are the main criteria for grading. </span></span></span></p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><span style=\"font-family:Georgia,serif;\">Students can take up to 2 unexcused absences.</span></p></div></div>",
