            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>In the last three centuries, nationalism has proved a powerful ideology that has reshaped the political map of the world. As the nation-state became the norm, nationalism inspired both state-led nation-building and bottom-up mobilizations. Yet nationalism has also sparked xenophobic sentiments that lead to discriminatory attitudes and sometimes ethnic or inter-state conflict. This course seeks to make sense of nationalism as a positive source of political creativity and as a dangerous source of tension. Students will be introduced to the major theories of nationalism and will be invited to analyse and discuss multiple case studies of nationalist movements and policies.</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Course prerequisites: Introduction to Comparative Politics or Introduction to Indian Politics.</p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Details about grading will be given at a later stage.</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Attendance is mandatory.</p></div></div>",
