            "document":"",
            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This course is about how people organize collectively to challenge established norms and institutions. Social movements seek to transform political, social, economic, and cultural systems. They vary widely in terms of their composition, objectives, and strategies. This elective course will introduce students to the major theories of political sociology that seek to explain why and how people mobilize in order to contest power. The course will also cover a wide range of empirical cases of social movements, both historical and contemporary.</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Course prerequisites: Introduction to Comparative Politics or Introduction to Indian Politics.</p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Attendance and participation: 20%.</p><p>Response paper: 20%.</p><p>Final assignment preparation: 10%.</p><p>Presentation: 10%.</p><p>Final written assignment: 40%.</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Students are expected to attend every class and participate in the class discussion. Any absence must be justified.</p></div></div>",
