            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This course will be suitable for 3rd and 4th year Mathematics students. The first half of the course will focus on the theory of Elliptic curves from a Number Theoretic perspective. The second half of the course will focus on algebraic aspects of Cryptography with focus on Elliptic Curve Cryptography (ECC).</p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><u><strong>Syllabus:-</strong></u><strong>  </strong>Basic theory of Elliptic curves: Weierstrass equation, doubly periodic func- tions, group law, torsion points, Elliptic curves over finite fields, Congruent Number Problem and its connection to Elliptic curves.<br>Cryptography: Simple cryptosystems, Public Key Cryptography, RSA cryp- tosystem, Discrete Logarithm, Diffie\u2013Hellman key exchange, Elliptic Curve Cryptography.</p><p> </p><p><u><strong>Pre-requisites:-</strong></u> Algebra 1, Algebra 2 &amp; Complex Analysis.</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Textbooks.</p><p>1. Lawrence C. Washington, Elliptic Curves : Number Theory and Cryptography (Second Edition), Chapman &amp; Hall/CRC 2008.</p><p>2. Neal Koblitz, Introduction to Elliptic Curves and Modular Forms (Third Edition), GTM Vol. 97, Springer-Verlag 199</p><p>3. Neal Koblitz, A Course in Number Theory and Cryptography (Sec- ond Edition), GTM Vol. 114, Springer-Verlag 1994.</p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>1. Assignments - 40%</p><p>2. Mid-Term Exam - 30%</p><p>3. Final Exam - 30%</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Attendance is not mandatory but highly recommended.</p></div></div>",
