            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><span style=\"font-family:Georgia,serif;\">Taught by <span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"line-height:107%\">Neel Chaudhuri, Anirudh Nair</span></span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 8pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Georgia,serif;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"line-height:107%\">This course explores a contemporary approach to actor training and the embodying and staging of text. The first part of the course focuses on body, mind, breath and voice as a single integrated whole and suggests a practice that prepares the actor\u2019s instrument for the state of performance. Students will work towards removing blocks that we develop as a result of socialisation, in order to find freedom in the flow of impulse and actions in response to stimulus. In the second part, we apply and realise this practice in devising and staging scenes from selected contemporary texts. The teaching methodology includes theatre games and exercises, partner and ensemble work, including simple acrobatics, improvisations, movement structures and basic textual analysis to unpack scripts for performance. </span></span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 8pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Georgia,serif;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"line-height:107%\"> <br>The Listening Body draws on principles and approaches that are grounded in the work and lineage of artists and teachers, beginning with Konstantin Stanislavski and navigating through various global practices through the 20th century. It proposes a living and breathing practice that develops, challenges and reimagines these traditions in response to the culture and experience of practitioners in India today. The course encourages students to consider their own context and desire as performers and build from there. </span></span></span></p></div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 8pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Georgia,serif;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"line-height:107%\">The majority of the course work will take place in class. Hence, attendance and participation in class are the main criteria for grading. </span></span></span></p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><span style=\"font-family:Georgia,serif;\">Students can take up to 4 unexcused absences.</span></p></div></div>",
