            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 8pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Georgia,serif;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"line-height:107%\">Taught by Navtej Singh Johar</span></span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 8pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Georgia,serif;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"line-height:107%\">This course will be equally devoted to theory and somatic practice. Revolving around the phenomenon of <i>ambivalence,</i> both the readings and practice will aim to look between-and-betwixt the possibilities and impossibilities of being and/or becoming insider/outsider, native/stranger, self/other.  An examination of ideas pertaining to boundaries, permissions, desires, negotiations and transgressions, will be countered with an analysis and exploration of bodily appetites of touch, taste, gaze, voice, sound, shape, gesture and so on. In particular, the liminal condition of <i>ambivalence</i> will be studied in relation to the <i>arbitrariness</i> of categories and divisions that modernity imposes, and the <i>absurd certitude</i> of nationalism that it can foster. The underlying thrust of this course will be to explore the sensory body being as being the source and the means of <i>clarity.</i>  </span></span></span></p></div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 8pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Georgia,serif;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"line-height:107%\">The majority of the course work will take place in class. Hence, attendance and participation in class are the main criteria for grading. </span></span></span></p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><span style=\"font-family:Georgia,serif;\">Students can take up to 4 unexcused absences.</span></p></div></div>",
