            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Note: While our effort will be hold face to face classes, the course may have to be partially online. Depending on the evolving situation we shall take a call closer to the start of the semester.<br>This is an undergraduate course to introduce students to three significant strands of scholarship in the Anthropology of Women and Work. Starting with the late 70s, an evolving gender studies focus offered pathbreaking approaches to women\u2019s roles in production. The first strand will explore how women\u2019s productive activities complement those of men in the simplest societies. We shall examine some issues raised in gender-based enquiries within the vast anthropological literature that emerged to understand women\u2019s labor and production in simple or pre-class societies.<br>,<br>A second strand concerns the Indian agricultural context. Here we analyze notions about the peasant household, as well as women\u2019s contribution to agrarian production. The course will examine the implications of imagining the cultivator as predominantly male, which led to the invisibility of women\u2019s contributions to agriculture. The effects of this bias will be explored along with reflections on the research that emerged to address it.</p><p>A specific focus of the section on India will be to explore the links between agrarian production and cultural production.</p><p>The course concludes with issues raised in recent documentaries about women\u2019s labor in the global fashion industry.</p><p>Reading selections are made with a view to generating active class discussion and introduce students to ongoing debates in the field. For example, through selected pages from Chakrabarty\u2019s\u2018Provincializing Europe\u2019, the class will be first introduced to significant issues and themes in the exploration of the Anthropology of Women and Work. The book\u2019s broad historical sweep offers a stimulating entry point to ask questions about labor, peasantry, distinctions between public and private; social institutions from which women were excluded; women\u2019s repetitive tasks such as grinding and associated narratives, and the concerns of social reformers \u2013 themes to emerge as the weeks unfold. If in the Introductory week our effort is to think of women\u2019s work not as an abstraction but deeply rooted in concrete realities, the second week asks how the recent pandemic has forced us to think of other compelling issues about labor - migration and women\u2019s visibility or invisibility in these processes. Questions raised by Chakrabarty\u2019s and Agnihotri\u2019s texts anticipate themes we shall explore over the remaining weeks.</p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>TBD</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>.</p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>TBD</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>TBD</p></div></div>",
