            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>In this course, we will both study the fool and play the fool. </p><p>These pandemic years have been difficult indeed. As we continue to grapple with the pandemic, in this class we will shift our focus to humour, through a deep exploration of what it is, why we have it, and how we do it.</p><p>What is funny and why? What work does humour do in human societies? Do other-than-human species make jokes? What is the relationship between comedy and power? These are some of the questions we will explore, through focusing in particular on the burgeoning and shifting scene of humour in the societies we live in. We will analyze and think with WhatsApp forwards and memes, stand-up comics and reels, and the jokes that we make, hear, and critique around us everyday. Our readings will include Beatrice Otto's Fools are Everywhere: The Court Jester Around the World; Sigmund Freud's Jokes and their Relation to the Unconscious; and Humour and the Performance of Power in South Asia, edited by Sasanka Perera and Dev Nath Pathak, among others. </p><p> </p></div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>To be discussed in class when the syllabus is handed out. </p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>7 Free absences. Anything beyond results in a .5 decrease of the final letter grade per absence. The only exception to this rule is a documented emergency. </p></div></div>",
