            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Note: While our effort will be hold face to face classes, the course may have to be partially online. Depending on the evolving situation we shall take a call closer to the start of the semester.</p><p>This course will introduce students to influential thinkers who have grappled with the inter-relationship between caste and gender. Each unit will offer a new way to understand this intertwining. Beginning with texts influential in bringing together understandings about caste and gender, the course is divided into 6 units: Approaches to Gender and Caste; Upper Caste Patriarchies and Cultural Models; Marriage Transactions; Dalit Identity; Gender Violence; Agrarian Production and Cultural Production.</p><p>B.R. Ambedkar\u2019s essay on caste endogamy sets the tone, followed by a 1990 foundational text on gender by Partha Chatterjee, and Anupama Rao\u2019s Introduction to an edited volume on Caste and Gender. From an analysis of upper caste models and patriarchies that inaugurated studies on the intertwining of gender and caste, the course takes up the concerns of recent scholarship on Dalits. A unique feature of the course is its attempt to integrate people\u2019s voices, songs and biographies, as forms of cultural production. Five of the six units in the course offer at least one such example for deeper engagement with people\u2019s own texts/narratives. While these come to us as reflective pieces analyzed by commentators, students may collectively explore other possible meanings. The aim is for the classroom to emerge as a space to elicit meanings from material with which anthropologists construct texts. Over the semester, students learn about caste and gender as empirically grounded phenomena, as well as analytical tools that illuminate our reality.</p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>TBD</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>.</p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>.</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>.</p></div></div>",
