            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Torture and Anthropology</span></p><p> </p><p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">If we are to make the study of torture meaningful, we must at the outset recognize that the complexity and diversity of this term is best grasped in its historical and ethnographic specificity. While the reading of torture is classified in multiple discursive regimes \u2013 judicial and punitive accounts, interrogational manuals, biographical and autobiographical details, online videos of lynching, to name a few \u2013 this course aims to situate torture in its relation to the social. In the process, we will read about how torture establishes bonds of solidarity as much as it breaks forms of sociality. Beginning with how torture, pain, and suffering (or what Max Weber calls the problem of theodicy) are linked, we will move to a discussion of torture as a ritual of initiation, where the mark of violence on the body is a pedagogy of affirmation and non-dialogue. Subsequently, the course will examine case studies of torturers and the problem of witnessing and remembrance. We will then locate the practice of torture within institutional contexts, such as the prison and rendition and concentration camps, showing the difficult relationship that torture establishes with state sovereignty. The course will close with reflections on the relation of torture to life and death.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Students will be evaluated by a mid-term (40%) and end-term (40%) paper. In addition, there will be weekly prompts (20%) of no more than a page to be written in class time.</span></p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>An understanding of how torture makes and unmakes the world</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>We will distribute the reading list before classes begin</p><p>For the initial classes the following readings are recommended</p><p>Pierre Clastres: Society Against the State</p><p>Elaine Scarry: The Body in Pain</p><p>Francois Bizot: Facing the Torturer</p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Discussed above</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>We will follow University rules for attendance</p></div></div>",
