            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This course will introduce a number of important concepts and foundational topics in the relativistic quantum theory of fields. The focus will be on the hamiltonian formulation of QFT,  spin 0 (scalar) and spin 1/2 (spinor) fields, and on simple tree-level processes for the most part. </p><p>Brief Course Outline</p><p>Quantum Mechanics + Special relativity, the need for many particles, antiparticles and quantum fields.</p><p>Fock Space, many particle QM, the quantum field as coupled harmonic oscillators.</p><p>Relativistic causality, cluster decomposition and locality, mode expansions.</p><p>Classical Field Theory: Lagrangians, Hamiltonians and equation of motion, Noether\u2019s theorem, Symmetries (spacetime and internal), conserved currents, energy-momentum tensor, Canonical Quantisation.</p><p>Perturbation theory and Scattering: Schrodinger, Heisenberg and Dirac pictures, Dyson formula and Lorentz invariant S - matrix, Wick contractions and normal ordering, simple tree level processes in the canonical operator formulation. </p><p>Green\u2019s functions, Propagators, LSZ and KL representation, Feynman rules.</p><p>QFT in curved spacetime - a primer.</p><p>Spinorial representations of the Lorentz Group. Weyl Spinors and Weyl equation. Dirac equation and plane wave solutions, quantisation of the Dirac field, anti-commutation relations, Majorana fermions. Propagator and Feynman diagrams and Feynman rules.</p><p>Basic Quantum Electrodynamics (Feynman rules and amplitudes for simple tree level processes).</p><p>* Spin-statistics and CPT theorem.</p><p>* UIRs of the Poincare group.</p><p>* Path Integrals in QM and QFT.</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>For a good part of the course we will (try to) follow the excellent recently published book:</p><p>\u201cQuantum Field Theory Lectures of Sidney Coleman\u201d (World Scientific)</p><p>This will be the primary reference. Lecture notes from the course are available also on arXiv: </p><p>https://arxiv.org/abs/1110.5013</p><p>The 1975 Harvard lectures of Sidney Coleman are available to watch here: </p><p>https://www.physics.harvard.edu/events/videos/Phys253</p><p> </p><p>One more important reference will be:</p><p>\u201cIntroduction to Quantum Field Theory\u201d  by M. Peskin and D. Schroder  [Chapters 1-4]</p><p> </p><p>Another classic is</p><p>\u201cThe Quantum Theory of Fields\u201d by Steven Weinberg [C.U.P , 3 volumes, Chapters 1-7 of Vol. 1 are especially recommended as they explain and develop systematically important conceptual aspects of QFT and motivate its structure]</p><p> </p><p>A very incomplete list of good introductory textbooks - with varying perspectives, different choice and order of topics, and distinct pedagogical styles - which may also be useful for particular topics, is the following:</p><p>\"Quantum Field Theory and the Standard Model\u201d (M. Schwartz)</p><p>\u201cQuantum Field Theory\u201d  (M. Srednicki)</p><p>\"Quantum Field Theory in a Nutshell\u201d (A. Zee)</p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p> </p><p>Credit: Exams (60%) + Viva (20%)+ Project (20%)</p><p>Audit: Exams (75%) + Viva (25%) (a 65% overall mark is required for a successful audit)</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Registered students are expected to attend all the lectures</p></div></div>",
