            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Modern Cosmology is a merely three-decade-old, relatively new subject. Nevertheless, this is a subject that is now soundly based on precision observations. Both theory and observation play a crucial role in understanding the nature of our Universe. This course is meant to be an introduction to modern cosmology as we know of today. The topics to be covered are: The Friedmann-Lemaitre-Robertson-Walker Universe, Thermodynamics of the early Universe, the physics of the first three minutes of the Universe, Cosmic Microwave Background, Cosmic Inflation, Cosmological perturbation theory and  the observational features of Cosmic Microwave Background, Additional topics (time permitting): Dark Energy and Dark Matter.</p><p><b>Prerequisite:</b> PHY 4810: Introduction to General Relativity with applications to Cosmology.</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p> 1. The Early Universe by Kolb and Turner</p><p> 2. Modern Cosmology by Dodelson</p><p> 3. Cosmology by Weinberg</p><p> 4. Lecture notes available on arXiv.</p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Assignments and Semester Project.</p><p>Details would be decided later</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Attending all the classes are compulsary </p></div></div>",
