            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"line-height:115%\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"color:#222222\">Is Shakespeare queer? Debate has raged for centuries about whether or not Shakespeare was gay, but that is pointedly not the question this class will ask. Instead, we will grapple with a double-headed monster that asks both: how does Shakespeare allow us to theorise queerness, and how does queer theory engage Shakespeare? We will read, among other texts, the Sonnets, as well as plays like <i>Romeo and Juliet</i>, <i>Richard II</i>, and <i>Othello</i>, queer theory texts by Lee Edelman, Valerie Traub, Jonathan Goldberg, Eve Kosofsky Sedgwick, and Judith Butler, and adaptations like <i>Omkara</i> and <i>Ram-Leela</i>. With every text we will think through the assumptions on which queer theory builds its arguments, and inquire into the extent to which Shakespeare might perhaps more fascinatingly be encountered as Shakesqueer.</span></span></span></span></p></div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>A-F</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>As per syllabus</p></div></div>",
