            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>While our position in space is an objective fact determined by geographic coordinates, our understanding of a place is fundamentally subjective. The same space can have radically different meanings depending on the observer. This course explores this tension through the theory and practice of Qualitative GIS: an area of cartography that tries to map our experience of place. Using visualizations, maps, and other digital media, we will experiment with different ways of capturing the \"placeness\" of space in fiction, history, and narrative texts more generally. Along the way you will become conversant with Geographic Information Systems, such as QGIS, and will also learn some of the basics of web mapping with MapBox. No prior knowledge of computer programming is required, but you are asked to keep an open mind about learning some basic HTML, CSS, and JavaScript, and maybe some Python. Due to the collaborative nature of the Digital Humanities, most projects will involve group work. </p><p><meta charset=\"utf-8\"></p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><em>Coverage:</em></p><p><meta charset=\"utf-8\"></p><p dir=\"ltr\">Students will learn how to interpret narrative data and map it spatially. As the definitions for doing this type of work are still being created, there are no options for cookie cutter methods, instead students will need to think critically about how best to represent the data.</p><p><em>Basic Computer Logic:</em></p><p dir=\"ltr\">Although DH relies on technologists who do the more sophisticated coding, it is necessary for practitioners to have a basic understanding of computer logic and programming. We will cover entry-level computer programming for GIS using Python and JavaScript for MapBox.</p><p><em>Professionalization:</em></p><p dir=\"ltr\">You will be asked to produce a public-facing web map. </p><p><em>Collaboration:</em></p><p dir=\"ltr\">The digital humanities are an inherently collaborative enterprise. Barring a few assignments pretty much everything will require collaboration. This means that you should respect other team members\u2019 opinions and their time. Everyone should work together fairly. Though I will not directly manage groups, you will be given opportunities to provide feedback on the collaborative process. If the group dynamic does not appear to be working, I will intervene.</p><p><em>No Objective Whatsoever:</em></p><p dir=\"ltr\">In a famous essay, Stephen Ramsay describes what he calls, \u201cThe Hermeneutics of Screwing Around.\u201d Much of the work done by Digital Humanists means taking the data and displaying it multiple ways until it reveals something interesting. This is possible because, unlike the social and physical sciences, literary scholars are not trying to test a hypothesis, but rather are trying to (re)describe a literary text in a new way. You are encouraged to \u201cscrew around\u201d with the data you gather even if it does not lead to a concrete conclusion. </p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><meta charset=\"utf-8\"><s>There are no formal requirements for this course, though students who have taken Introduction to Digital Humanities will have a distinct advantage. For students who have not done so, they can consult supplemental materials on GitHub, QGIS, and Relational Databases. </s><strong>Revised Dec. 25th, 2021</strong></p><p><strong>This course will be cross-listed with the CS department. At the moment, some students are experiencing a registration block. If you are not able to register, please contact johannes.burgers@ashoka.edu.in to indicate your interest. Also, CC the TA Sonal Rana (sonal.rana_ma23@ashoka.edu.in) on the email. Generally, English majors, upper-level CS majors, and students who have taken Introduction to DH will be able to register. All other students will need to be interviewed.</strong></p><p><strong>Note: CS Majors will need to do a separate assignment to have this meet the requirements for the CS department.  </strong></p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Participation, Discussion, Activities 15%</p><p><meta charset=\"utf-8\"></p><p dir=\"ltr\"><meta charset=\"utf-8\"></p><p dir=\"ltr\">Conference Presentation 10%</p><p dir=\"ltr\">Project 1: Conceptual Mapping 20%</p><p dir=\"ltr\">Project 2: Mapping the Partition City 20%</p><p dir=\"ltr\">Project 3: Web Mapping Partition 35%</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><meta charset=\"utf-8\">Due to the collaborative nature of this course, attendance is mandatory. Should you miss more than 4 classes, especially for consecutive sessions, we will need to chat. Should you miss more than 6 classes we will have a more candid talk, and your grade will start to decline precipitously.</p><p>I have provided a map to our classroom for students unfamiliar with Ashoka. Please consult as necessary. </p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://github.com/joostburgers/heurist_analysis/blob/45c4c87dff2fb6680a1becf74c609d5068fee745/Class%20attendance.png\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/joostburgers/heurist_analysis/main/Class%20attendance.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 313px;\"></p></div></div><div><strong>Attachment</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><table><tbody><tr><td><a style=\"color:blue\" href=\"https://ams.ashoka.edu.in/UploadFiles/CourseCatalogueFiles/026b3a02-905f-4355-84e8-1f65b9a02c8e.pdf\" download=\"Fuzzy Cartographies_ Qualitative GIS and Web Mapping v2.pdf\">Fuzzy Cartographies_ Qualitative GIS and Web Mapping v2.pdf</a></td></tr></tbody></table></div></div>",
