            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"margin:0in\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Garamond&quot;,serif\">We often think of the Middle Ages as a time when people (and ideas) were stagnant. And yet people did travel, more slowly perhaps than we do now but with curiosity and enthusiasm. </span><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Garamond&quot;,serif\">In fact, the Middle Ages is full of travelers: pilgrims en route to Jerusalem, knights returning from battle, and merchants journeying to urban markets. People, languages, texts and ideas migrated. Some travelers returned to share their impressions with others in geographical treatises, crusade narratives, and pilgrim handbooks. Other writers stayed home but imagined voyages in romance tales or dream visions. In all these cases, travel, real or imagined, facilitated exchanges between cultures that had profound impacts on notions of self and community. </span></span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0in\"> </p><p style=\"margin:0in\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Garamond&quot;,serif\">In this seminar, we will investigate how travel, as an act and an idea, courses through medieval literature from around the globe. The seminar is organized around different types of travel\u2014wandering, crusade, pilgrimage, exploration, and dream vision. Reading authors such as Xuanzang, Geoffrey Chaucer, Ibn Battuta, and John Mandeville through the lens of mobility studies\u2014the critical study of the movement of people, goods and ideas\u2014we will ask historically-situated questions with transhistorical relevance. What defines travel writing and what generic boundaries do these writings transgress? How do narratives of travel construct self and community in the medieval past and today? </span><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Garamond&quot;,serif\">How does writing about travel establish and/or complicate authorial subjectivity? How might travel at once destabilize and/or reinforce notions of the center? Is there something \u2018medieval\u2019 about medieval travel?</span></span></span></p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"margin:0in\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Garamond&quot;,serif\">In this course you will</span></span></span></p><ul><li style=\"margin:0in 0in 0in 0.5in\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Garamond&quot;,serif\">develop an understanding of the purposes and uses of medieval English travel writing;</span></span></span></li><li style=\"margin:0in 0in 0in 0.5in\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Garamond&quot;,serif\">become familiar with key genres in medieval literature such as hagiography, chanson de geste, and dream vision;</span></span></span></li><li style=\"margin:0in 0in 0in 0.5in\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Garamond&quot;,serif\">develop literary analysis skills through close-reading;</span></span></span></li><li style=\"margin:0in 0in 0in 0.5in\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Garamond&quot;,serif\">gain an understanding of how medieval English literature is historically situated while also not over-determined by its historical moment; </span></span></span></li><li style=\"margin:0in 0in 0in 0.5in\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Garamond&quot;,serif\">engage in independent learning through a research-based digital assignment that requires the use of primary and secondary sources;</span></span></span></li><li style=\"margin:0in 0in 0in 0.5in\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Garamond&quot;,serif\">hone academic writing skills through bi-weekly blog posts and two literary analysis papers</span></span></span></li></ul></div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>A full list of assignments will be given on the first day of class. These will include an in-class presentation and a final research paper of 15-18 pages. </p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Students may miss up 3 classes without any penalty to their course participation grade. </p></div></div>",
