            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"background:white\"><span style=\"line-height:107%\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"color:#222222\">Translating the transitions that trans* theory asks us to make, this class will think about trans* theory transnationally. For too long considered the outcome of Western liberalism, trans* theory and narratives in fact exist in several shapes around the world. Whether it is the Sufi mehfil of erotic transcendence, the Indic landscape of hijras, or the Thai ecosystem of lady-boys, trans* theory has a rich life scattered across cultural and sexual geographies. We will transition across some of this terrain over the course of the semester as we are transported by texts from Iran (Afsaneh Najmabadi), India (Serena Nanda, Gayatri Reddy, Bullhe Shah), Taiwan (Qiu Miaojin), and France (Paul Preciado), among others. All along these travels, we will be guided by the etymological sense of \"trans\" as something that moves beyond what we think we know and how we like to think. </span></span></span></span></span></p></div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>A-F</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>As per syllabus</p></div></div>",
