            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p class=\"MsoFooter\" style=\"margin:0in\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Gentium Book Basic&quot;\">Collective life articulates power. On the one hand, forms of assembly and presence always enact power through ritual, action, prescribed norms of self-presentation, and established codes of social interaction. These same forms of collectivity, on the other hand, also hold potential to perform a rhetoric of resistance or, at the very least, hold out a promise of transformation. If performance is understood in its broadest sense as embodied presence going beyond aesthetic forms to include all kinds of social behaviour, then we will see that performance and power are inextricably intertwined and mutually constitutive. This course investigates the relationship between performance and politics that lies at the heart of modernity. We will focus on the politics of performance, and equally, on the performance of politics.   </span></span></span></p><p class=\"MsoFooter\" style=\"margin:0in\"> </p><p class=\"MsoFooter\" style=\"margin:0in\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Gentium Book Basic&quot;\">Our investigation will lead us to view some recurring concerns of modern social theory from a performance perspective: concepts such as community, the public sphere and counterpublics, discipline, action, assembly, and affect as well as identities such as gender, race, and caste. We will organize our analysis of performance/ politics around four themes: structures, processes, selves, and identities. First, we will explore the ways in which thinking with performance in its broadest sense\u2014as shared live experience\u2014can help us understand social relationships and political structures. Second, we will examine how performance\u2014and often, performance alone\u2014makes possible certain political processes. Third, we will trace the fraught political relationships between individual and collective selves. Finally, we will analyze the politically charged articulation of social identities. Course material may include films on music and sport, along with writing by BR Ambedkar, Hannah Arendt, Bego\u00f1a Aretxaga, Judith Butler, Uma Chakravarti, Emile Durkheim, Diana Taylor, Victor Turner, Byung-Chul Han, Jurgen Habermas, Nancy Fraser, Arlie Hochschild, Stuart Hall, Teresa Caldeira, Ann Cvetkovich, Erving Goffman, Ngugi wa Thiong\u2019o, and Jisha Menon.            </span></span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0in\"> </p></div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>TBD</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>TBD</p></div></div>",
