            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p class=\"WPNormal\" style=\"margin:0in\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Monaco\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Garamond&quot;,serif\">This course is an introduction to the central figures and problems of Ancient Greek Philosophy. We will engage with questions about the nature of ethics, knowledge, and the structure of reality, examining how various ancient views relate to one another and to present day philosophical concerns. We will begin by discussing the roots of Greek philosophy, and by seeking to locate the boundary between myth and philosophical thinking. We will consider some central pre-Socratic views, focusing especially on Heraclitus and Parmenides. We will then consider Socrates, Plato, and Aristotle in detail. These philosophers\u2019 perspectives, from the alluring to the outrageous, can bring into focus both their distinctive, sometimes alien, worldview and their enduring philosophical legacy. </span></span></span></p></div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Monaco\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Garamond&quot;,serif\">tba</span></span></span></p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Monaco\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Garamond&quot;,serif\">tba</span></span></span></p></div></div>",
