            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>The course will concentrate on Indian Philosophy during its 'middle period': from the 5th century to the 12th century.  There are two reasons why this is known as the 'Golden Age' of Indian Philosophy.  (1) By this time the ideas and arguments had attained a sophistication that was not there in the earlier period; and (2) Buddhism, a crucial ingredient in the philosophical mix, providing an impetus for the non-Buddhist systems to evolve in order to address its powerful critiques, still flourished, prior to its disappearance from India in the 12th century.</p><p>We will focus on the following topics: logic, theism versus atheism, momentariness versus persistence, idealism versus realism, and the mind-body problem.  We include some recent developments in the study of these topics.</p></div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>The following will count towards your grade:</p><p>- Presentation</p><p>- Perusall comments</p><p>- Quiz questions</p><p>- Mid-length assignments</p><p>- Final Essay</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Since the course will be taught online, attendance will not count towards the grade, so as not to penalize those who have a bad internet connection.</p><p>But it will be difficult to get a good grade unless you attend or watch the recordings of the classes, because it will be hard to score well on the various components of the grading rubric.</p></div></div>",
