            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p dir=\"ltr\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-e3927781-7fff-0b56-d8f0-315acd165bb5\" style=\"line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt;font-family:Arial;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">This course will introduce students to the analytic tradition in philosophy. It will provide an overview of the  origins, motivations and ambitions of early analytic philosophy. We will cover three aspects of the history of analytic philosophy: (1) its initial founding phase, as inaugurated in the early seminal writings of Gottlob Frege and Bertrand Russell, as well as Ludwig Wittgenstein's Tractatus; (2) the inheritance and reshaping of some of the central ideas of the founders of analytic philosophy by logical positivists like A.J. Ayer and Rudolf Carnap (3)  Criticisms and developments of (1) and (2) by thinkers like the later Wittgenstein, Quine and Kripke.</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;\"> </p><p dir=\"ltr\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-c8ccc704-7fff-538e-d731-90444d6078c5\" style=\"line-height:1.38;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt;font-family:Arial;color:#222222;background-color:#ffffff;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">In this course we will study questions like the following.</span></p><ul dir=\"ltr\"><li style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 12pt; margin-bottom: 12pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt;font-family:Arial;color:#222222;background-color:#ffffff;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">How is mathematical knowledge possible?</span></li><li style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 12pt; margin-bottom: 12pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt;font-family:Arial;color:#222222;background-color:#ffffff;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">What is the relationship between math and logic? (Are mathematical truths really all just logical truths?)</span></li><li style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 12pt; margin-bottom: 12pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt;font-family:Arial;color:#222222;background-color:#ffffff;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">Are most traditional philosophical claims and questions nonsense? Can we come up  with a criterion that demarcates meaningful terms from nonsense?</span></li><li style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 12pt; margin-bottom: 12pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt;font-family:Arial;color:#222222;background-color:#ffffff;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">Can using contemporary logic to analyze language help us more clearly state and/or solve metaphysical questions?</span></li><li style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 12pt; margin-bottom: 12pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt;font-family:Arial;color:#222222;background-color:#ffffff;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">Is all knowledge either analytic (roughly, something trivial we know by logic and definitions alone) or empirical?</span></li><li style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 12pt; margin-bottom: 12pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt;font-family:Arial;color:#222222;background-color:#ffffff;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">What does understanding a language (or the meaning of a word) consist in?</span></li></ul></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This class aims to familiarize students with some major puzzles and theories in (broadly analytic) philosophy of literature.  It also aims to improve student skills at</p><ul><li>Reading, interpreting and creatively responding to dense philosophical texts</li><li>Creating, developing and communicating original philosophical arguments.</li><li>Productive philosophical conversation</li></ul></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Readings will be posted on the course website.</p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><table width=\"500\" height=\"105\" cellspacing=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" border=\"1\"><tbody><tr><td>20%</td><td>Reading Response Activity</td></tr><tr><td>20%</td><td>Class Participation</td></tr><tr><td>30%</td><td>12 (drop 4) Short Response Papers</td></tr><tr><td>30%</td><td>Final Paper (Pitch, Draft &amp; Revision)</td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>TBA (pending COVID updates)</p></div></div>",
