            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>What can we learn from Buddhism and Buddhist thinkers about how we should treat each other? This course will explore a variety of answers to this question. Students will engage with texts from multiple Buddhist traditions and time periods beginning from the earliest Buddhist texts written 2,000 years ago to contemporary work. In the first part of the course, we will look at some of the general ethical principles and general moral virtues espoused by Buddhist thinkers. In the second part, we will examine Buddhist approaches to particular moral questions such as: Is it permissible to abort a fetus? Is it permissible to end our own life? What are our duties to our natural environment? To animals? To our society?</p><p> </p></div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><span style=\"font-size:11.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Grading Rubric:<br>Initial reflection/final reflection (2 x 2.5%) - 5%<br>In-class quizzes/activities - 25%<br>Midterm exam - 20%<br>Final exam - 22.5%<br>Outline/proposal for paper/project - 5%<br>Paper/Project - 22.5%</span></span></p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><span style=\"font-size:11.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Attendance does not officially count for your grade but 25% of your grade will come from regular in-class quizzes/activities. I will not count your 4 lowest in-class quiz/activity grades.</span></span></p></div></div>",
