            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Did women travel in the premodern world? If yes, why there is hardly any accounts written by or on women? We have read and heard a lot about all the great travellers of the ancient and medieval times: Faxian, Marco Polo, Ibn Battuta, Ma Huan, Benjamin of Tudela, Niccolao Manucci\u2026 the list goes on but all men!</p><p>This does not mean that women did not travel at all. They did undertake long journeys across long distances, between Asia, Europe, Africa and the Americas. Along the way, many of them disguised as men to protect themselves. Many travelled as pirates, some became queens, mystics, prophetesses and saints. Others were traders, sailors, admirals or pilgrims. Even many more were captured and taken across continents (for e.g., from India and Mozambique to Mexico and the Caribbean), and were forced to slavery and concubinage.</p><p>In this course, we explore such untold peregrinations of women between ca. 800 and 1800 CE with a focus on India and the Indian Ocean world. We shall read primary sources together in various languages to unearth the arduous journeys of those premodern women outside their comfort zones.</p><p>This is a reading seminar: we will read excerpts from primary sources in each class (2-3 pages per week). In addition, you need to read 10-15 pages for each class and write a short note of 500 words each week.<br> </p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>On the successful completion of this course, you will be able to</p><p>\u2022    Comprehend some of the major issues and debates on women travelers, the premodern world, and the Indian Ocean world.<br>\u2022    Approach social and cultural processes in any community in a global, oceanic and long-term perspective, and to take gender as a crucial analytical category in exploring history.<br>\u2022    Develop the advanced skills of reading primary sources critically, especially for research and writing.<br>\u2022    Familiarise yourself with conceiving, writing, and presenting a research paper.<br> </p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This course is a reading seminar: reading and discussions are the central characteristics of this course, there will not be any lecturing. We will read excerpts from primary sources in each class (2-3 pages per week). In addition, you need to read about 10-15 pages for each class and write a short note of 500 words each week (from the 3rd week onward).</p><p>It is designed for final year undergraduates, ASP students, and Ph.D. students. Ideally, you should have successfully completed at least your first year of undergraduate studies. </p><p>No prior knowledge of History is required.</p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>The course is assessed and graded on the basis of four criteria:</p><p>\u2022    Active participation in the classroom discussions (30% of the overall mark).<br>\u2022    Weekly notes (25% of the overall mark).<br>\u2022    Written essay of 4000 words, including footnotes but excluding bibliography (45% of the overall mark).</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Attendance is mandatory. One can take up to 4 notified or unnotified absences.</p></div></div>",
