            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><h2 style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 0cm 88.35pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:14pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\">(1) Translation and Transliteration</span></span></h2><h2 style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 0cm 88.35pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:14pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\">Persian to English (Prose and Poetry)</span></span></h2><p class=\"MsoBodyText\" style=\"margin-top:.05pt; margin:0cm\"> </p><p class=\"MsoBodyText\" style=\"margin-top:0cm; margin-right:5.65pt; margin-bottom:.0001pt; margin-left:5.0pt; text-align:justify; margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:14pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\">Persian texts will be given to students to translate into English. The same texts will also be transliterated into Roman characters which will help them to pronounce and transliterate the Persian words correctly. Students are required to learn the proper pronunciation of Persian words and to transliterate them by regular exercises. The transliteration system of <i>Encyclopaedia Iranica</i>, Columbia University will be used for the exercise.</span></span></p><p class=\"MsoBodyText\" style=\"margin-top:0cm; margin-right:5.65pt; margin-bottom:.0001pt; margin-left:5.0pt; text-align:justify; margin:0cm\"> </p><p class=\"MsoBodyText\" style=\"margin-top:0cm; margin-right:5.65pt; margin-bottom:.0001pt; margin-left:5.0pt; text-align:justify; margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:14pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\">Texts: </span></span></p><p class=\"MsoBodyText\" style=\"margin-top:0cm; margin-right:5.65pt; margin-bottom:.0001pt; margin-left:5.0pt; text-align:justify; margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:14pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><b>Prose:</b> <i>Setar </i>by Jalal Al Ahmed;<b> </b></span></span><span style=\"font-size:14pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\">Golestan of Saadi Shirazi Chapter no. 2  Hekayat no. 27, </span></span></p><p class=\"MsoBodyText\" style=\"margin-top:0cm; margin-right:5.65pt; margin-bottom:.0001pt; margin-left:5.0pt; text-align:justify; margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:14pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><b>Poetry:</b> Monazre-i- Bute-i-Kadu ba Derakht-i-Chenar by Anwari;<b> </b></span></span><span style=\"font-size:14pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\">Dard o Dagh by Mirza Ghalib</span></span></p><p class=\"MsoBodyText\" style=\"margin-top:0cm; margin-right:5.65pt; margin-bottom:.0001pt; margin-left:41.0pt; text-align:justify; margin:0cm\"> </p><p class=\"MsoBodyText\" style=\"margin-top:0cm; margin-right:5.65pt; margin-bottom:.0001pt; margin-left:41.0pt; text-align:justify; margin:0cm\"> </p><h2 style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 0cm 88.35pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:14pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\">(2) Persian Texts </span></span></h2><h2 style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 0cm 88.35pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:14pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\">(Prose and Poetry)</span></span></h2><p class=\"MsoBodyText\" style=\"margin-top:.5pt; text-align:center; margin:0cm\" align=\"center\"> </p><p class=\"MsoBodyText\" style=\"margin-top:0cm; margin-right:5.75pt; margin-bottom:.0001pt; margin-left:5.0pt; text-align:justify; margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:14pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\">Students once translated and transliterated the above texts, will be required to read, answer the questions and retell or write the text in their own words in Persian. Their comprehension, expressions, and pronunciations will be monitored by the faculty. The exercise will improve their grasp of the texts, literary expressions, and articulation of speech.</span></span></p><p class=\"MsoBodyText\" style=\"margin-top:0cm; margin-right:5.75pt; margin-bottom:.0001pt; margin-left:5.0pt; text-align:justify; margin:0cm\"> </p><p class=\"MsoBodyText\" style=\"margin-top:0cm; margin-right:5.65pt; margin-bottom:.0001pt; margin-left:5.0pt; text-align:justify; margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:14pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><b>Prose:</b> <i>Setar </i>by Jalal Al Ahmed; Hekayat ------, Golestan by Saadi Shirazi</span></span></p><p class=\"MsoBodyText\" style=\"margin-top:0cm; margin-right:5.65pt; margin-bottom:.0001pt; margin-left:5.0pt; text-align:justify; margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:14pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><b>Poetry:</b> Darakht-i-Baqa by Rumi; Monazre-i- Bute-i-Kadu ba Derakht-i-Chenar by Anwari; Dard o Dagh by Mirza Ghalib</span></span></p><p class=\"MsoBodyText\" style=\"margin-top:0cm; margin-right:5.65pt; margin-bottom:.0001pt; margin-left:5.0pt; text-align:justify; margin:0cm\"> </p><p class=\"MsoBodyText\" style=\"margin-top:0cm; margin-right:5.65pt; margin-bottom:.0001pt; margin-left:5.0pt; text-align:justify; margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><b><span style=\"font-size:14.0pt\" lang=\"EN-US\">(3) Persian Chronogram (The Abjad System)</span></b></span></span></p><p class=\"MsoBodyText\" style=\"margin-top:.55pt; margin:0cm\"> </p><p class=\"MsoBodyText\" style=\"margin-top:0cm; margin-right:12.9pt; margin-bottom:.0001pt; margin-left:5.0pt; text-align:justify; margin:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:14pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\">The Abjad System or Persian Chronogram is a unique system in Persian language to derive dates from letters that constitute the words. The method was used by the Persian poets in India and Iran to record the dates of events or death of eminent men. Every Arabic letter has a numerical value by which words are transformed into figures.</span></span></p></div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>There will be three monthly tests out of which students have to appear in any two (25 Marks) Best of the two will be considered for the final grading</p><p>Class Performance (25 Marks)</p><p>End Sem Exam (50 Marks)</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>All the classes are inter-connected, students are supposed to attend all the classes.  </p></div></div>",
