            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 8pt\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"line-height:107%\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><b><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"line-height:107%\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Garamond&quot;,serif\">ENG-4203-1 </span></span></span></b><b><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"line-height:107%\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Garamond&quot;,serif\">Apparitions of Macbeth <i>Jonathan Gil Harris </i>(GIS, PS)</span></span></span></b></span></span></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom:0cm; margin-top:0cm; margin:0cm 0cm 8pt\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"line-height:107%\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><b><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"line-height:107%\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Garamond&quot;,serif\">MW 10:10-11:40</span></span></span></b></span></span></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom:0cm; margin-top:0cm; margin:0cm 0cm 8pt\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"line-height:107%\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><i><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"line-height:107%\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Garamond&quot;,serif\">Macbeth</span></span></span></i><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"line-height:107%\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Garamond&quot;,serif\"> stands unsurpassed among Shakespeare\u2019s works for its capacity to frighten.  It is not just that it features scary Witches who predict the future in riddles, or a murderous tyrant who strikes terror into every corner of his kingdom.  Much of the power of the play derives from its staging of eerie, unsettling apparitions \u2013 a floating dagger, a bloody ghost, a series of visions that emerge from a cauldron.  Even the name of the play has acquired a legendary apparitional power: merely to mention it in a playhouse is supposed to conjure unspeakably bad luck.  What is behind the play\u2019s ability to scare the heck out of us?  This seminar will scrutinize <i>Macbeth </i>and its terrifying apparitions.  As we will see, these apparitions are not just plot points or theatrical special effects.  They are also emblematic of the spectral power of matter to conjure untimely possibilities and impossibilities \u2013 to make us feel, as Lady Macbeth says, \u201cthe future in the instant.\u201d  We will consider how <i>Macbeth</i>\u2019s apparitions have eerily predicted subsequent apparitions of the play, in theory (Sigmund Freud\u2019s account of psychological attachment, Terry Eagleton\u2019s analysis of capitalist reification, Michel Serres\u2019s imagining of human-non-human assemblages) and in cinema (Polanski\u2019s <i>Macbeth</i>, Kurosawa\u2019s <i>Throne of Blood</i>, Bhardwaj\u2019s <i>Maqbool</i>, Jayaraj\u2019s <i>Veeram</i>).  In the process, we will treat the \u201capparitional\u201d as a theoretical lens that helps us think about the temporalities of political conflicts involving tradition and modernity, indigeneity and cosmopolitanism, globalisation and planetary turmoil, violent tyranny and resistance.</span></span></span></span></span></span></p></div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>A-F</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Attendance required; all absences need to be notified for in advance</p></div></div>",
