            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"margin:0in 0in 0.0001pt\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">The chorus was an integral part of ancient Greek drama. Singing and dancing in the orchestra, the choruses of tragedy moralized, hymned the gods, and lamented, incorporating lyric meters and rhythms into drama. In comedy, playwrights created ever more fantastical choruses of animals and even clouds, poking fun at language, philosophy, religion, and political life. This course is an introduction to Greek and Roman drama through the chorus, considering ancient Greek choral lyric, the tragic choruses of Aeschylus, Sophocles, and Euripides, the comic choruses of Aristophanes, and the transformation of the chorus into monologue in the Roman dramas of Seneca. We will also consider the endurance of the choral voice in modern performance, including musicals on stage and screen.</span></span></p></div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>TBA</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>TBA</p></div></div>",
