            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>First few lectures in this course will be centered around need of renewable energy.</p><p>A comparison between exxisting energy sources and associated problems will be discussed with current scientific data.</p><p>We will discuss the possible energy sources that may offer much greener energy. This will include a details study about solar cells, dye snesitised solar cells, catalytic production, storage and use of hydrogen as fuel etc.</p><p>Advantanges and disadvantages of existing renewable energy will also be discussed.</p><p>Everyday declining reserves of our traditional energy sources such as coal or oil and an alrming level of environmental pollution has necessiated the discovery less harmful energy supply sources.</p><p>Some of the topics, for example, solar cells, will be discuss covering the recent development in this area.    </p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><span style=\"font-size:16px;\"><strong>The expected outcome are as follows:</strong></span></p><p>1) Students will be taught about the various alternative energy sources that may reduce the impact of environmental pollution</p><p>2) A better undrstanding about materials that use solar light and produce electricity</p><p>3) A critical knowledge about various modern energy materials like batteries, solar cells and hydrogen fuel</p><p> </p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This course will be usefull to everyone who wants to understand solar cells and hydrogen fuel etc.</p><p>Books/reading material:</p><p>1) Advanced Materials for Clean Enegy- Xu. Kobayashi</p><p>2) Renewable Energy - W. Buhrke</p><p>** A freely availble review titled \"Optimization of Solar Energy Harvesting: An Empirical Approach\" is attached.</p><p> </p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>There will be a final written exam (50 marks) and a report (30 marks) submission will be compulsory.</p><p>Marks will be divided between written exam and report: Written exam (50 marks) and a report (30 marks).</p><p>A mid term exam/report/assignment (20 marks).</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Minimum 80%</p></div></div><div><strong>Attachment</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><table><tbody><tr><td><a style=\"color:blue\" href=\"https://ams.ashoka.edu.in/UploadFiles/CourseCatalogueFiles/9653ec11-d2b0-4dd6-b460-b916539eff77.pdf\" download=\"Optimization of Solar Energy Harvesting- An Empiricl Approach.pdf\">Optimization of Solar Energy Harvesting- An Empiricl Approach.pdf</a></td></tr></tbody></table></div></div>",
