            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 8pt; text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><b>Instructor:</b> Anshu Ogra</span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 8pt; text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><b>Course description: </b></span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 8pt; text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\">The epistemological roots of climate change analysis are deeply embedded in the natural sciences. This course introduces students to an innovative shift in climate change pedagogy: from global climatological narratives to lived everyday experience. It uses everyday life as a conceptual tool for engaging with the often-frustrating question: \u2018What can I do to address climate change?\u2019.  The action paralysis induced by this dilemma is indicative of spatial and temporal disconnect between the \u2018objective\u2019 narrative of the (climate) sciences, and the lived narratives of unprecedented weather variation experienced in everyday life. This course will use a feminist science studies framework of situated knowledge to help students move beyond the global vs local divide in climate change discussions and engage with the lived experience of unprecedented weather variations on the ground in order to better address this pressing challenge of our times. </span></span></p></div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>TBA</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>TBA</p></div></div>",
