            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 8pt; text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><b>Course Title: </b>Natural Resource Governance</span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 8pt; text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><b>Instructor:</b> Vijay Ramprasad</span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 8pt; text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><b>Course description</b></span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 8pt; text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"color:black\" lang=\"EN-GB\">The goal of this course is to provide a foundation of natural governance theory and understand how these theories influence natural resource management. </span>This course will introduce students to key theories and approaches that are pertinent to the governance of natural resources in the developing world. By the end of the course, <span style=\"color:black\">students will understand environmental governance mechanisms and the changing policy landscape that shapes social and environmental outcomes. This course will involve students closely in governance challenges from assigned interdisciplinary readings across multiple sectors (e.g., forests, agriculture, water, information communication technology), encourage participatory learning and understanding of multiple perspectives by group activities, and provide assignments to promote the initiative in research and understanding of governance challenges. </span></span></span></p><p style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 8pt; text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><b>Prerequisites:</b> Courses in conservation, ecology, policy, or political ecology are highly recommended.</span></span></p></div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>TBA</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>TBA</p></div></div>",
