            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 8pt\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"line-height:107%\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><b><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"line-height:107%\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Garamond&quot;,serif\">ENG-2412-1 Critical Thinking Seminar: Critical Bhakti <i>Nitya </i><i>Pawar </i></span></span></span></b></span></span></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom:0cm; margin-top:0cm; margin:0cm 0cm 8pt\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"line-height:107%\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><b><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"line-height:107%\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Garamond&quot;,serif\">MW 10:10-11:40</span></span></span></b></span></span></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom:0cm; margin-top:0cm; margin:0cm 0cm 8pt\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"background:white\"><span style=\"line-height:107%\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"line-height:107%\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Garamond&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Bhakti is a term that has become synonymous with blind faith and a lack of criticality. This seminar works towards a deeper understanding of its meanings. While we primarily study literature from the Bhakti Movement in the Indian subcontinent, the ideas and questions range from the contemporary political sphere to the ancient usage of the term bhakti. Throughout the semester we engage with some of the following questions: Who <span style=\"background:white\">is a bhakt and what is bhakti? Is it one idea or there are multiple bhaktis? Is there particular literature that can be called the bhakti literature? What kind of movement(s) does the Bhakti Movement include in it? Is bhakti complete and blind surrender? Or can it be an expression of dissent? What is the object of bhakti? To what extent is a bhakt\u2019s devotion erotic? Is bhakti a gendered phenomenon? How is Mira\u2019s bhakti different or the same as that of Andal\u2019s or Sur\u2019s or Kabir\u2019s? What makes them stand out as bhakts or saints? Would it be possible to call a Sufi saint a bhakt?</span>  <span style=\"background:white\">We will read popular saint-poets such as Kabir, Mira, and Andal along with some not-so-popular figures such as Janabai, Lalon Fakir, and Dayaram. This course aims towards thinking of bhakti itself as a mode of critical engagement. For this purpose, the course also builds a conversation with critical thinkers such as Bruno Latour, Helen Cixous, Roland Barthes, and others. In turn, one of the key takeaways of the course will be to think about surrender and assertion while reading, thinking, and writing.</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This is a CTS.  You will be expected to workshop drafts of your essays, and improve your skills as a critical academic writer.</p></div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>A-F</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>You will be expected to attend every class.</p></div></div>",
