            "document":"",
            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>In today's age every organisation has data and by analysing that one can make useful predictions. In that sense, stored data offers us a huge potential to get an insight and make useful predictions. At the same time, efficient and meaningful analysis of huge data is a tremendous mathematical (and of course computational) challenge. This course will give you an overview of some of these challeges and some efficent attempts to resolve them.        </p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><ul><li>In the first part of this course we will discuss various applications of linear algebra in data science specifically in data compression. We will also discuss respective algorithms and their implementations using Python/ R.</li><li>In second part of the course we will discuss theory of Markov chains and use it to analyse random movement of particles over a graph network. This is extremely important for studying social network. We will end this section with the understanding of two major results:   a) Polya's result regarding recurrence and transience of random walks and</li><li>                                                                                                                                                       b) Google's page rank algorthm</li><li>In the third part of the course we will discuss some more advanced topics of predictive analytics (typically suitable for large datasets) </li><li>                 </li><li><b>Regression</b>: Review of Multiple Linear Regression, Variable Selection, Bayesian Linear Regression, Ridge Regression, LASSO, Principal Component Regression, Functional Regression</li><li><b>Classification</b>: Review of Linear Classifiers (LDA and QDA), Logistic Regression, CART, CHAID</li></ul><p> </p><p> (We may change the order if required. We may drop or add some topics depending on our progress)</p><p> </p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Prerequisite: Probability theory or Probability and Statisitcs (MAT-2020), Linear algebra</p><p>Desirable: Linear algebra and matrix analysis, Statistical inference (it is ok if you have not done these courses but ready to work hard). Programing experience also help you to think about efficient algorithms.</p><p>Suggested texts (may add some more later): </p><p>1. Foundations of Data Science by Kannan et al. (HBA) </p><p>2. Random walks and eletric networks by Doyle and Snell</p><p>3. The elements of statistical learning by Hastie, Friedman et al. (available at https://hastie.su.domains/ElemStatLearn/)</p><p> </p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Will be shared later.</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Will be shared later.</p></div></div>",
