            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"margin-right:0cm; margin-left:0cm\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\">This course examines the political economic contexts of environmental transformations, as well as the ways in which our understandings of and relations with nature are materially and discursively bound up with notions of culture, identity, and power. The course does not attempt to present a comprehensive survey of the political ecology literature, which has burgeoned over the past two-three decades. Rather, it is a close exploration of the historical genealogies of the field, as well as theories and themes related to nature, society, and politics, which fundamentally underlie the relationships between humans and environments. Political economies of nature, neoliberalization and environmental governance, agrarian questions, gendering nature, political ecology of water, environmental conflicts, resistance and social movements are but some of the exciting themes that this course will be grappling with.       </span></span></p></div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>- Class participation</p><p>- Response papers</p><p>- Presentations </p><p>- Final research paper  </p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>There is an attendance policy, which will be mentioned in the course syllabus. </p></div></div>",
