            "html_details":"<div><strong>Office timing</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Monday to Thursday: 4 PM to 4.30 PM</p></div></div><div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p> </p><p>This is a small course about a large and fascinating subject, that of Indian Civilizations. It has been structured in a way that it can be immersed in, I hope, with enjoyment.  The course will draw out civilizational elements from prehistory till the present \u2013 through travels and lives, through ideas and art forms \u2013 in which small phenomena will be linked to the larger world of the Indian subcontinent and beyond. In the process, the course will explore a varied and rich tapestry that includes rock art, the Harappan Civilization, the iconic emperor Ashoka,  the poetry of Bhakti saints,  the travels of Indians beyond India and Mughal art along with its influence on European painters like Rembrandt. Indian civilization, as the course will emphasize, is not to be seen merely as part of the dead past but as an element that continued to be invoked in present times, by literary giants like Rabindranath Tagore and statesmen like Jawaharlal Nehru, and by more ordinary people in India\u2019s villages and towns. The  course will involve scholarly readings and  literature, as also film appreciation and analysis, and a creative project to be \u2018performed\u2019 in class.</p><p><strong>COURSE OUTLINE</strong></p><p><strong>Week One: Introduction</strong></p><p>Is there an idea of Civilization?</p><p>Is there an idea of India?</p><p>Is there an idea of Indian Civilizations?</p><p><br>Readings:</p><p>Sunil Khilnani. 1997 (1998 reprint). The Idea of India. London: Penguin Books, chapter four (\u2018Who is an Indian?\u2019), pp. 150-95.</p><p>Sanjay Subrahmanyam. 2013. \u2018Is \u201cIndian Civilization\u201d a Myth?\u2019 in Sanjay Subrahmanyam Is Indian Civilization a Myth \u2013 Fiction and Histories. Ranikhet: Permanent Black, pp. 1-10. </p><p><strong>Week 2 : Civilizations and Civilizational Figures </strong></p><p>The Process of Discovery</p><p>Finding Forgotten Cities</p><p>Finding Emperor Ashoka </p><p>Readings:</p><p>Nayanjot Lahiri. 2003. \u2018The Discovery of the Indus Civilization: Early Intuitions and Unknown Reports, 1826-1920\u2019 in Biswamoy Pati, Bhairabi Prasad Sahu and T.K. Venkatasubramanian (ed.) Negotiating the Past \u2013 Essays in Memory of Partha Sarathi Gupta. New Delhi: Tulika Books, pp. 3-28.</p><p>Charles Allen. 2012. Ashoka. London: Little Brown. Chapters 7 and 8.</p><p><strong>Week Three:  Civilizational achievements of Prehistoric People </strong></p><p>Journeys from Africa to India </p><p>Rock art and an artistic sense </p><p>Readings:</p><p>Shanti Pappu and Kumar Akhilesh. 2014. \u2018Attirampakkam\u2019  in in Dilip K. Chakrabarti and Makkhan Lal (ed.) History of Ancient India Volume 1 - Prehistoric Roots. New Delhi: Vivekanand International Foundation and Aryan Books International, pp. 363-71.</p><p>Giriraj Kumar. 2014. \u2018Rock Art\u2019 in Dilip K. Chakrabarti and Makkhan Lal (ed.) History of Ancient India Volume 1 - Prehistoric Roots. New Delhi: Vivekanand International Foundation and Aryan Books International, pp.301-46.</p><p><strong>Week Four :  Clean and Dirty </strong></p><p>Cities, toilets, sewers</p><p>Ideas about pollution and cleanliness </p><p>Readings:</p><p>Virginia Smith. 2009. Clean \u2013 A History of Personal Hygiene and Purity. Oxford: Oxford University Press. Chapter 1.</p><p>Michael Jansen. 1989. \u2018Water supply and sewage disposal at Mohenjo-Daro\u2019, World Archaeology 21 (No. 2), pp. 177-192.</p><p><strong>Week Five : Kingship and Empire</strong></p><p>Emperor Ashoka\u2019s  messages in the Landscape of Empire                                                                                         </p><p>Kingship, Empire and War  in texts</p><p>Readings:</p><p>Nayanjot Lahiri. 2015. Ashoka in Ancient India. Ranikhet: Permanent Black. Chapter 6.</p><p>Upinder Singh. 2011. \u2018The Power of a Poet: Kingship, Empire and War In Kalidasa\u2019s Raghuvamsa\u2019, Indian Historical Review 38 (2):177-98. </p><p><strong>Week Six and  Week Seven: Class Presentations </strong></p><p><strong>Week Eight: Emotions and Indian Civilizations (Love and Laughter)</strong></p><p>Couples and Conceptions of Love                                               </p><p>Poking fun at people</p><p>Readings/Visual material: </p><p>Songs from Mirabai</p><p>Aisi Taisi Democracy (stand up comedy show)</p><p><strong>Week Nine: Bhakti saints</strong></p><p>Idea of Bhakti                                                                                </p><p>Songs of Bhakti saints across India</p><p>Readings:</p><p>John Stratton Hawley. 2005. Three Bhakti Voices \u2013 Mirabai, Surdas, and Kabir in their Times and Ours. New Delhi: Oxford University Press.</p><p>John Straton Hawley and Mark Juergensmeyer. 2004. Songs of the Saints of India. New York and Delhi: Oxford University Press.</p><p><strong>Weeks 10 and Part of  Eleven: Mughal India \u2013 The Accommodation of Difference </strong></p><p>Political culture and religious vocabulary</p><p>Mughal interactions with non-Islamic worlds</p><p>Readings:</p><p>Sanjay Subrahmanyam. 2010. \u2018A Roomful of Mirrors: The Artful Embrace of Mughals and Franks, 1550-1700\u2019, Ars Orientalis volume 30 (\u2018Globalizing cultures: art and Mobility in the Eighteenth Century\u2019):39-83.</p><p>Gauvin Alexander Bailey. 1998. \u2018 The Indian Conquest of Catholic Art: The Mughals, the Jesuits, and Imperial Mural Painting, Art Journal volume 57 (1) (\u2018 The Reception of Christian Devotional Art\u2019): 24-30.</p><p><strong>Week 11: The Past in the Present</strong></p><p>Invoking past civilizations in Modern India                                                          </p><p>Living Antiquarianism     </p><p>Readings:</p><p>Relevant extracts from the writings of Rabindranath Tagore and  Jawaharlal Nehru</p><p>Nayanjot Lahiri. 2013. \u2018Living Antiquarianism in India\u2019 in Alain Schnapp (ed.) World Antiquarianism \u2013 Comparative Perspectives. Los Angeles: The Getty Research Institute Publications Program, pp. 423-38.     </p><p><strong>Week 12 and Week 13:  Student Presentations and Discussion</strong></p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>The course will help students understand civilizational elements in India, from prehistory till the present</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>See 'overview' for readings</p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Two presentations and two essays based on the presentations, alonngwith participation in the DS and in class discussion</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Attending classes is mandatory. More than five absences will adversely impact the grade of the student</p></div></div>",
