            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This course will focus on the nature of personhood from a philosophical perspective. What is a person? What makes you a person? What, if anything, separates persons from other living, sentient beings, or from mere computers? Are features like rationality, consciousness, moral agency, or the capacity for thought and language required for personhood, and does having one or more of these features suffice for personhood? These questions, which are central to philosophy, will be the central focus of this course. We will look at a number of philosophical and non-philosophical texts which attempt to inform them. By the end of course, students should not only have gained familiarity with a range of issues and arguments central tophilosophy and various sub-fields (notably the philosophy of mind and metaphysics), but also how to think and write with greater clarity and precision regarding a wider range of topics.</p></div></div>",
