            "html_details":"<div><strong>Office timing</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>drop in Tuesday and Thursday noon to 1pm, or by appointment</p><p><strong>offered by: </strong>Assistant Professor Dr. Kathleen Harbin (incoming); <strong>mailto</strong>: kharbin@brockport.edu&gt;</p></div></div><div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Is the essential nature of our minds their capacity to reason, to behave in certain ways, to grasp certain features of the world? And what does understanding the mind allow us to know about ourselves, about the best kind of life for human beings, and about our relations with others? This course explores the nature of the human mind and what it can tell us about ourselves and our place in the world. We will consider whether the operations of human minds are fundamentally different from the functions of animals or robots, whether our minds enable us to make choices that are truly our own or instead only to channel the influential forces in our environment, and what the nature of our minds implies about how we should live and treat each other.</p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>By the end of the course, students will be able to:</p><ul><li>Understand important perspectives on the nature of the mind</li><li>Understand how perspectives about the mind and the human capacity for action relate to ethical questions and questions about how we should live</li><li>Recognize how different disciplines and methodological approaches can address questions about mind and behaviour</li><li>Write clearly and persuasively, with well-reasoned arguments in support of a clear thesis</li><li>Analyze challenging texts; this includes the capacity to locate, understand and evaluate challenging arguments</li></ul></div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Weekly Quizzes (10%)</p><p>Exegetical Reading Responses (four, 5% each)</p><p>1,000 Word Paper 1 (20%)</p><p>1,000 Word Paper 2 (30%)</p><p>Online Participation (including discussions, posts, and replies to other students) (20%)</p> </div></div>",
