            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This course covers elementary probability theory, the concept and methods of sampling, basic techniques for making estimates using data, and simple linear regression. Here is the list of topics we will cover in this class:</p><ul><li>Probability and Counting</li><li>Conditional Probability and Bayes' Rule</li><li>Discrete Random Variables</li><li>Continuous Random Variables</li><li>Joint Distributions and Conditional Expectation</li><li>Averages, Law of Large Numbers, and Central Limit Theorem</li><li>Point Estimation</li><li>Interval Estimation</li><li>Hypothesis Testing</li></ul><p> </p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>What you'll learn</p><ul><li>How to use probability to think about randomness and uncertainty</li><li>The story approach to understanding random variables</li><li>Probability distributions that are widely used in statistics and data science</li><li>How to make good predictions and think conditionally</li><li>Problem solving strategies</li><li>Using R to run simulations and solve probability problems</li><li>Construct estimators using method of moments and maximum likelihood, and decide how to choose between them</li><li>Quantify uncertainty using confidence intervals and hypothesis testing</li></ul></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Reference books :</p><ul><li>Larsen and Marx. An Introduction to Mathematical Statistics and Applications</li><li>Blitzstein. Introduction to Probability</li></ul><p>Online Content References :</p><ol><li>https://online.stat.psu.edu/stat415/section/6</li><li>https://www.probabilitycourse.com/preface.php</li><li>https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PL2SOU6wwxB0uwwH80KTQ6ht66KWxbzTIo</li></ol> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Your course score will be determined as the following weighted average: </p><p>Homework (30%) : There are 8 homeworks in this course. I'll drop one of your lowest scores out of 8. In other words, your best 7 scores in the homework will count towards your final grade.<br>Final (70%)</p><p>Letter Grade Distribution:</p><p>We will convert this score to a letter grade beginning with the values below as cutoffs.  These cutoffs might be adjusted, but only in the downward direction (to make letter grades higher).</p><table style=\"width:500px;\" cellspacing=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" border=\"1\"><tbody><tr><td>90</td><td>85</td><td>80</td><td>75</td><td>70</td><td>65</td><td>60</td><td>55</td><td>50</td><td>45</td><td>40</td><td>&lt;40</td></tr><tr><td>A</td><td>A-</td><td>B+</td><td>B</td><td>B-</td><td>C+</td><td>C</td><td>C-</td><td>D+</td><td>D</td><td>D-</td><td>F</td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p></p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Attendance is expected and will be taken each class. Students missing more than 10 classes would get F in their final grade. If students are late in entering the class by more than 5 minutes, they would be marked absent. Students are responsible for all missed work, regardless of the reason for absence. It is also the absentee\u2019s responsibility to get all missing notes or materials.</p></div></div>",
