            "document":"https://ams.ashoka.edu.in/UploadFiles/Content/ProgramCourseInfo/PHI-1060[PHI-1060-1]/49ed2804-a1ac-445c-848e-f436c8f1298a.pdf",
            "html_details":"<div><strong>Office timing</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>TBA - online</p></div></div><div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Critical  thinking  in  <strong>any</strong>  field  (yes, any) requires  the  ability  to  assess arguments.  In  this  course,  you  will  work  on sharpening your formal reasoning skills. To that end, we will study the nature of good and bad arguments by analyzing the properties of an artificial language known as first-order logic.</p><p>This is a <strong>required course in Philosophy</strong>. It is technical in the sense that you need to do a lot of derivation exercises and you need to learn and understand definitions of logical concepts. It is also a course that can get really exciting and interesting once you start to appreciate the fact that in so many ways, the ways we communicate is messy and ambiguous - which thinking abut Logic and its various tool brings out. </p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>By the end of this course, you will </p><ul><li>be familiar with basic concepts of logic, </li><li>be able to translate statements from ordinary language into well-formed sentences of first-order logic and vice versa,</li><li>be able to determine logical properties of arguments such as (various forms of) validity and soundness and thus be able to distinguish good from bad arguments.  </li></ul><p>Relatedly, you will  </p><ul><li>be able to construct formal proofs in propositional logic and </li><li>have acquired some familiarity with first-order predicate logic and be able to construct formal proofs that involve (multiply) quantified expressions.</li></ul><p>Logic is a rigorous discipline and the (artificial) language of first-order logic is precise and unambiguous. As we work on translating English sentences into the language of first-order logic (and vice versa), we will discover that  ordinary language is much more ambiguous than we  typically realize. </p><p>Expressing one\u2019s thoughts and one\u2019s arguments in a precise and logically compelling way is a skill that, to be mastered, requires a lot of practice. But it is also a skill that, once acquired, boosts your analytical abilities and allows you to look at your own writing and at that of others with an understanding improved by the discerning force of reason.</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>We will be using a open software called Logic 2010 - it comes with its own textbook. The intro chapter and the first two chapters are attached below, as is the syllabus from last year, which will be similar to this year's syllabus.</p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Below  is what I have used in the previous semester. Let me note that for the coming semester, I may tweak things a bit. Given that at least part of the class will be taught online, I may drop the attendance requirement, make the class partly asynchronous, and add one or two quizzes on conceptual issues per week and perhaps discussion board participation...       </p><p>Discussion Board Participation                                                                       15%     </p><p>Homework Assignments                                                                                  30%</p><p>Weekly Quizzes                                                                                                25%</p><p>3 x Online Assessments (1.5 h each) spread out over the course     3 x 10% = 30%</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attachment</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><table><tbody><tr><td><a style=\"color:blue\" href=\"https://ams.ashoka.edu.in/UploadFiles/Content/ProgramCourseInfo/PHI-1060[PHI-1060-1]/49ed2804-a1ac-445c-848e-f436c8f1298a.pdf\" download=\"PHI 1060 Syllabus - Monsoon 2020.pdf\">PHI 1060 Syllabus - Monsoon 2020.pdf</a></td></tr><tr><td><a style=\"color:blue\" href=\"https://ams.ashoka.edu.in/UploadFiles/Content/ProgramCourseInfo/PHI-1060[PHI-1060-1]/cf6b81b2-46e7-497d-bd13-e4f36d53a784.pdf\" download=\"LogicText Chap 0 Aug 2013.pdf\">LogicText Chap 0 Aug 2013.pdf</a></td></tr><tr><td><a style=\"color:blue\" href=\"https://ams.ashoka.edu.in/UploadFiles/Content/ProgramCourseInfo/PHI-1060[PHI-1060-1]/836719d7-9e9e-4287-8156-36476e3c1246.pdf\" download=\"LogicText Chap 1 Aug 2013.pdf\">LogicText Chap 1 Aug 2013.pdf</a></td></tr><tr><td><a style=\"color:blue\" href=\"https://ams.ashoka.edu.in/UploadFiles/Content/ProgramCourseInfo/PHI-1060[PHI-1060-1]/608389b8-ad14-43c2-b7c5-aa5c730a6d97.pdf\" download=\"LogicText Chap 2 Aug 2013.pdf\">LogicText Chap 2 Aug 2013.pdf</a></td></tr></tbody></table></div></div>",
