            "html_details":"<div><strong>Office timing</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>TBD</p></div></div><div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This course examines the internal processes involved in making sense of the environment<br>and deciding what action might be important. The cognitive processes like perception, attention,<br>learning, memory, language, problem-solving, reasoning, and thinking will be studied using<br>experimental and naturalistic observations of behaviour. Empirical studies will be critically reviewed<br>to understand cognitive processes.</p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>At the end of the course, you will:<br>1. Describe, compare and contrast cognitive processes and theories associated within the<br>primary areas of scientific research (e.g., models of memory, attention, etc.);<br>2. Comprehend basic research methods used to discover cognitive processes;<br>3. Demonstrate the ability to read, analyze, summarize, present scientific literature, and<br>generate meaningful questions;<br>4. Explain how theories and research findings from cognitive psychology can inform everyday<br>problems.</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Galotti, K. (2016). Cognitive psychology: In and out of the laboratory. New Delhi: Sage. <br>Brown, P. C., Roedigger, H. L., McDaniel, M. A. (2017). Make it stick: The science of successful<br>learning. Cambridge, MA: Belnap Press.</p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>TBD</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>TBD</p></div></div>",
