            "html_details":"<div><strong>Office timing</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Phone: 9910437666<br>Virtual Office: via Zoom / WhatsApp <br>Office Hours: by appointment</p></div></div><div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>The course will introduce students to the process of writing complete works in three forms:<br>- Fiction <br>- Poetry<br>- Translation</p><p>Course activities will be of four kinds:<br>- Reading prescribed pieces and discussing them in the class from the point of view of the writer<br>- Writing short pieces in class and outside in response to prompts<br>- Writing one longer piece in each of the forms mentioned above outside the class <br>- Making a presentation<br>- Discussing fellow-students' work in a workshop format</p><p>This course must be completed to take subsequent creative writing courses, leading to a minor or an interdisciplinary major.</p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>- Identifying your capabilities as a creative writer<br>- Identifying where you need to do more work<br>- An understanding of your preferred form(s)<br>- The ability to judge your own work<br>- Writing regularly<br>- Being part of a writing community</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Class Structure &amp; Schedules</p><p>Week 1-4: Fiction<br>Day 1: Discuss reading, write, read the work done in class, prompt for the week<br>Day 2: Discuss reading, write, read the work done in class<br>Day 3: Read and discuss work done on prompt<br>Day 4: Read and discuss work done on prompt, prompts for next week<br>Day 5: Discuss reading, write, read the work done in class, prompt for the week<br>Day 6: Discuss reading, write, read the work done in class<br>Day 7: Read and discuss work done on prompt<br>Day 8: Read and discuss work done on prompt, prompts for next week</p><p>Week 5-8: Poetry<br>Day 1: Discuss reading, write, read the work done in class, prompt for the week<br>Day 2: Discuss reading, write, read the work done in class<br>Day 3: Read and discuss work done on prompt<br>Day 4: Read and discuss work done on prompt, prompts for next week<br>Day 5: Discuss reading, write, read the work done in class, prompt for the week<br>Day 6: Discuss reading, write, read the work done in class<br>Day 7: Read and discuss work done on prompt<br>Day 8: Read and discuss work done on prompt, prompts for next week</p><p>Week 9-12: Translation<br>Day 1: Discuss reading, write, read the work done in class, prompt for the week<br>Day 2: Discuss reading, write, read the work done in class<br>Day 3: Read and discuss work done on prompt<br>Day 4: Read and discuss work done on prompt, prompts for next week<br>Day 5: Discuss reading, write, read the work done in class, prompt for the week<br>Day 6: Discuss reading, write, read the work done in class<br>Day 7: Read and discuss work done on prompt<br>Day 8: Read and discuss work done on prompt, prompts for next week</p><p>Week 13: Presentations</p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>20% <br>- Class participation (including attendance), respectful and constructive criticism and suggestions </p><p><br>55% to be distributed between the following, with a minimum of 25% and a maximum of 30% for each.<br>- Short Story (2,500-3,500 words) <br>- Poetry (at least 6 pages in double-spaced printed form on A4 paper)</p><p>15%<br>- Translation (1,000 words)</p><p>10%</p><p>- Presentation: A 10-minute presentation during examination week, where you will pre-circulate a short story or poem of your choice and then highlight those aspects of it that seem to you to make it successful, speaking from a practitioner's point of view.</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>You are permitted TWO absences in a semester for non-health/non-emergency reasons.</p><p>Beyond this there will be half a grade cut (from class participation and attendance) for each subsequent missed class.</p></div></div>",
