            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This course is an introduction to qualitative research methods \u2013 modes of explanation, research design, data collection and analysis \u2013 with a focus on a variety of political and sociological questions.</p><p>Through this course, you will be familiarized with a variety of research methods and tools, including interviews, participant observation, case studies and the use of documentary/primary sources. You will also learn to read and evaluate qualitative contributions to a variety of fields of studies which include identity politics, agrarian change, the study of the state and elite studies. By engaging with classic and contemporary literature, we will discuss the advantages and limitations of a variety of methodological approaches to the study of politics and debate their ethical dimension</p><h3>The Course Format</h3><p>The first half of the course is organized around the sequence that scholars conventionally follow to conduct qualitative research: find a research question, engage with existing literature, formulate a hypothesis, collect material, analyze it and finally convert that work into writing. The second part of the course covers the four chosen themes. The discussion sections will be the place to discuss the content of the class conversation, the readings, but also to learn hands-on techniques of qualitative research.</p></div></div>",
