            "html_details":"<div><strong>Office timing</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>9:00 - 10: 00 am; Mondays/ Wednesdays and By appointment. </p></div></div><div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>The course will explore questions of power and its engagement with ideas of sex and gender. The course asks questions like: How do feminists talk about \u2018women\u2019? What is the relevance of feminist theory to policy issues? What have been some of the most relevant theoretical interventions in the subject? Within these larger issues, the course will examine the interrelations of caste, gender, sexuality and class and also specific questions pertaining to power like pornography, disability and violence among others.</p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>An understanding of the key concepts mentioned above. </p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Lectures: Students are expected to attend all lectures and to have completed the reading assigned for that day before class. Students are expected to be able to participate in colloquies conducted by the professor.</p><p>If students are facing difficulties connecting online, they should contact the professor early during the semester.</p><p>Readings: All the mandatory readings would be made available to the students electronically at least a week before the lectures on the said topic.</p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Written assignments: There will be two essays that need to be submitted for the course. One essay of 2000 words-due on the Friday before the mid term break; and the second essay of 4000 words due the Friday of the reading week, before the final examinations begin. The requirements and structure of<br>the essay will be discussed in the first class of the term. The written assignments comprise 70% of the final grade: 30% and 40% respectively.</p><p>There will be penalties for late submission and extensions will be granted only in documented cases of illness or family emergency.</p><p>Apart from the essay, students will be graded on their class participation, which includes their attendance, responses and presentations through the semester. The grade on class participation is worth 30% of final grade. 10% for attendance and 20% for class participation.</p><p>Attendance Policy: Students are allowed 5 excused absences. Upon exceeding the given excused absences, students will receive a grade cut.</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Attendance Policy: Students are allowed 5 excused absences. Upon exceeding the given excused absences, students will receive a grade cut.</p></div></div>",
