            "html_details":"<div><strong>Office timing</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>We will be using Google Classroom as the Learning Management system for this course. You will automatically be added to the Google Classroom for this course via Ashoka LMS. All the course material, including lecture video recordings will be made available through the Google Classroom. In addition, we will be accepting student submissions only through Google Classroom links. No email based submissions will be considered.<br><br>On every Sunday, lecture video recordings for the next week will be uploaded on Google Classroom. We will meet at noon (12 pm) every Monday for one hour for discussion and Q/A. Students will be expected to have watched the lecture recordings that were published eight days prior to that particular Monday. Students will be expected to have gone through the required reading as well. For example, discussions on September 6th, Monday, will focus on the material covered in the lecture recordings published on August 29th, Sunday.</p></div></div><div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Computer Organization and Systems (henceforth abbreviated as COS) can be thought of as one of the layers of abstraction in describing computing systems. It is the layer above digital design but below operating systems. COS concerns itself with the basic building blocks of computing systems starting with transistors. It assumes that transistors with certain specifications are already there, and it proceeds to design computing hardware, e.g., processor, memory, etc., on top of those transistors. Thus it can also be thought of as the \"interface\" between the hardware of a computing system and the software running on that hardware.</p><p> </p><p>Familiarity with the basic (hardware) building blocks of computing systems is required not only for hardware engineers and computer architects, but also for computer programmers at all levels. Optimizing one's code for execution speed, memory usage, energy efficiency, and security requires one to be knowledgeable about the underlying hardware on which one's code will run.</p><p> </p><p>In this course, we will talk about topics such as performance metrics of hardware systems, instruction set architecture (or ISA), computer arithmetic, program execution, pipelining, memory hierarchy, and so on. We will also introduce the MIPS assembly language and learn how to perform basic operations on it.</p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>After successfully completing this course, students should be conversant with the following topics:<br> </p><ol><li>various types of computing devices in today's world,</li><li>basic building blocks of those devices,</li><li>performance metrics of computing devices,</li><li>how the software interacts with the hardware, or in other words, the \"interface\" between the software and the hardware,</li><li>classic and fundamental ideas in the the design of computing systems,</li><li>how to design the hardware to improve performance, energy efficiency, security, and so on,</li><li>how to write software to utilize the underlying hardware's strengths and avoid its bottlenecks,</li></ol><p>etc.</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><ul><li>Computer Organization and Design: The Hardware/Software Interface (5th Edition), David Patterson and John Hennessy. This book will be referred to as COD-PH.<br> </li><li>Computer Architecture: A Quantitative Approach (5th Edition), John Hennessy and David Patterson. This book will be referred to as CA-HP.<br> </li><li>More readings to be assigned as the semester progresses. These will be updated on the Readings section for that lecture.</li></ul> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>The following is a tentative guideline for the grading policy and may undergo a change.<br> </p><ol><li>Exams : 40%<br>There will be a mid-term exam and an end-term exam, both carrying 20% weightage each.<br> </li><li>Assignments - 40%<br>An individual assignment will be due every two weeks or so; approximately 6-7 assignments will be handed out in all over the semester. Assignments might involve programming.<br> </li><li>Quizzes: 20%<br>There will be continuous evaluation throughout the semester in form of weekly quizzes. Each quiz will have an instructor-assigned weightage, which may vary from one quiz to another.</li></ol> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>None.</p></div></div>",
