            "html_details":"<div><strong>Office timing</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>TBD</p></div></div><div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">This is the first course in the Macroeconomics sequence of the Graduate Economics program and aims to equip students with tools pertaining to dynamic economic analysis, which can then be used to analyze pertinent macroeconomic questions. The focus of this course is economic growth. Students are introduced to various canonical models which constitute the foundations of modern macroeconomics. </p><p> </p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>The recommended textbooks for this course are the following:</p><ol><li>Acemoglu, Daron, Introduction to Modern Economic Growth, Princeton Press, 2009.</li><li>Heer, Burkhard, and Alfred Maussner. Dynamic general equilibrium modeling: computational methods and applications. Springer Science &amp; Business Media, 2009</li><li>Ljungqvist, Lars, and Thomas J. Sargent, Recursive macroeconomic theory, MIT press, 2018.</li><li>McCandless, George. The ABCs of RBCs: an introduction to dynamic macroeconomic models. Harvard University Press, 2008.</li><li>Stokey, Nancy L., Robert E. Lucas, and Edward C. Prescott. Recursive Methods in Economic Dynamics, Harvard University Press, 1989.</li></ol><p>Students are not required to buy these textbooks. Pdf versions are easily available online and should be accessed for reference. Lecture notes will be provided on the course website. </p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>TBD</p> </div></div>",
