            "html_details":"<div><strong>Office timing</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>We meet from 10:10 AM - 11:40 AM; Every Tuesdays, Thursdays.</p></div></div><div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Comparative Politics is the study of political phenomena occurring predominantly within countries. The comparative method is a way of examining such phenomena. The subfield itself is broad and encompasses a variety of pertinent questions. In this introduction, we will focus on the thematic question: How does regime type affect policy outcomes? As a first cut, we will explore the selectorate theory. We will use its logic to demonstrate how democracies can have policy outcomes that are systemically distinct from their autocratic counterparts. Next, we will explore the economic and cultural determinants of democracy and study how transitions to democracy can occur. In third part of the course, we will emphasize institutional variations within democracies and identify their consequences. For the last part the course, we will re-examine the policy consequences of regime type. Is it merely a dichotomy; namely that \u201cdemocracy is good\u201d and \u201cautocracy is bad\u201d?</p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Through the substantive portion of this course, students will 1) identify the major issue-areas in comparative politics, 2) define and demarcate major concepts in comparative politics, and 3) explain the policy predilections of different regime types. Through an emphasis on social scientific methodology, students will 1) understand the importance of methods in political science, and 2) learn about the use of appropriate theories to explain political phenomena.</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>W. R. Clark, M. Golder and S.N. Golder, Principles of Comparative Politics. 2nd edition, CQ Press 2012. ISBN 978-1-60871-679-1. Hereafter referred to as the \u201cTextbook\u201d.</p><p>B. Bueno de Mesquita, and A. Smith, The Dictator\u2019s Handbook: Why bad behavior is almost always good politics. Public Affairs 2011. ISBN: 978-1-61039-184-9. Hereafter referred to as \u201cHandbook\u201d.</p><p> </p><p>You get some readings on Library Dspace here : https://bit.ly/2ZBOZcY   </p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Final exam                                             (25)<br>Midterm exam                                       (25)   <br>Class attendance                                  (10)   <br>Discussion Section Participation          (10)<br>In-class quizzes                                    (15)</p><p>Essay                                                   (15)     </p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>You are expected to show up for both the formal lessons and the discussion sections (DS). You may miss a total of three lessons (from both the lessons and the DS), unexcused, without grade penalty. Each unexcused absence beyond the third lesson will result in a 1% deduction from the final grade. As attendance may be taken at any lesson, it behooves the student to show up. Attendance also requires the student to arrive on time.</p></div></div>",
