            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>The course can be divided into two sections. The first section introduces axiomatic mentors in economics, related to individual choice theory. We refer to the classic textbook to introduce the individual choice theory and discuss rationality and the conditions under which it is guaranteed. We discuss Arrow\u2019s impossibility theorem and possibility results with domain restrictions like single-peaked preferences and intermediate preferences.</p><p> </p><p>The second part consists of topics on fair division and welfare economics. The main reference for these topics is the textbook by Moulin. We discuss a number of rules like proportional rule, uniform gains, equal surplus/ uniform loss rule for fair division. We look at cardinal (utilitarian, egalitarian, Nash) as well as ordinal divisions (Borda, Condorcet, Scoring rules). We discuss Shapley value and core. Lastly, we discuss topics on the tragedy of commons and how to achieve efficient outcomes using fair methods satisfying properties like envy-freeness.</p><p> </p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><ol><li>\u201cCollective choice and social welfare\u201d by Amartya Sen (Harvard University Press, Year: 2019)</li><li>\"Fair division and collective welfare\" by Herv\u00e9 J. Moulin (MIT Press, 2004)</li></ol> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Weightage: 20% to presentation, 40% each to the mid-term and the final exam.</p><p>Grading will be on absolute thresholds: A: 85 and above, A-: 80-84 , B+: 75-79, B: 70-74, B-: 65-69, C+: 60-64, C: 55-59, C-:50-54, D+:45-49, D:40-44, D-:35-39, F: 34 and below.</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Students with more than 7 absences will be penalised.</p></div></div>",
