            "html_details":"<div><strong>Office timing</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p> Intro to Audio Video Production Basic MS-1001 | Wednesday and Friday Morning 10:10 Slot</p><p>Office hours Wednesday, 3:00-5:00 pm</p></div></div><div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This is a basic technical course on audio-visual media, students will learn to listen, watch and create audio-visual stories of their own. This includes an introduction to handling audio and video recording systems. From microphones to cameras, storyboarding and basic audio and video editing.</p><p> </p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Media Literacy on how to hear and view media in the audio-visual format, separately and together.</p><p>Understanding basic camera operations:</p><p>-  Lighting techniques</p><p>-  Basic audio-video editing tools </p><p>-  Sound and video recording</p><p>-  Constructing an audio and audio-visual narrative from scratch</p><p>Mastering basic elements of storytelling from scripting to logging, from production to preview.</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>HARDWARE REQUIREMENTS:</p><p>The following hardware will be required in order to attend the classes online: </p><p>A laptop or desktop with an i5 processor at least, and 4GB RAM </p><p>A smartphone with a working back and front camera</p><p>Smartphone and laptop/desktop with ample memory available</p><p>An internet connection with 5 Mbps speed dedicated to a single user with good data </p><p>A set of earphones or headphones for the duration of the class </p><p> </p><p>SOFTWARE REQUIREMENTS:</p><p>Over the tenure of this course, we will be delving into recording, editing, and formatting audio and video individually and together. The software we will use for each component is as follows:</p><p>1. Audio editing: Audacity </p><p>2. Video editing: DaVinci Resolve (16 or 17)</p><p> </p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Three assignments through the semester will be an ascending base of developing skills in seeing, making a media product and maintaining a proper record of the process. All classes will involve group work.</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Attendance Policy: We have a total of 13*2 lecture sessions. Each session consists of two classes. Students can miss up to 2 classes with no penalty. 2.5% will be deducted from the attendance grade for every class missed beyond 2 classes. </p><p> </p><p>Class Participation:</p><p>This will include a) your participation interaction inside and outside the class. b) your performance in quizzes c) submission of an in-class activity. d)Video has to be active when the class is going online</p><p>The students will have to submit three assignments throughout the semester. All three assignments will be individual. The exact details of the assignment will be shared during the class.  </p><p> </p><p>* Late Submission will get a 10% grade cut on each Assignment. In case of emergency, the student has required to email both the Instructors and CC the TA 24 hours prior to the submission is due. Professor will grant extension accordingly if the reason is valid and supported with evidence. No end moment requests will be entertained. </p><p> </p><p>General Policies</p><p>The syllabus is a guiding force for all of us in this class. Please read it carefully and make sure you understand it. Ask questions if there is anything that is not clear to you.</p><p>Academic Integrity- Academic dishonesty in any form will be dealt with as per University Policy. If you steal someone else\u2019s work (video or audio) / use downloaded animations, it will be reported to the OAA, and be proceeded accordingly.</p><p>Remember, this is a technical course. That means the class is important, and you also need to put in time outside the class. You should have gone through the reading material before attending classes. Additionally, you should try out the technicals taught in class (like shooting, lighting, editing) in your own time.</p><p>If you are absent/late to any class, it is your responsibility to update yourself with whatever topic or information you had missed with your group members. In case of further queries, you can reach out to the TA. </p><p>If you can\u2019t meet the equipment-related prerequisites mentioned above then please take the course in the next semester provided the pandemic fades away by then and we are back on-campus.</p></div></div>",
