            "html_details":"<div><strong>Office timing</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Thursday: 11 a.m. to 12 noon</p></div></div><div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Note: The new instructor of this course (Dr. Suratna Das) might make some minor changes at a later date.</p><p>The theory of electricity and magnetism as a unifying theory of two disparate topics is one of the pillars of physics. This course will develop the fundamental ideas of the subject and discuss the unification via the theory of relativity, going upto Maxwell\u2019s equations.</p><p>Course Content:</p><p>1. Review of basic mathematical ideas: vector algebra, vector calculus</p><p>2. Electrostatics: Fields, potentials, work and energy<br>3. Potentials: Laplace equation, method of images, multipole expansion</p><p>4. Magnetostatics: Forces, role of currents, vector potential</p><p>5. Special theory of relativity: Lorentz transformation, four vectors<br>6. Unification of E and B, Maxwell\u2019s equations<br>7. Electric field in matter: conductors, dielectrics, superconductors<br>8. Magnetic field in matter: Diamagnets, paramagnets and ferromagnets</p><p>9. More on electrodynamics, if time permits</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Books<br>1. Introduction to Electrodynamics, by D J Griffiths</p><p>2. Electricity &amp; Magnetism, by E M Purcell</p><p>3. The Feynman Lectures in Physics vol 2, by R P Feynman, R B Leighton, and M Sands</p><p>4. Mathematical Methods for Physicists by Arfken and Weber</p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>The classes will be interactive with discussions and problem solving. Evaluations will be based on homework and quizzes, midterm examination, and final examination (30+35+35).</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Students are expected to attend all the classes</p></div></div>",
