            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Why do individuals identify with different groups and what motivates them to behave in extreme ways to uphold group goals? How are group differences in status and opportunity maintained and justified through generations? This course will answer these and similar questions by engaging with the various ways that groups interact and behave. We will examine how the individual relates to their social identity and how that identity shapes individual actions. The course will cover foundational and contemporary social-psychological theories on prejudice, stereotyping, conformity, identity, intergroup bias, intergroup conflict and violence as well as peace and reconciliation. Through active discussion and reflection with students the course will look at how intergroup relations is being reshaped in a digital world and the significance of social identity in light of recent global events and movements.</p></div></div>",
