            "html_details":"<div><strong>Office timing</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Tuesday [10am-12noon]</p></div></div><div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Unlike quantitative research methods that are aimed at hypothesis-testing and generalization, qualitative methods aim to understand a phenomenon in a context-sensitive manner and help generate hypotheses. Here are just a handful of questions that you can answer using qualitative methods: How do Ashoka University students perceive their experiences in relations to Delhi University students? What was the impact of COVID on migrant workers? How are the experiences of upper-caste women different from that of SC/ST/OBC women? How do employees at an organization perceive their bosses in corporate organizations? This course equips students with the theoretical as well as practical aspects of qualitative research in psychology. Further, students will learn about writing and publishing qualitative research<br><br> </p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>By the end of the term, you will be able to:</p><ul><li>Understand the theoretical assumptions underlying qualitative research.</li><li>Identify, conceptualize, plan, and execute a qualitative research project.</li><li>Critically examine your role in shaping research from an intersectional perspective.</li><li>Apply the most appropriate sampling strategies and data collection techniques.</li><li>Plan and undertake thematic analysis of qualitative data.</li><li>Understand what makes for high-quality qualitative work.</li></ul></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>All required books and readings will be provided:</p><p>Braun, V. and Clarke, V. (2013) Successful qualitative research: A practical guide for beginners. London: Sage.<br>Lune, H., &amp; Berg, B. (2017) Qualitative research methods for the social sciences (9th ed.). Essex: Pearson.</p><p> </p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Letter Grade [Percentage]</p><p>A [90 -100]</p><p>A- [85-89]</p><p>B+ [80-84]</p><p>B [75-79]</p><p>B- [70-74]</p><p>C+ [65-69]</p><p>C [60-64]</p><p>C- [55-59]</p><p>D+ [50-54]</p><p>D [45-49]</p><p>D- [40-44]</p><p>F [0-39]</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Attendance will be taken within the first five minutes of every class. I expect students to attend all lecture and discussion sessions. The following rules will apply for absences: </p><ul><li>Missing 4 classes: Excused (no grade cut)</li><li>Missing 5 classes: One grade cut on the final grade for the course </li><li>Missing 7 classes: Two grade cuts on the final grade for the course </li><li>Missing 9 or more classes: A \u2018Fail\u2019 grade for the course </li></ul></div></div>",
