            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This third year undergraduate course will be an introduction to Quantum Mechanics.</p><p>Historical introduction and motivation: The need for quantum mechanics - structure and stability of atoms, atomic spectroscopy, blackbody radiation, properties of solids and gases. Wave-particle duality. The double slit and delayed choice experiments.</p><p>The fundamental basis of quantum physics: Amplitudes as pre-probabilities, their addition and multiplication for quantum processes - the principle of superposition.<br>Introducing the fundamental postulates of (the hamiltonian formulation of) quantum mechanics: Hilbert space of states, bra-ket notation, observables as linear operators, Schrodinger equation and unitary evolution, state vector collapse - Born rule.</p><p>The energy, position and momentum basis - transforming between different bases. Heisenberg\u2019s Uncertainty Principle, the Classical limit and Ehrenfest\u2019s Theorem. Pauli matrices and two-level quantum systems.</p><p>Illustrating the basic concepts through simple examples: particle in a 1D potential (Dirac delta, infinite and finite square-well potentials) - bound states and scattering. Tunnelling and quantum mechanical explanation of radioactive decay.</p><p>The harmonic oscillator - the algebraic and analytical solution in QM.</p><p> Angular Momentum in Quantum Mechanics. </p><p>Spin in Quantum Mechanics.</p><p>The hydrogen atom - derivation of its energy levels. </p><p>*Identical particles - symmetric and antisymmetric wave functions. Pauli exclusion principle.</p><p>*Basics of Quantum theory of composite systems, quantum entanglement, density matrices and open quantum systems.</p><p>Starred (*) topics may be omitted due to lack of time.</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><br>Introduction to Quantum Mechanics, by David J. Griffiths [Pearson, Indian edition]  (part I mostly)</p><p>Also useful for this course would be:<br>Principles of Quantum Mechanics, by R. Shankar [Springer]</p><p>Other books useful for reference and supplementary reading include:</p><p>Feynman Lectures on Physics (Vol. III)<br>The Quantum Challenge , by Zajonc and Greenstein</p><p>Quantum Mechanics, lectures by Leonard Susskind (youtube). A text based on these introductory lectures is also available: \u201cQuantum Mechanics: The Theoretical Minimum\u201d (Penguin)</p><p> </p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Assessment will be based on: Regular assignments (50%), viva (20%), final exam (20%) and class attendance and participation (10%). </p><p> </p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Students are expected to attend all the lecture and discussion sessions.</p></div></div>",
