            "document":"",
            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This course pursues four inter-related objectives. The first one is to critically engage with the concepts of democracy and authoritarianism in South Asia. What constitutes democracy, what defines an authoritarian regime, and in what ways any political regime necessarily displays features of both streams?</p><p> </p><p>The second objective is to confront theory to the context of South Asia or, to be more precise, to the multiple contexts offered by countries conventionally grouped under the denomination \u201cSouth Asia\u201d. We will compare the trajectories of state-building in India, Pakistan, Bangladesh and Sri Lanka. We will examine some of the major developments that have marked the postcolonial history of these four countries, debates around the idea of the nation, around the definition of national identities. We will apply the concepts of democratization, democratic consolidation, democratic breakdown and collapse across the subcontinent.</p><p> </p><p>The third objective of this course is to select some of the basic elements constitutive of a democratic society and regime and to look again at South Asian trajectories: The rule of law and the role of the judiciary, the relationship between civilian and military power, the question of pluralism and status of minorities, the role of political parties and elections, and the presence of democratic and anti-democratic counter-forces embedded in civil society organizations or institutions.</p><p> </p><p>Finally, we will study transversally some aspects of political culture that also bind South Asian countries together: the cult of political leaders and dynasticism, the criminalization of politics, among others. </p></div></div>",
