            "html_details":"<div><strong>Office timing</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>4 PM to 6 PM, Friday, Online meeting, by prior appointment only.</p><p>Please write to me 1 days in advance so that we can fix the e-meeting.</p></div></div><div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>In the present century, exceptional advancements in computational power and numerical optimization routines have turned quantitative methods to be critically important for solving biological problems. This course lays a basic foundation of model thinking and provides an exposure to quantitative treatments of various biological processes.</p><p> </p><p>During this course the students will actively participate in learning several key quantitative biology techniques, including ODEs, cellular automata, phase plane analysis, stability analysis, steady-state analysis, quantifying chaos and population stability, through active participation in the class. Upon completion, the students will appreciate the rationale, principles and methodology of constructing and analysing models in various fields biology,<em> inter alia</em>, population dynamics, microbiology, enzyme kinetic, epidemiology, and evolution.</p><p> </p><p>Primary focus of this course will be on the graphical interpretations and hands-on training sessions. The amount of mathematics involved will be minimal. Basic knowledge of coding in any computational programming language will be helpful for this course.</p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Quantitative thinking and modelling intuition in Biology.</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>There is no prescribed text book for this course. Suitable reading materials will be shared after the lectures. Interested students may to go through the following books for additional reading.</p><ul><li>Murray, J.D., 2007. Mathematical biology: I. An introduction (Vol. 17). Springer Science &amp; Business Media.</li><li>Otto, S.P. and Day, T., 2011. A biologist's guide to mathematical modeling in ecology and evolution. Princeton University Press.</li><li>Strogatz, S.H., 2018. Nonlinear dynamics and chaos with student solutions manual: With applications to physics, biology, chemistry, and engineering. CRC press.</li><li>Railsback, S.F. and Grimm, V., 2019. Agent-based and individual-based modeling: a practical introduction. Princeton university press.</li></ul> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>There are four grading components. Their relative weightages are given below.</p><ul><li>Exam (best 2 out of 3): 40%</li><li>Classroom assignments 30%</li><li>DIY Project: 20%</li><li>Class participation: 10%</li></ul><p> </p><p>At the end of the course a letter-grade will be given based on the overall percentage marks as per the scheme below.</p><p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\">90 \u2013 100 A<br>80 \u2013 89 A-<br>75 \u2013 79 B+<br>70 \u2013 74 B<br>65 \u2013 69 B-<br>60 \u2013 64 C+<br>55 \u201359 C<br>50 \u2013 54 C-<br>45 \u2013 49 D+<br>40 \u2013 44 D<br>&lt;40 F</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><ol><li>Attending classes is not mandatory.</li><li>If you decide to attend a class you should maintain general online classroom meeting norms.</li><li>If you have a genuine reason to miss one of the exams (with approval from OAA), inform me at the earliest so that I can schedule a makeup exam.</li><li>If you copy or cheat in some other way during exam, you will receive \u2018F\u2019 for the course, without any further discussion.</li><li>For the classroom assignments and DIY project, you are allowed to take help from your colleagues or other authentic resources on the web provided you acknowledge the sources appropriately.</li></ol></div></div><div><strong>Attachment</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><table><tbody><tr><td><a style=\"color:blue\" href=\"https://ams.ashoka.edu.in/UploadFiles/CourseCatalogueFiles/330ce2b4-0d6f-4d03-8943-48a2e6c31c62.pdf\" download=\"Syllabus.pdf\">Syllabus.pdf</a></td></tr></tbody></table></div></div>",
