            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This course introduces some central arguments and ideas in the history of western phi- losophy 1600-1800, studying figures like Descartes, Leibniz, Locke, Berkeley, Hume, and Kant. Philosophers in this period responded to developments in science by making philosophical proposals which still set the agenda for work on perception, knowledge, consciousness etc. in western philosophy today. We will follow an ongoing conversation on topics like the following. How (if at all) are certain kinds of knowledge possible, e.g., knowledge of mathematics, the external world, causation, the future, and scientific laws? What is the relationship between the mind and the body? Can studying the nature and sources of human knowledge teach us something about the limits to what philosophy and science can hope to achieve or the best methods for doing philosophy?</p><p><strong>offered by</strong>: Associate Professor Dr. Sharon Berry (incoming); <strong>mailto</strong>: seberry@invariant.org</p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This class aims to make students familiar with some of the most influential arguments and theories in early modern western philosophy. It also aims to improve student skills at</p><p>\u2022 reading, interpreting and creatively responding to dense philosophical texts</p><p>\u2022 productive philosophical conversation</p><p>\u2022 developing and writing up arguments</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>All readings will be available for free on the course website.</p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p> </p><table style=\"width:500px;\" cellspacing=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" border=\"1\"><tbody><tr><td>10%</td><td><p>Reading response activities, e.g., comments on assigned texts in Perusal. Due 24 hours before class.</p></td></tr><tr><td>20%</td><td><p>Participation: Credit can be earned by participating in discussions in class or on the course website.</p></td></tr><tr><td>25%</td><td>Short Paper (3-4 pages). Your grade will be split as follows: \u202210% abstract/paper pitch<br>\u202230% first draft<br>\u202260% revision (graded to a higher standard)</td></tr><tr><td>35%</td><td>Medium Paper (4-6 pages). Your grade will be split as above.</td></tr><tr><td>10%</td><td>Tiny slideshow presentation (2-5 minutes) and subsequent Q&amp;A/discussion</td></tr></tbody></table><p>Extra Credit: There will be many opportunities to earn extra credit.</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Attendance during scheduled course meetings is not mandatory (see participation grades below) but strongly encouraged. All handouts and lectures from class will be available online.</p></div></div><div><strong>Attachment</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><table><tbody><tr><td><a style=\"color:blue\" href=\"https://ams.ashoka.edu.in/UploadFiles/Content/ProgramCourseInfo/PHI-2450[PHI-2450-1]/d13125fa-e317-4fe7-98ca-69ca16a8f9af.pdf\" download=\"Early_Modern_Syllabus.pdf\">Early_Modern_Syllabus.pdf</a></td></tr></tbody></table></div></div>",
