            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Description:</p><p>Governance Entrepreneurship</p><p>Using the spirit of enterprise to enable system-change</p><p>Fall 2020<br>Faculty: Piyush Tewari, Priyank Narayan<br>Office Hours: Via Google Docs sign-up sheet</p><p>Working with governance structures has become imperative for changemakers. Whether it is about selling or scaling, Government can be a key customer as well as a facilitator. So, what are some of the principles of entrepreneurship that can be applied to deal with Government and governance structures? What differentiates it from entrepreneurship in a purely business setting?</p><p>This course teaches cutting edge techniques to facilitate system-change by combining the spirit of enterprise with zeal for public service. The instructor is a renowned policy advocate and campaign strategist responsible for several successful system-change interventions in the public health and safety space. More information about the instructor is available at: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Piyush_Tewari</p><p>The course covers all key aspects of building a successful and enterprising campaign to bring about positive change in governance. It pushes students to think hard about the change that they wish to see and then guides them through the structure of achieving that change. The course thoroughly examines power structures and dynamics and teaches students how to navigate through old and new power systems. Students can expect to gain a deeper understanding of governance, power, and strategizing. They can also expect to bolster their skills in community organizing, negotiation, and strategic communication.</p><p>Writing Assignments and Tests: Grades for the course will be based on three small writing assignments and a final presentation by teams of three students on a system-change campaign plan. The details of the final paper will shared in class on Day 1.</p><p>Grading: Grades will be based as follows: 30 percent grade (10 percent each) for completion of the three writing assignments; and 55 percent based on the final project. The remaining 15% will be awarded based on attendance and class participation.</p><p>Class Schedule:</p><p>Class 1: Introduction to Governance Entrepreneurship</p><p>Readings: To be prescribed before class</p><p>This class will cover,</p><p>The Pledge</p><p>The link: Governance and entrepreneurship</p><p>Problem solving: Partisan vs Pragmatic problem solving</p><p>The need to be enterprising</p><p>Determining the ask</p><p>Definition of Advocacy</p><p>Exercise</p><p>Class 2: Power</p><p>Readings: To be prescribed before class</p><p>This class will cover,<br>a. What is Power and where does it lie b. Forms of Power<br>c. Video<br>d. Exercise</p><p>Class 3: Power structures in Governance</p><p>Readings: To be prescribed before class</p><p>This class will cover,<br>a. Federal structures \u2013 Functioning of the Parliament<br>b. State structures \u2013 Functioning of State legislatures<br>c. Supreme Court of India \u2013 Basic functioning and cycle of a petition<br>d. Guest Speakers \u2013 Proposed Speakers: GK Pillai, Former Union Home</p><p>Secretary and Chakshu Roy, Head, Legislative at PRS Legislative</p><p>Class 4: Power Mapping and Stakeholder Analysis I</p><p>Readings: To be prescribed before class This class will cover,</p><p>Proprietary Material 2</p><p>a. AARs<br>b. Segmentation<br>c. Exercise<br>d. Guest Speaker \u2013 Proposed Speakers: Prof. Rajeev Gowda, Member of</p><p>Parliament (Rajya Sabha) and Menaka Guruswamy, Time 100 and lawyer behind the 377 judgment</p><p>Class 5: Telling your story</p><p>Readings: To be prescribed before class</p><p>This class will cover,</p><p>Why a story</p><p>Structure of your story</p><p>Videos</p><p>Exercise</p><p>Class 6: Organizing and Campaigning I</p><p>Readings: To be prescribed before class</p><p>This class will cover,</p><p>Organising vs Mobilising</p><p>Effective Organising</p><p>Video</p><p>Guest Speaker \u2013 Proposed Speaker: Manish Sisodia, Deputy Chief</p><p>Minister of Delhi</p><p>Class 7: Organizing and Campaigning II</p><p>Readings: To be prescribed before class</p><p>This class will cover,<br>a. Building a network of supporters<br>b. The common ask<br>c. Mobilizing resources<br>d. Guest Speaker \u2013 Proposed Speaker: Aruna Roy, Former NAC Member</p><p>and Activist (RTI, NREGA, Right to Food)</p><p>Class 8: Organizing and Campaigning III</p><p>Readings: To be prescribed before class</p><p>This class will cover,</p><p>Building leadership teams</p><p>Strategizing</p><p>Building a campaign</p><p>The launch</p><p>Video</p><p>Class 9: Negotiating 101</p><p>Readings: To be prescribed before class This class will cover,</p><p>BATNA</p><p>The range</p><p>Using data and emotion</p><p>Exercise</p><p>Class 10: Communication Strategy I</p><p>Readings: To be prescribed before class</p><p>This class will cover,</p><p>Tools of communication</p><p>Strategic communication</p><p>Building a communication plan</p><p>Video</p><p>Class 11: Communication Strategy II</p><p>Readings: To be prescribed before class</p><p>This class will cover,</p><p>Building a communication plan contd.</p><p>Strategic communication</p><p>Guest Speaker \u2013 Proposed Speakers: Alex Kuruvilla, Managing</p><p>Director, Conde Nast, India and Rajdeep Sardesai, News Anchor</p><p>Exercise</p><p>Class 12: Project Presentations I</p><p>Students to present final presentations for grading Class 13: Project Presentations II<br>Students to present final presentations for grading</p><p> </p></div></div><div><strong>Attachment</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><table><tbody><tr><td><a style=\"color:blue\" href=\"https://ams.ashoka.edu.in/UploadFiles/Content/ProgramCourseInfo/ENT-2006[ENT-2006-1]/03806251-6ba2-4ed3-948c-43219c86f892.pdf\" download=\"Governance Entrepreneurship.pdf\">Governance Entrepreneurship.pdf</a></td></tr></tbody></table></div></div>",
