            "html_details":"<div><strong>Office timing</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Office timings are flexible and will be scheduled with individual students based on their need. </p></div></div><div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This course is structured into two parts </p><p>Part-I The logic and formation of the immune system. <br>Part-II How the components of the immune system work to protect the host from pathogens.</p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>After completing the course students will be able to</p><p>- Identify key immune components and processes</p><p>- Describe and compare the main mechanisms in innate and adaptive immunity</p><p>- Examine connections between the innate and immune system to analyze how they work together</p><p>- Understand the principles of how the immune system recognizes everything it encounters</p><p>- Discuss the genetic basis for immunological diversity and the development of mature lymphocyte receptor repertoires</p><p>- Describe antigen recognition by B and T cells and how antigen shapes resulting effector responses</p><p>- Recognize the cellular components and major mechanisms in mucosal immunity</p><p>- Understand the principles behind vaccine or infection induced immunity</p><p>- Dissecting some recent findings related to COVID19</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><strong>Main Reference text </strong>- Janeway's Immunobiology (Kenneth Murphy and casey Weaver). I am using the 9th Edition for reference and the library has one hard copy and a few chapters on D-space. You can also refer to the 5thedition (without copyright infringement) online if you search in ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books (search for Immunobiology, this is a searchable book not a browsable one). </p><p><strong>Suggested reading</strong> - How the Immune System Works (Lauren Sompayrac). You can go over this to ease into concepts before or during the course.This is provides a nice overview, is an easy read and I suggest reading the entire text over a week or two. The library has a copy and a few chapters are on D-space. I will not be teaching this course from an aspect of evolution but a series of articles by Vineeta Bal and Satyajit Rath (between 1996 to 1998) in the journal Resonance will be a nice read.</p><p>We will be using primary literature on occassion in the course (provided at the time of the associated lectures). On occasion, there will be a quiz or MCQ to infer class understanding of key concepts before moving on to the next topic / lecture, it is mandatory that these are completed in time. Lectures will be taken with the assumption that assigned prework has been done.</p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Evaluation criteria for BIO-3443/BIO-6443-1 (Immunology course Monsoon 2021)</p><p><strong>Summary:</strong></p><p>A. 30% marks for continuous / formative evaluations</p><p>B. 35% mid-semester evaluation</p><p>C. 35% end-semester evaluation</p><p><strong>Details of formative evaluation (or how the 30% in A is divided)</strong></p><p>- 10% for class participation (evaluated in questions / discussions of relevance, in class and in immunology-releated seminars, pre-class prep). In general, make the instructor stay awake in class (or seminar) and you earn this.</p><p>- 10% real time, in-class assignment or quiz</p><p>- 10% take home assignment or exam</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>None.</p></div></div>",
