            "html_details":"<div><strong>Office timing</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>By appointment, https://calendly.com/amita-baviskar</p><p> </p></div></div><div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This workshop aims at helping ASP and MLS students in Sociology-Anthropology design and execute their research projects.  It will be run as an intensive seminar where students actively collaborate with each other to refine their research proposals and provide support during data collection and interpretation.  By the end of the course, students should have finalised their project design and started collecting data.</p><p> </p><p>Since this is a student-driven workshop, its structure will evolve according to participants\u2019 needs.  Nevertheless, here is a provisional list of topics that we expect to address:</p><p>*  The well-designed proposal: asking a good question, converting it into a do-able project</p><p>*  What counts as evidence?</p><p>*  Mapping the field: using preliminary surveys, genealogies and other relationship charts</p><p>*  Using secondary sources</p><p>*  Interviewing and observing</p><p>*  Making notes, record-keeping and revising</p><p>*  Ethical concerns</p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>By the end of the course, each student shall have finalised their research proposal and made some progress towards collecting and interpreting data.</p><p> </p></div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Students will be graded on the basis of (1) the quality of their participation in the course, and on (2) timely submission of assignments.  The grade break-up is as follows:</p><p>Proposal presentation (another student\u2019s): 10%</p><p>Comments on other proposals: 20%</p><p>Revised proposal: 30%</p><p>Written assignment: 30%</p><p>Overall participation: 10%</p><p> </p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Each student is allowed up to 4 absences during the semester, as long as they inform the professor and GA in advance. Those students who are absent from a class must send written comments on the proposals that they missed discussing, by the end of the week. The comments should be added to the Classroom Stream.</p></div></div>",
