            "html_details":"<div><strong>Office timing</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Tuesday 10.10 to 11.40</p></div></div><div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Understanding structure, expression and dynamics of a genome allows us to correlate structure with function and help to find molecular correlates of different phenotypic characteristics. Recent developments of high throughput technologies have opened unprecedented level of dissecting a genome that has opened up new ways of deciphering genotype-phenotype correlation. We will expose the students to these new ways of understanding genomes and show how the genomic data can be used to understand functional features.</p><p>Lecture Schedule</p><p> </p><p>Aug 31                                   Definition and introduction to high throughput approaches to biology </p><p>                                                AB</p><p>Sept 7                                    DNA sequencing technologies                                       KMG   </p><p> </p><p>Sept 14                                 Next Generation Sequencing (NGS) and technology platforms                                                    KMG</p><p>Sept 21                                 Strategies for sequencing entire genomes                       BC</p><p>Sept 28                                 Genome assembly and annotation                      AB</p><p>Oct 5                                      Application of genomics 1: Single nucleotide variation      BC</p><p>Mid Sem Break                                 </p><p> Oct 19                                  Application of genomics 2:  Copy number variation          BC</p><p>Oct 26                                   Application of genomics 3:  Disease susceptibility and diagnosis KMG</p><p>November 2                       High throughput gene expression analysis                            KMG</p><p>November 9                       What is proteomics and basic methods                                  VF SS</p><p>November 16                     Large scale proteomics analysis, use of mass spectrometers         VF SS</p><p>November 23                     Exercises 1                                                                          BC and KMG</p><p>November 30                     Exercises 2                                                                          BC and KMG</p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Students will learn about the genomes and history of genomic analysis including some of the technologies such as Sanger sequencing, next generation sequencing (NGS) technology along with the evolution of various NGS platforms. They will be exposed to the various \u201c-omics\u201d data and its applications. Hands on training will be provided to allow students to appreciate the various applications of NGS data.</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>There is no specific textbook. We will be giving a reading list of articles along with the lectures.</p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Relative grading system</p><p>Research paper                       50%</p><p>Final exams                             50%</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>None at present</p></div></div>",
