            "html_details":"<div><strong>Office timing</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Monday, 8:30 am - 10:00 am (VA)</p><p>Wednesday, 4:30 am - 6:00 pm (DA)</p><p> </p></div></div><div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><ul><li>Structure and bonding: Ionic, Covalent, Coordinate and Hydrogen bonds, The octet rule,  Formal charge, Sigma (\u03c3-) and pi (\u03c0-) bonds,  Hybridisation, , Inductive effects, Hyperconjugation, Mesomeric effects, Steric effect,  Acidity and basicity, Acids, Bases   (DA)</li><li><p>Aromaticity: H\u00fcckel\u2019s rule and characteristics of aromatic compounds benzenoid and non-benzenoid compounds, Alternant and nonalternant hydrocarbons, Annulenes, Anti-aromaticity, Homo-aromaticity and Nomenclature of aromatic compounds.  (VA)</p></li><li>Nomenclature:  Functional groups, IUPAC Nomenclature of aliphatic organic compounds: Alkanes, Alkenes, Alkynes, Alcohols, Amines, Carboxylic acids, Ethers, Halides, and nitriles.  (DA)</li><li>Stereochemistry: Representation of stereostructures: Fischer, Newmann, and Sawhorse Projection formulae and their interconversions. (DA)</li><li>Conformational analysis: Butane and cyclohexane (mono and disubstituted) and their relative stability and energy diagrams. (DA)</li><li>Configurational analysis: Geometrical isomerism: cis\u2013trans, syn-anti, and E/Z notations with C.I.P rules. (VA)</li><li>Optical isomerism: Chirality, Enantiomers, The Cahn\u2013Ingold\u2013Prelog (R and S) nomenclature, The D and L nomenclature, Diastereoisomers (or diastereomers), Diastereoisomers,  Mesomer Racemic mixture,  resolution of racemic mixture and ee%. (VA)</li></ul><p> </p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><ol><li>Students will develop understanding about various types of bond formations. Will learn about the factors that decide the preference of one type of bonding over others and also the stability of molecules which are ionic or covalnet. Will also learn about hydrogen bonds and its importance in supramolecular systems.   </li><li>Electronic and steric factors basically control the behaviour of a molecule in any chemical reaction. A clear understanding of electronic and steric effects enables us to predict a number of chemical properties.  </li><li>Will learn the international nomeclature system for organic systems. </li><li>Will study the fact that why some system exist in a particular conformation. What makes a specific geometric arrangement more stable than the other.  </li><li>Concept of aromaticity and basic principles will be explained.</li><li>Chiral systems, enantiomers and nomenclature of chiral mole cules will be taught.</li></ol><p> </p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Suggested Reading/Books:</p><p>Organic Chemistry by Jonathan Clayden, Nick Greeves and Stuart Warren.</p><p>Advanced Organic Chemistry: Part A: Structure and Mechanisms  by Francis A. Carey  and Richard J. Sundberg.</p><p>Stereochemistry of Organic Compounds: E. L. Eliel and S. H. Willen</p><p> </p><p>Interested in studying more about atomic orbitals: Principles of Atomic Orbitals by N. N. Greenwood</p><p>  </p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Final Marking Schemne-</p><p>Assignments: 30%</p><p>Quiz: 20%</p><p>Final Exam: 50%</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>60% </p></div></div>",
