            "html_details":"<div><strong>Office timing</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Class Hours: Tuesdays 2.50 pm-4.20 pm </p><p>                                        4.30 pm-6.00 pm </p><p> </p><p>Office Hours: Wednesdays 5 pm-6 pm</p></div></div><div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>The course offers students the opportunity to engage with contemporary approaches to figure drawing through critical discourse and practical explorations. It is envisaged as a virtual studio space for deliberations into artistic visions, experiences, and wisdom that allow them to negotiate the everyday through the practice of drawing.</p><p>Students will be introduced to contemporary artistic practices that push the boundaries of excepted notions of \u2018high\u2019 art and critique hierarchies of attitude and the way value is ascribed to art. Tracing the history of figure drawing as a genre that goes back to Classical antiquity to Italian Renaissance, extending into the 18th-century French academia and the 19th century Victorian Era, students will get a broad overview of how the established notion of accuracy and idealized beauty continues to be challenged and reinvented as artists take on a variety of approaches to drawing the human figure. The idealized body is often replaced with bodies that are bruised, grotesque, and out of proportions with visible stretch marks, skin hair, wrinkles, and pigmentation. There is also a conscious shift towards drawing from memory and imagination as opposed to drawing from a live model or from photographic references. This becomes quite evident in the works of artists who choose to create monumental, site-specific drawings often laden with political commentary and emotive power.</p><p>In this course, students have the flexibility to work with both analog and digital mediums and materials in enabling them to connect to their own context, concerns, and interests with a sense of immediacy by using the human figure as a trigger.</p><p> </p><p>Framework</p><ul><li>Rethinking the body beyond a representational image, as an entity with constant trans-mutative possibilities in terms of form, functionality, and aesthetics.</li><li>Probing ideas of beauty, identity, sexuality and gender, and space-time memory in the context of the body and the human figure.</li><li>Reflecting on processes of overlapping, erasure, and incision as acts layered with emotive and intuitive sensibilities.</li></ul><p> </p><p>Course Modules</p><p>Class I: Introduction to the course -Broad overview of the assignments, readings, essential viewings, drawing materials, etc.</p><p>Class II: Finding inspiration and getting started with the process book- Digging through personal albums, archives of any kind in terms of books, magazines, posters, newspaper cuttings, etc. and collating them in the form of collages</p><p>Class III: Explaining the basics of form, composition, scale &amp; perspective and demonstrating techniques of drawing using charcoal, watercolors, and ink </p><p>Class IV: Focusing on how to work on minute details of the body parts, including head, hands, limbs, feet, and skin.</p><p>Class V: Demonstrating approaches to figure drawing, including drawing from observation, references, and memory.</p><p>Class VI: Based on the previous sessions of learning, experimenting with drawings based on memory, imagination, myth, and fantasy.Class VII: Exploring how to compose a group of figures in relation to space; creating multiples using repetition, overlap, and layers</p><p>Class VIII: Discussion on how to choose a project idea, create a framework, timeline, and sketches that explain what the final outcome is expected to be.</p><p>Class IX: Working on the various stages of the individual project</p><p>Class X: Working on the various stages of the individual project</p><p>Class XI: Discussion Review and feedback about possibilities of enhancing the works</p><p>Class XII: Discussion on how to present the work to an audience virtually</p><p>Class XIII: Project presentation and display as part of the final assessment.</p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p> </p><ol><li>Introduction to contemporary artist practices that use the human figure as a subject to address issues of racism, inequality, oppression, and power politics.</li><li>Familiarity with visual thinking approaches and techniques that overlap disciplines of creative writing, poetry, theatre, film, design, and craft.</li></ol></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Reading list</p><p>Malbert, R., &amp; Praill, S. (2016). Drawing people: The human figure in contemporary art. Thames and Hudson.</p><p>Dexter, Emma. Vitamin D: New Perspectives in Drawing. Phaidon, 2012.</p><p>Loomis, Andrew. Figure Drawing for All It's Worth. Titan Books, 2011.</p><p>Pe\u00b4rard Victor Semon, and Rune Hagman. Victor Perard's Drawing Faces and Expressions. GD/Perigee, 1983.</p><p> </p><p>Reference to artists and artworks</p><p>William Kentridge, Nine Drawings for Projection series (1989-2003)</p><p>Kiki Smith, Fountainhead (1991); The Vitreous Body (2001); and Untitled (Book of Hours) (1986)</p><p>Nalini Malani, Eros (2009); I am Everything You Lost (2016); Childhood fears (2009)</p><p>Anju Dodiya, Supernatural (2019); The Air is a Mill of Hooks (2018); Altar for erasures(2012);</p><p>Kara Walker, Gone: An Historical Romance of a Civil War as It Occurred b'tween the Dusky Thighs of One Young Negress and Her Heart (1994)<br> </p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Mid-Term Assessment: Process book-entry (80%), Class assignments (20%)</p><p>End semester Assessment: Project Presentation (80%), Project Essay (20%)</p><p>Course Deliverables: </p><ul><li>Image and video documentation of process book entries, class assignments, and the final project.</li><li>A brief essay of approx.500 words explaining the motivation, processes, ideas, and concerns involved within the project.</li></ul> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Up to four absences need no prior approval</p><p> </p></div></div>",
