            "html_details":"<div><strong>Office timing</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>We meet from 2.50-4.20 pm, every Tuesdays and Thursdays. </p></div></div><div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>What exactly does regime type (democracy/autocracy) has to do with interstate warfare? It turns out there is a body of literature, known as the Democratic Peace (hereafter DP), that focus on such issues. The DP or the absence of wars between democracies, is one of the more significant findings to have emerged within International Relations scholarship in recent decades. It has consequently attracted significant and critical attention of a large body of scholars and policy-makers alike. In this course we will examine the history of the idea, its main empirical claims, the explanations for it, the auxiliary claims and the criticisms of the research. While the methodological slant will be on quantitative research, we will also examine issues of research design as well as historical case studies as appropriate. </p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>1) Since the course is focused on one topic, the DP, students will acquire substantive knowledge about the major issues in DP research. They should be able to highlight the major works and the arguments made therein. 2) Students should be able to provide a reasoned critique of the major works. This is part of the process of learning to reason in a social scientific manner. 3) Students should gain an exposure to some of the quantitative literature on international conflict. 4) Finally, students should be able to judge the validity of the democratic peace and crucially, justify their judgment.</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>A set of asisgned readings are in Dpsace </p><p>Dspace Readings: https://bit.ly/3hNA4nO </p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Final exam                                          (25)<br>Midterm exam                                     (25)<br>Essay                                                  (25)<br>In-class quizzes                                  (10)<br>In class presentation                           (10)   <br>Class participation &amp; Attendance        (5)</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>You are expected to show up for class. You may miss three lessons, unexcused without grade penalty. Each unexcused absence beyond the third lesson will result in a 1% deduction from the final grade. As attendance may be taken at any lesson, it behooves the student to show up. Attendance also requires the student to arrive on time.   </p></div></div>",
