            "document":"",
            "html_details":"<div><strong>Office timing</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This is flexible as we are still online </p><p>If we do come back to campus for in-person classes I will have fixed timings. But for now - I am at your disposal most times of the day </p><p>Students coordinate directly with me regarding when they want to meet</p><p> </p><p>TA -- Dhruvan Nair   dhruvan.nair_ugta@ashoka.edu.in</p></div></div><div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Long form, non-fiction narrative journalism aims to develop your writing style or 'voice.'</p><p>We will learn and expose ourselves to writing techniques and execute pieces using creativity, research and reporting</p><p>Like all media studies classes, this class will focus heavily on reporting and writing for news (not literature or opinion)</p><p>Student journalists will be encouraged to develop human-interest stories which require first hand news / information gathering</p><p>We will study/ critique contemporary long form news writing in Indian and global publications</p><p>The length of submissions will be over 1,500 words and assignments will be submited on deadline. </p><p>Student journalists will be encouraged to come up with story ideas .. they will also be assigned on-going news stories which they will be asked to deep-dive into<br>Student journalists will have to do first-hand interviews for their pieces and will be asked to maintain a log of those interviews</p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Writing.</p><p>Think of this as a pure non fiction writing class with a twist. The twist being news, contemporary issues.</p><p>The 'outcome' of this class is the end of semester assignment -- which hopefully will be a publishable piece of journalism. </p><p>In the lead up to that - we will perfect our writing by writing Simple, writing Descriptive, writing with Authority, writing with Imagination &amp; writing with Honesty </p><p>We will learn about effecive interviewing, developing sources - on and off the record, incorporating sound, taste, smell into our copy.</p><p>    </p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Joan Didion's Slouching Towards Bethlehem // Ryszard Kapuscinski's Shah of Shahs // John Hershey's Hiroshima </p><p><br>These 3 books need to be read within the first month of the Semester, as there will be additional readings in between classes </p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Final Assignment  30%<br>Interview  10%<br>MidTerm Assignment  20% <br>Other writing assignments/ projects 30%<br>Attendance &amp; Participation  10% </p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Attendance &amp; participation is between 10 to 15% of your grade </p><p>Students are allowed to take two unexcused absenses, following which they will be penalised </p><p>Students who are unwell, representing Ashoka in sports, debate, drama or any other university sanctioned event are excused and expected to make up missed work and laise with the TA / colleagues about assignments, etc.</p><p>I dont require a doctor's certificate or proof that you have the 'iron lung'</p><p>I take students on their word as honest adults</p><p>I am a nice guy until I stop being a nice guy. There is always someone in the class who tries to take advantage of me and that person(s)</p><p>is never heard of again!) </p><p> </p></div></div>",
