            "document":"https://ams.ashoka.edu.in/UploadFiles/Content/ProgramCourseInfo/ES-1001[ES-1001-1]/340d76ae-7a5d-4df9-a517-9b6aaeafdd34.pdf",
            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This course introduces students to major concepts and debates in human-wildlife conflict. Because this subject is interdisciplinary, we read papers from conservation NGOs on how conservation priorities are decided, from ecologists on the mechanism of conservation from the animals' perspective and an understanding of the ecosystem, from social scientists on understanding human perspectives and we also read about possible solutions. In selecting readings, I try and cover every type of conflict schenario.</p><p>Two caveats, though:</p><p>1. This course does privelege the \"wild\" animal. Domestic animals will only figure in the course as prey or if they have a negative impact on the \"wild\" animals. </p><p>2. Although every perspective in this conflict is valid and important, we will be focusing on how these influence the conservation of the \"wild\" animal. </p><p>Students also have to write a final literature review that investigates one aspect of human wildlife conflict for a significant proportion of the grade. Otherwise class is structured as following:</p><p>1. Readings every class where students have to post their comments on the discussion board</p><p>2. We then discuss paper and its larger significance in class. </p><p>By the end of the class, you should have a fairly broad understanding of conservation studies and human wildlife conflict as well as niche understanding on the sub-topic of your choice (last year, the course led to 2 students developing a theoretical economic model for reducing collusion in compensation schemes, 1 student investigating role of fire on herps, one student looking at role of nature programs on conservation, one on whether aesthetic values biased conservation, 1 on subsidies for small holders to transition to wildlife friendly agriculture, 1 on reasons for cannibalism in polar bears, etc etc). All disciplines welcome. </p><p>PFA a tentative syllabus attached. But you can also consult students from last year on the course. </p></div></div><div><strong>Attachment</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><table><tbody><tr><td><a style=\"color:blue\" href=\"https://ams.ashoka.edu.in/UploadFiles/Content/ProgramCourseInfo/ES-1001[ES-1001-1]/340d76ae-7a5d-4df9-a517-9b6aaeafdd34.pdf\" download=\"Human Wildlife Conflict Syllabus (1).pdf\">Human Wildlife Conflict Syllabus (1).pdf</a></td></tr></tbody></table></div></div>",
