            "html_details":"<div><strong>Office timing</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Faculty: Alok Bhattacharya (AB), Department of Biology</p><p>alok.bhattacharya@ashoka.edu.in</p><p> </p><p>L.S. Shashidhara  (LSS), Department of Biology,</p><p>ls.shashidhara@ashoka.edu.in</p></div></div><div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Science entails systematic pursuit of knowledge, which essentially involves unbiased observations and multiple methods of validation. Science gives us the ability to understand how our world works and how we interact with our physical surroundings. It not only incorporates basic ideas and theories about how our universe behaves but it also provides a framework for learning more and tackling new questions and concerns that come our way. Science also provides an unparalleled view of the order and symmetry of the universe and its workings\u2014subatomic particles to the never-ending space. Science enables you to integrate with your surroundings, both living and non-living. It has also given us the tools to alter living and non-living things. It has the potential to have both positive impacts such as coping with natural disasters, curing diseases, and discovering new sources of energy, as well as negative impacts in the form of climate change and weapons of mass destruction.<br><br>The course narrates some of the key theoretical and technical developments in the evolution of the sciences and offers a synoptic view of the development of concepts that drive modern science.</p><p> </p><p>Lecture schedule</p><p>Aug 31:           What is Science 1                                           AB</p><p>Sept 2:             What is Science 2                                           LSS</p><p> </p><p>Sept 7:             Is it possible for robots to be scientists?         AB</p><p>Sept 9:             Science in History                                           AB</p><p> </p><p>Sept 14:           Ethics and practice of modern science            AB     </p><p>Sept 16:           Scientific and Technological foundations</p><p>of modern Astronomy                                     AB</p><p> </p><p>Sept 21:           Newton and classical mechanics                     AB</p><p>Sept 23:           Understanding Atom and birth of modern</p><p>chemistry                                                         AB</p><p>           </p><p>Sept 28:           Atoms in combination: Materials and</p><p>transformation                                                 AB</p><p>Sept 30:           Electricity, magnetism and industrial</p><p>revolution                                                        AB</p><p>           </p><p>Oct 5:              Science, Technology, and communication     AB</p><p>Oct 7:              Properties of light and quantum mechanics   AB</p><p> </p><p>Mid semester break</p><p> </p><p>Oct 19:            What is life                                                     LSS</p><p>Oct 21:            Study of Life Before Mendel</p><p>and Darwin                                                     LSS</p><p> </p><p>Oct 26:            Mendel and understanding heredity               LSS</p><p>Oct 28:            Tracing Abstract concepts to genes to            LSS</p><p>discovery of DNA as genetic material</p><p> </p><p>Nov 2:             Natural selection, evolution, and generation</p><p>of diversity on Earth                                                   LSS</p><p>Nov 4:             Great Synthesis: Genetics, Evolution,</p><p>Cell theory and chemistry of life                    LSS</p><p> </p><p>Nov 9:             Origin life                                                       LSS</p><p>Nov11:            Human evolution: concepts of                        LSS</p><p>cognition and consciousness     </p><p> </p><p>Nov 16:           Chance and randomness in Biological,</p><p>Chemical and physical world                        LSS/AB         </p><p>Nov 18:           Science and technology of Energy                 AB</p><p> </p><p>Nov 23:           Climate Science and impact of climate         </p><p>change on biosphere                                       AB</p><p>Nov 25:           The Earth and the Cosmos                              AB</p><p> </p><p>Nov 30:           Interdisciplinarity and integrative science     AB</p><p>Dec 2:              Future of Science                                            LSS</p><p> </p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>An understanding of the methods and approach to science, how major concepts and technologies were developed, the ethics of science and where science is heading. The course pans different disciplines of science.</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>References for LSS\u2019s lectures</p><p> </p><p>https://explorebiology.org</p><p>https://www.ibiology.org</p><p>https://www.pearson.com/us/higher-education/series/Campbell-Biology-Series/2244849.html</p><p> </p><p>References for AB\u2019s lectures</p><p> </p><p>https://www.bookdepository.com/Brief-History-Science-Thomas-Crump/9781841195520</p><p>https://1lib.in/book/2708514/3661fa?id=2708514&amp;secret=3661fa</p><p>https://archive.org/details/scienceinhistory03bern</p><p>https://www.discovermagazine.com/technology/the-robot-scientists-are-coming-but-thats-not-a-bad-thing</p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Evaluation/Grading</p><p> </p><p>Quiz/short writeups:               20%</p><p>Papers/experiments:                20</p><p>Mid-semester:                         30%</p><p>End semester:                          30%</p><p>Relative grading system will be followed.</p><p> </p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>None at present</p></div></div>",
