            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This is an introductory course intended for students who want to learn the basics of<br>programming. No prior programming experience is expected, though it helps to be<br>\"computer literate\". We will delve into computational thought and the principles which<br>underlie modern programming, including rudimentary complexity theory. We will also<br>explore the history and evolution of current computation and the internet. Students will<br>learn how to write simple code in and express algorithms in the form of pseudocode. In<br>terms of algorithms, we will start with some sorting and searching, as well as a number of<br>useful computational tools and techniques. After these basics, we will learn about image<br>and sound processing, and (if physical classes happen) working with hardware.</p><p>A general outline of the topics we will cover:</p><p><br>History of Computation<br>    Ancient history<br>    Approaches across civilizations<br>    Before 1900; looms, etc.<br>    Early and mid 20th Century (lighting systems and World Wars)<br>    Recent history<br>    Current happenings</p><p>What is computer science?<br>    The study of processes<br>    Detour: Binary<br>    Logic and gates (basics)<br>    Truth tables<br>    Analog computation<br>    Computer languages and pseudocode<br>    Reading and writing<br>    What are algorithms?<br>    Limits of computation and basics of complexity theory</p><p>Puzzle Solving<br>    Representing puzzles mathematically<br>    Procedural and functional thinking<br>    Classes of techniques<br>    Inherent complexity? (or stupid solvers)<br>    Big-O Notation<br>    Composing (or adding) puzzles</p><p>Understanding intelligence and automated decisionmaking<br>    Historical conceptualization of intelligence<br>    Current understanding and experiments<br>    Analysis and decisionmaking<br>    Vehicles and assumptions of agency<br>    Paradoxes and illusions (details later)</p><p>Abstraction and Encapsulation<br>    Representing problems<br>    Precise solutions<br>    Real-world examples and issues<br>    Complexity flashback<br>    Sequential, random, and other kinds of access to information</p><p>Simple programs and structures (with visualization; Python + Turtle)<br>    Conditionals and branching<br>    Loops<br>    Repeated procedures (spirals etc.)<br>    Arrays<br>    Functions<br>    \"Clever\" Code<br>    Recursion (Square roots, Hanoi)</p><p>Visualization<br>    Basics of representing data in 2D<br>    Zooming in or out<br>    Distorting shapes<br>    Dealing with colours<br>    Shapes (spirals redux, polygons, grids, epicycloids)<br>    Graphs<br>    Fractals (Mandelbrot, Julia, Sierpinski, infinite wallpaper)</p><p>Lots of recursion<br>    Recursion<br>    Even more recursion<br>    (See above)</p><p>Sorting and Searching<br>    Linear Search<br>    Binary Search (also a quick mention of BSTs)<br>    Selection Sort<br>    Insertion Sort<br>    Quick Sort</p><p>Randomization<br>    Logistic Map (with animation)<br>    Monte Carlo<br>    Sierpinski redux (and similar curves)<br>    What does \"random\" even mean?<br>    Bertrand Paradox</p><p>Sculpture<br>    Embodying computation<br>    Origami<br>    Optical and other illusions</p><p>Audio Manipulation<br>    Representing sounds<br>    Stretching and squeezing<br>    Characteristics: Treble, Bass, etc. (&lt;- we might not cover this, depending on average expertise/comfort with music and math)<br>    Cutting, repeating, modifying beats</p><p>Image Manipulation<br>    Representing images<br>    Dealing with colour<br>    Synthesizing new images<br>    Convolutions and kernels<br>    Edge detection, sharpening, blurring, etc.</p><p>-----</p><p>Some optional topics (IF we have time):<br>    Anti-buzzwording: AI, Blockchains, etc.<br>    Karnaugh maps<br>    Some basic data structures<br>    Graph theory<br>    Game theory (tic-tac-toe)</p><p> </p><p> </p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>You will learn the basics of computational thinking and gain a rudimentary understanding<br>of computer programming.</p><p> </p><p>Note: If you already possess some coding ability, and want to improve, or to start coding<br>more seriously in a principled manner, please take the \"Introduction to Computer<br>Programming\" (CS 101) course offered in the spring. This course is not a replacement for<br>101. This is an FC, intended for general audiences; 101 is more intensive, and meant for<br>people who are considering a CS major.</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>None. We will provide all reading materials, books etc.</p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Two exams, at least four HWs, and a \"puzzle day\" event.</p><p>Exam 1 = 25%<br>Exam 2 = 25%<br>HWs (total) = 30%<br>Puzzle Day = 20%</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>None. I will provide recordings, but people who miss out on live classes usually do not do well.</p></div></div>",
