            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>The goal of this class is to present students with access to advanced lectures on emotion, memory and cognition. Broadly divided into three modules, the lectures will be delivered by Dr. Bhismadev Chakrabarti, Dr. Narayanan Srinivasan, and Dr. Shona Chatterjee. </p><p> </p><p>The 3 lecture series by Dr. Bhismadev Chakrabarti will be on the key concepts in emotion and empathy, going into their definitional histories, and introducing theoretical debates around these terms. An important  distinction between first person vs second person aspects of emotional neuroscience will be explored. The second person approach, which will be explored by Dr. Chakrabarti, involves the observer understanding another person's emotions; while emotional understanding and cognition from the first person perspective will be delved into by Dr. Srinivasan. Moving further, the course will investigate empathy and emotional processing in non-human animals, particularly through rodent models, and then in non-human primates\u2014 does the chimpanzee have a theory of mind? Again, students will learn about several theoretical debates around the theory of mind in primates. The course will then shift its focus on humans; the developmental perspectives of emotion and empathy, and subsequently in adults with and without psychopathological conditions. </p><p> </p><p>Dr. Shona Chattarji will then steer the course towards a neuroscientific approach, on the ways in which emotion and memory are connected, and the neural basis of emotionally charged memory, memory consolidation under stress, and PTSD. Dr. Srinivasan\u2019s module will focus largely on the themes of cognition and emotion, exposing students to a range of topics within cognition. He will deal with emotion-cognition interactions, emotions and attention, emotions and memory, emotions and decision making. He will then move on to talking about emotion regulation: the process model of emotion regulation, different strategies used in emotion regulation, the neuroscience of emotion regulation, mindfulness/meditation and emotion regulation.</p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p> </p><p>The main expectation of students is that they bring their ideas of what they would want to learn to the course, participate in shaping it, pay full attention in class, and genuinely engage with discussions and presentations. </p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Class material (slides, readings, assignments) will be available on Google Classroom; alternatively, this material can be accessed via Google Drive as well. Classes will be recorded and uploaded for your convenience. The professors will provide necessary and recommended readings during the course, which will be made available to you in an accessible format. </p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This course will have three grading components as follows:</p><p>Academic Integrity/Attendance/Class Participation (10%): Your participation in class or even by email or over Google Classroom will count towards this 10%. Your attendance counts as part of your participation grade.<br>Student Presentation (40%): Students will each be given a prompt related to the course themes; you will have class presentations towards the end of this course (10 mins presentation + 10 mins Q&amp;A and discussion = 20 mins) which will be graded by faculty members across the department. These presentations will be open to the department, and grades will be averaged across the inputs from faculty who are grading presentations - the reason we will have multiple faculty grading this is because your topics may span a range that covers multiple areas of faculty specialization.<br>Two MCQ quizzes (25% each): These will be administered over the duration of the course to test conceptual knowledge of what is taught. </p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This course will have three grading components as follows:</p><p>Academic Integrity/Attendance/Class Participation (10%): Your participation in class or even by email or over Google Classroom will count towards this 10%. Your attendance counts as part of your participation grade.<br>Student Presentation (40%): Students will each be given a prompt related to the course themes; you will have class presentations towards the end of this course (10 mins presentation + 10 mins Q&amp;A and discussion = 20 mins) which will be graded by faculty members across the department. These presentations will be open to the department, and grades will be averaged across the inputs from faculty who are grading presentations - the reason we will have multiple faculty grading this is because your topics may span a range that covers multiple areas of faculty specialization.<br>Two MCQ quizzes (25% each): These will be administered over the duration of the course to test conceptual knowledge of what is taught. </p></div></div>",
