            "html_details":"<div><strong>Office timing</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Friday noon-1pm</p></div></div><div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><h3>Course title: Introduction to Mathematical Thinking<br><br>Course description:</h3><p>Some of humankind\u2019s most powerful and beautiful ideas live in Mathematics. This ancient and most human of disciplines also happens to be the ideal arena in which to gain experience in both analytical thinking as well as creative problem solving -- these twin aspects of mathematics are what will drive this course. The topics we will choose to work with will not require any technical background \u2013 you will be given all the tools you need. During this course, you will develop a set of broadly useful problem solving strategies and gain experience in making rigorous arguments while encountering landmark ideas. Among other things, we will look at the existence of non-rational lengths, the foundation of calculus, and Cantor\u2019s set theory -- ideas that we take for granted today but which represent some of the \"great works\" of our collective intellectual history.<br><br>A sampling of topics we will cover:<br>The notion of infinity<br>Graph theory<br>A new look at induction<br>Symmetries and an introduction to algebra<br>Some ideas from probability</p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><h3>In this course the goals are to:</h3><h3><br>Develop a set of broadly useful problem solving skills and strategies</h3><p>These include strategies such as first addressing a simplified version of the question, examining extreme cases, making conjectures in the absence of solutions and the like. More broadly, you will gain experience with struggling with an unyielding problem, treating mistakes and false starts as essential, and being flexible, creative and persistent.</p><h3><br>Gain experience in critical and analytical thinking</h3><p>Mathematics trains us to always ask and answer the question, \u201cHow do we know that?\u201d You will be expected to make clear arguments of your own, and to analyse the arguments of others.</p><h3><br>Encounter some of history\u2019s landmark ideas</h3><p>Over the course of these sessions, we will look at, among other things, the existence of non-rational lengths, the foundation of calculus, and Cantor\u2019s set theory. We take all of these for granted today, but they were all radical ideas in their time. This course aims to give you at least a glimpse of some of these \u201cgreat works\u201d.</p><p> </p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>None</p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Evaluation<br>Your grade will have three components:<br><br>Assignments: 40%<br>You will have a problem set to turn in every couple of weeks. I understand that you may want to work on them collaboratively, and that is absolutely fine. However you are to write up your work by yourself.<br>Quizzes: 40%<br>There will be regular short, simple quizzes, based on the classwork and problem sets. They will not be announced. They may take place in the DS. Please note that there will be no make-ups for individual missed quizzes, though we may hold a couple of extra optional quizzes at some point. I understand that some of you may have to miss a quiz or 2 for some reason, and so we will drop the 2 lowest or missing quizzes from your total. Please note: you are expected to be present in the class, and if you have joined a zoom class mysteriously at the very moment a quiz was announced, or have done it while not in the class, it won't be counted.<br>Final evaluation: 20%</p><p>Here is how letter grades will be assigned:</p><p>90 and up: A</p><p>80 and up: B</p><p>70 and up: C</p><p>50 and up: D</p><p>Below 50: F</p><p>Pluses and minuses as well as borderline cases will be at my discretion.</p><p> </p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>I expect you to attend all classes. However I understand that there will be times when you are unable to attend, for whatever reason. At such times you do not need to inform me. However if you are going to be absent for a number of sessions, please do let me know.</p></div></div>",
