            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This course \u2013 required of interdisciplinary majors in English and Performing Arts \u2013 explores the social phenomenon of performance and its theoretical value to the humanities. It investigates the historical context within which performance studies emerged in the late-twentieth century and traces its disciplinary development through early twenty-first century. The course will focus on three recurring themes in performance studies: the relationship between representation and performance, the paradigm of performativity, and the debate between whether performance is an ephemeral or enduring phenomenon. Moreover, in reading these theories alongside Indian theoretical and performance texts, this course decenters the U.S.-focussed history of performance studies and investigates how this discipline can engage with non-Western cultures.</p></div></div>",
