            "html_details":"<div><strong>Office timing</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Tuesday 11.50am-1:20pm</p><p>Friday 11.50am-1:20pm</p></div></div><div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Have you ever visited a keymaker? You must have seen lots of premade keys with unique shapes and sizes. However, only certain keys might work for a particular lock. But what makes a particular key functional, not the others? It entirely depends on the structural features of the key. Similarly, in biology, we have thousands of such keys for specific locks that mediate numerous biological functions. This course will discuss how these biological keys or biomolecules are structured for their specific functions. Through this journey, we will ask some of these questions:</p><p> </p><ul><li>What is the molecular basis of biomolecular structures: size-shape-stability?</li><li>Atomic and molecular understanding of biomolecular complexity</li><li>Why so many players? Thousands of structure-based molecular keys in cell function</li><li>Structured, unstructured/disordered biomolecules, and polymorphism</li><li>Ordered vs disordered biomolecules, a sweet balance between life and death </li><li>How does structure define a biomolecular function? Understanding the molecular basis of sensory organs</li><li>What can go wrong if the structure becomes defective? A story of cell dysfunction to disease state.</li><li>Effects of genetic disorders in biomolecular structural defects. How do we restore them?</li></ul></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Students will acquire a fundamental understanding of the molecular basis and dependency of biomolecular structures and functions. We will walk you through a multidisciplinary approach to understand the atomic and molecular level understanding of biomolecular architecture and its role in stability, diversity, and function. We will discuss how to utilize the molecular understanding of biologics in solving various genetic and epigenetic diseases. Students will also be introduced to the possibility of the structure-based functional aspect in synthetic biology and synthetic life.</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Reading materials and class notes will be provided during the lectures.</p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Class participation: 20</p><p>Assignments: 30</p><p>Test 1: 25</p><p>Test 2: 25</p><p>Test 3: 25</p><p>(best two scores out of 3)</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>80% attendance </p></div></div>",
