            "html_details":"<div><strong>Office timing</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Course coordinators: Nayanjot Lahiri, Department of History</p><p>                                    Email: nayanjot.lahiri@ashoka.edu.in</p><p>                                    Alok Bhattacharya, Department of Biology</p><p>                                    Email: alok.bhattacharya@ashoka.edu.in</p><p>Faculty support:        Kritika Garg, Department of Biology</p><p>                                    Email: kritika.garg@ashoka.edu.in</p></div></div><div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This is a course where archaeology and science meet in order to learn about the human past from the relics of past activities. These relics range from the garbage that people have generated as they have lived their daily lives to deliberate constructions like temples and fortifications.  Extraction of information from archaeological data and sites requires the ingenuity of modern science ranging from dating techniques and experimental methods to analysing small samples of biological remains in unprecedented detail. </p><p>Lecture schedule</p><p> </p><p>3rd September              Methods, theories and practice of archaeology         </p><p>Nayanjot Lahiri, Ashoka University</p><p> </p><p>10th September            Biological, chemical and physical principles of understanding past material</p><p>                                    Alok Bhattacharya, Ashoka University</p><p> </p><p>17th September           Theoretical and methodological approaches towards the study of prehistoric sites in India</p><p>                                    Shanti Pappu, Sharma Centre for Heritage Education, Chennai</p><p> </p><p>24th September            Approaches towards the study of lithics in prehistory</p><p>Kumar Akhilesh, Sharma Centre for Heritage Education, Chennai</p><p> </p><p>Age determination in Archeology</p><p>Ashok Singhvi, National Physical Laboratory, Ahmedabad</p><p> </p><p>Floral analysis in archaeology</p><p>Using diatoms in archaeology based on various cases studies</p><p>Karthick Balasubramanian Agarkar Research Institute (Pune)</p><p> </p><p>Nayanjot Lahiri, Ashoka University</p><p>29th October                Remote-sensing and geophysical-survey techniques for studying landscapes</p><p>                                    M.B. Rajani (NIAS, Bengaluru)</p><p> </p><p>5th November                    Consumption, production and exchange of food in early food producing cultures with special reference to Ganga Plain</p><p>                                    Rakesh Tiwari (Retired Director-General, ASI, New Delhi)</p><p> </p><p>12th November            Production and exchange of artefacts in Harappan civilisation</p><p>                                    VN. Prabhakar (IIT, Gandhinagar, Ahmedabad)</p><p> </p><p>19th November            Consumption, production and exchange of food in Harappan civilisation</p><p>                                    Akshyeta Suryanarayan</p><p> </p><p>November 26</p><p>using DNA sequencing</p><p>                                    K. Thangaraj ( CDFD, Hyderabad)</p><p> </p><p>3rd December               DNA extraction and sequence analysis: Practical demonstration</p><p>                                    Kritika Garg, Alok Bhattacharya, Ashoka University</p><p> </p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>One would be able to answer the following questions.</p><p>What is the history of archaeological science? How has it helped in studying past environments and landscapes?  How does palaeobotany study the human use of plants? Why is it necessary to understand archaeogenetics as a tool for recovering the lives and lineages of past people?  These are some of the important questions that archaeology and science can help answer in order to develop a coherent view of past human societies.</p></div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Evaluation system</p><p>Quiz1                           25%</p><p>Quiz2                           25%</p><p>Research paper           50%</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>None at present</p></div></div>",
