            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Distributed computing systems, by definition, involve a multitude of computing agents \u2013 often distributed over different geographic locations \u2013 connected by means of a communication network. Distributed computing is concerned with leveraging the presence of multiple computing entities \u2013 and thus more computing power \u2013 to solve various computing problems. However, as Spiderman\u2019s uncle famously said once, \u201cWith great power, comes great responsibilities.\u201d That\u2019s especially true for distributed systems. With the separation and independence that follows the presence of more than one computing system, arise the issues of communication and coordination. Unlike sequential computing, where we are primarily worried about time complexity and space complexity, in distributed computing, we also have to take these issues into account. This makes it a tricky \u2013 but highly interesting \u2013 subject of study.<br><br>In this course, we will primarily focus on distributed network algorithms. In distributed network algorithms, the different computing agents are modeled as nodes of a graph and they are connected via edges of that graph. Rather than studying any domain-specific problems, we will study fundamental problems that arise as basic building boxes in most areas of distributed computing.<br><br>The course will be divided into three parts. In the first part, we will talk about different models of distributed computing. We will discuss information dissemination algorithms such as broadcast, convergecast. We will look at how to construct a BFS tree in a distributed manner, and so on. We will conclude this section with a study of the shortest path problem in the distributed setting.<br><br>The second part of the course will focus on the distributed minimum spanning tree problem and the distributed leader election problem. Note that the leader election problem can also be thought of as a global \"symmetry breaking\" problem.</p><p>The third part of the course will focus on various local \u201csymmetry breaking\u201d problems such as independent set and coloring.</p><p><br>NOTE:<br> </p><ol><li>This course is intended to supplement, not supplant, a course on distributed systems.<br> </li><li>This course will be useful mostly to those students who wish to pursue doctoral study and research in the following research area: \"the theory of distributed computing systems.\"</li></ol></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>After successfully completing this course, students will have a preliminary understanding of<br> </p><ol><li>how distributed computing systems are modeled,</li><li>how distributed algorithms are designed and analyzed,</li><li>what the fundamental algorithmic problems in distributed computing are,</li><li>how the structure of the network graph affects the performance of distributed algorithms,</li></ol><p><br>and so on.</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Primary reading material: The textbook \"Distributed Network Algorithms\" by Gopal Pandurangan. The textbook is available for free on his website: <a href=\"https://sites.google.com/site/gopalpandurangan/dna\">https://sites.google.com/site/gopalpandurangan/dna</a>.<br><br>Secondary reading materials:<br> </p><ol><li>Distributed Algorithms (by Nancy Lynch): <a href=\"https://www.elsevier.com/books/distributed-algorithms/lynch/978-1-55860-348-6\">https://www.elsevier.com/books/distributed-algorithms/lynch/978-1-55860-348-6</a>.<br> </li><li>Distributed Computing: A Locality-Sensitive Approach (by David Peleg): <a href=\"https://epubs.siam.org/doi/book/10.1137/1.9780898719772\">https://epubs.siam.org/doi/book/10.1137/1.9780898719772</a>.</li></ol><p><br>Students will not be expected to have access to the secondary reading materials, considering that they are prohibitively expensive. But if somehow a student manages to get access to any of these two books, then it is highly recommended that they try to take advantage of it. Each of these books is a classic and provides a rigorous treatment of the subject matter.</p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Each part of the course will have its own exam. There will be intermittent problem sets meant to serve as assignments. The different evaluation components will contribute the following proportions to your total score:<br> </p><ul><li>Three sectional exams \u2013 20% each</li><li>The assignments (combined) \u2013 40%</li></ul><p><br>The assignments will be, for the most part, algorithmic problems. It is important that you are already familiar with describing algorithms \u2013 precisely and concisely \u2013 in English or in pseudocode. You should also be comfortable with mathematically analyzing the performance of algorithms. We will not run computer programs (although interested students are welcome to do so at home) to verify the correctness of an algorithm or to measure its performance. We will prove an algorithm\u2019s correctness and mathematically derive bounds on its performance. Thus there will be plenty of mathematical writing to do, but no coding, in this course.</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>None.</p></div></div>",
