            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>An important feature of mental states, such as beliefs, desires, and experiences, is that they can be about, or represent, things in the world. For example, Mary\u2019s belief that the cat is on the mat is about a cat, intuitively, and represents the world as being such that this cat has a certain property, namely being on the mat. The power of minds or mental states to represent things in the world is known as intentionality. Despite its central place within the philosophy of mind, intentionality raises a number of puzzles closely connected to other areas of philosophy, including the philosophy of language, metaphysics, epistemology, and the philosophy of mathematics. For example, there are numerous puzzles related to what is known as singular thought, or thoughts about a particular thing. Consider the thought that Pegasus does not exist, for instance. This thought is about Pegasus, apparently, and so presupposes the existence of Pegasus. Yet the thought is true only if Pegasus does not exist. Or consider that John can seemingly believe that Mark Twain is a famous author without also believing that Samuel Clemens is a famous author, even though \u2018Mark Twain\u2019 and \u2018Samuel Clemens\u2019 name the same person. Or consider that we can seemingly have singular thoughts about abstract objects: our knowledge that 3 = 2 + 1 is about the number 3, intuitively. How is this possible, if numbers exist outside of space and time? The purpose of this course is to survey intentionality, its place within the philosophy of mind, and the various puzzles it raises. The course should be of interest to anyone interested in the philosophy of mind, philosophy of language, metaphysics, epistemology, philosophy of mathematics, and perhaps logic (though to a lesser extent). </p><p> </p></div></div>",
