            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Have you ever jumped in terror upon mistaking a rope for a snake? Have you ever been puzzled by a discovery that what you thought you knew for sure turned out to be a disastrous misconception? On every step we are bound to make mistakes, question our beliefs, and experience doubts, and yet it seems that sometimes we do know something and somehow manage in this world. In classical India, the attempts to understand the sources and validity of our knowledge grew into impressive epistemological traditions, such as Nyaya and the epistemological school of Buddhism. In fact, all philosophical schools in India developed their own theories of knowledge, in line with the fundamental presuppositions of these schools. In this course we will discuss some of the central topics in epistemology in classical India, such as perception, inference, and reliable testimony, as well as skeptical challenges, theories of truth and mistaken cognitions. As we will see, some of these debates have parallels in Western philosophy, and Indian theories have much to offer to contemporary epistemological thought.</p><p><strong>offered by</strong>: Visiting Professor Dimitry Shevchenko; mailto: <strong>dima812000@yahoo.com</strong></p></div></div>",
