            "document":"https://ams.ashoka.edu.in/UploadFiles/Content/ProgramCourseInfo/SAN-2006/ENG-2406[SAN-2006/ENG-2406-1]/825e58b0-92f7-4bea-bd9b-0648ddfc2e10.pdf",
            "html_details":"<div><strong>Office timing</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Class timing:</p><p>Mondays and Wednesdays  2.50-4.20 PM</p><p>Office Hours</p><p>Tuesdays 1.00 \u2013 4.00 PM. Please write me an email and make an appointment.</p></div></div><div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This course does not expect any linguistic access in Sanskrit. Using translations, we will survey the treatment of the human figure in Sanskrit literature \u2013 from the Epics, poetry and plays, even religious stotras. We will make occasional excursions into Prakrit, Tamil and other literatures. Through a close reading of the selections we will try and do the following. One, we will note the cultural semiotics and poetic topoi that cluster around each body part, and how these change over place, time and language. Further, we will see how this toolkit of standard comparata and allusions for the human body intensifies and magnifies within kavya literature \u2013 constituting the very body of Classical Sanskrit poetry, as it were. Finally, we will look at the aesthetic roles of these bodily descriptions, and how Sanskrit poetry and theatre take the body as a locus of thought and feeling as much  (or perhaps more) than they do the mind-heart. Towards the end of the course we will see a ku?iya??am dancer\u2019s interpretation of the classical body.</p><p> </p><p>What is expected of you</p><p>Students will be expected to read the translations and any prescribed secondary readings in advance. In the class we will map the figures and allusions and track their synergistic interactions. Students are expected to collectively outline the historical trends in the thematisation of the body in  kavya literature \u2013 while tracing the interaction between poetic traditions.</p><p>Syllabus</p><p>Text selections, translations and secondary readings will be shared through the LMS.</p><p> </p></div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>  Attendance</p><p>10%</p><p>Class Participation</p><p>25%</p><p>Class presentation</p><p>25%</p><p>Assignments</p><p>15%</p><p>Final Essay</p><p>25%</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attachment</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><table><tbody><tr><td><a style=\"color:blue\" href=\"https://ams.ashoka.edu.in/UploadFiles/Content/ProgramCourseInfo/SAN-2006/ENG-2406[SAN-2006/ENG-2406-1]/825e58b0-92f7-4bea-bd9b-0648ddfc2e10.pdf\" download=\"Monsoon2021_CourseOutline_Body_Poetic_in_Sanskrit_Kavya.pdf\">Monsoon2021_CourseOutline_Body_Poetic_in_Sanskrit_Kavya.pdf</a></td></tr></tbody></table></div></div>",
