            "html_details":"<div><strong>Office timing</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Class timing:</p><p>Mondays and Wednesdays 10.10- 11.40 AM </p><p>Office Hours </p><p>Tuesdays 9.00 AM to noon. Please write me an email and make an appointment.</p><p> </p></div></div><div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This course presupposes a basic understanding of Sanskrit grammar, and is recommended for students who have completed Beginners Sanskrit I (formerly Sanskrit 1001). Students who haven\u2019t taken Beginners Sanskrit I should contact the instructor before August 15th 2021 for an assessment. </p><p>In Intermediate Sanskrit I, we will read from one of the best-travelled specimens of narrative literature in Sanskrit \u2013 the Pa\u00f1catantra. Composed sometime before the 6th century CE, it is an accessible sample of natural Sanskrit prose peppered with the occasional verse. The language is idiomatic and the syntax is uncomplicated, making it a suitable text for developing practice one\u2019s  Sanskrit reading skills. We will read the selections closely, and no word will be left untranslated.  Further, we will use the text as a springboard to discuss topics in Sanskrit grammar in an inductive fashion. We will study some elementary concepts of Sanskrit poetics and metrics as well. By occasionally reading from a (Devanagari) Pa\u00f1catantra manuscript, we will develop our abilities at interpreting unpunctuated handwritten texts. </p><p>What is expected of you :</p><p>We will be reading the textual extracts closely. Students will be expected to prepare the assigned portion of the text in advance, and will take turns translating and interpreting the selections in class. Turn by turn, students will give a brief synopsis of the narrative from the last session at the beginning of every class.</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Syllabus </p><p>In Monsoon 2021, we will read the Preface (Kathamukha), Book 1 ( Mitrabheda) and Book 3  (Kakolukiyam) from Franklin Edgerton\u2019s 1930 edition of the Pa\u00f1catantra.</p><p> </p><p> </p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Attendance </p><p>10%</p><p>Class Participation </p><p>20%</p><p>Homework </p><p>25%</p><p>Tests and Quizzes </p><p>20%</p><p>Final Examination </p><p>25%</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attachment</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><table><tbody><tr><td><a style=\"color:blue\" href=\"https://ams.ashoka.edu.in/UploadFiles/Content/ProgramCourseInfo/SAN-2001[SAN-2001-1]/df3206d7-d067-41b8-90da-ecb2b35f2715.pdf\" download=\"Monsoon2021_CourseOutline_IntermediateSanskrit_I_Pancatantra.pdf\">Monsoon2021_CourseOutline_IntermediateSanskrit_I_Pancatantra.pdf</a></td></tr></tbody></table></div></div>",
