            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><span style=\"font-family:georgia,serif;\">Taught by Punita G. Singh</span></p><p> </p><p><span style=\"font-family:georgia,serif;\">This course focuses on temporal aspects of music from an interdisciplinary perspective. Intuitive human tendencies like entrainment and beat induction have led to most music adhering to a cyclical meter with a regular pulse, but creativity and cultural propensities produce artistic variants that enrich the musical universe. Some genres of music create hierarchical metrical structures. Some displace or layer sound sequences to create syncopation and polyrhythms. Some build up compound rhythms from simpler patterns, while some dispense with a temporal scaffold altogether. The use of instruments to create rhythm patterns or mark time also varies across cultures. Drawing on concepts in music as well as anthropology, cognitive neuropsychology, literature and physics, the impulse to perceive and produce rhythm is explored and experienced through attentive listening and performance activities.</span></p></div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><font face=\"georgia, serif\">Grading for all co-curricular courses is based on attendance and class participation.</font></p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><span style=\"font-family:georgia,serif;\">Unexcused absences will affect the student's grade.</span></p></div></div>",
