            "document":"",
            "html_details":"<div><strong>Office timing</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Tues     10:10 \u2013 11:40 am</p><p>Thurs   10:10 \u2013 11:40 am</p></div></div><div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This course will introduce you to some common statistical techniques used by scientists to answer questions of ecological or conservation relevance. Throughout the course, you will learn how to quantify the states of ecological systems (e.g., population size, body size of a bird population); and assess drivers of ecological patterns (e.g., is butterfly movement dependent on temperature, influence of forest cover on tiger presence).</p><p>You will learn how to manage, analyse and visualise ecological data. The class will be hands-on, and involve practical worksheets. Throughout, we will link learnings to ecological questions. We will start with simple quantifications, and build complexity as we advance along this course.</p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>At the end of the course, you should be able to:</p><p>1) Input, and manage your data in R<br>2) Summarize and visualize your data<br>3) Construct simple statistical models that incorporate both deterministic and stochastic components (i.e., a structural model, and uncertainty)<br>4) Conduct simple analyses in R<br>5) Know how to select amongst your different models and make inference based on model output.</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>We will use open-source software R and RStudio. Basic knowledge of these software is not necessary, but will be advantageous.</p><p>All students need to have a computer with R (https://cran.r-project.org/) and RStudio (https://www.rstudio.com/) installed. R and RStudio work on Windows, Mac and Ubuntu.</p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Assignments    \u2013 80%</p><p>Group Project \u2013 20%</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Students are expected to attend all classes. </p></div></div>",
