            "html_details":"<div><strong>Office timing</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>TTh:3-4pm or by appointment</p></div></div><div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>The course will focus on a general development of the renrmalization group (RG) as a systematic way to explore the large scale ``emergent'' behaviour of different types of systems.   Technical aspects of RG will be discussed by considering specific cases,  like, polymers, quantum systems, and  critical phenomena.   The approach taken will help us  to see how  RG can lead to a proper<br>description of a system, avoiding any prior knowledge of its phenomenology.<br>We shall start with the real space RG, and then go over to various avatars of the  field theoretic<br>RG.</p><p>Special topics would include functioonal RG, Kosterlitz-Thouless transition, and dynamic renomalization group.</p><p> </p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Acquaintance with the modern language of emergent phenomena, </p><p>Hands-on experience with the implementation of the RG programme.</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Chaikin-Lubensky: Principles of condensed Matter Physics</p><p>McComb: Renormalization Methods</p><p>Relevant papers and review articles</p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Homework, term paper and presentation.</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Attendance is required.</p></div></div>",
