            "html_details":"<div><strong>Office timing</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Will be announced closer to the semester.</p></div></div><div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>In this course one will learn the basic concepts in probaility theory, like events, probaility assignment, relative frequency definion, probaility space, conditional probaiity, random variables both discrete and continuous ones.  Some limit theorems like the law of large numbers, central limit theorem will be seen.  We will see how theory of probability provides the mathematical framework for doing statistical analysis. These concepts will enable one to answer some interesting and useful question in real life. </p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>At the end of the course a student should master basic concepts of probaility and will be able to use it for some real life problems. This will </p><p>also the student to formulate mathematically a statistical analysis question. This course will also give them some basic exposure regarding use of basic statistical software like R.  </p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>The text book for the course is : A first course in Probability , Sheldon Ross, 9th Edition, Academic Press.</p><p>Some other suggested texts:</p><p>1. S. M. Ross: Introduction to Probability and Statistics for Engineers and Scientists. </p><p> 2. J. L. Devore: Probability and Statistics for Engineering, Cengage, 8th edition, 2012.</p><p>3. V. K. Rohatgi, E. S. Saleh: An Introduction to Probability and Statistics, Wiley-Blackwell, 3rd edition, 2015.</p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>It will be a combination of assignments/quizzes, midterm and final term.</p><p>Tentatively:  </p><p>assignments/quizzes : 30% (the exact number of assignments and class quizzes will be announced closer to the semster)</p><p>mid term : 25 % - 30%</p><p>Final term : 30% - 35 % </p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Plan to attend the lectures. Lectures will help you read the book and understand the material and solve the problems. That said, attendance is not mandatory. In case we have in-person lectures, I may give quizzes in class. There may be additional quizzes in discussion sessions. No makeup quizzes are given. </p></div></div>",
