            "semester":"Monsoon 2021",
            "document":"https://ams.ashoka.edu.in/UploadFiles/Content/ProgramCourseInfo/MS-2342[MS-2342-1]/9cd3049e-2455-4645-bd87-3c7c6d7e4665.pdf",
            "html_details":"<div><strong>Office timing</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Mondays/ Wednesdays 10 am to 11.30 am </p><p>Mondays 4.30 to 5.30 pm </p><p>All students are encouraged to seek individual appointments by email outside of these hours. While on zoom , timings are flexible and meetings can be scheduled with mutual agreement. </p></div></div><div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This course focuses on the role of the media in diplomacy and foreign policy in South Asia especially with regard to reporting on contentious issues. Limiting the geography to SAARC countries, the aim is to research and analyze the manner in which different forms of the media act as both a part of the policy message,  as well as representatives of civil society concerns in a post-colonial, post partition subcontinent. The course will introduce students to an overview of how the Indian media constructs the idea of South Asia, and try to understand why, and how certain stories come to dominate.</p><p>The course will include guest lectures from diplomatic correspondents across the South Asian region mainly from members of the South Asian Women in Media collective of women journalists in the SAARC countries. </p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Through lectures, guest speakers, and class discussions and assignments, the students will learn how to navigate foreign ministry websites, distinguish different forms of diplomatic communication, and understand the craft of reporting on diplomacy which involves writing skills, nuance and objectivity. It will also introduce students to how mass media is leveraged through storytelling formats to dominate narratives. </p><p>Students will also learn the history of the oldest newspapers of the subcontinent, learn about media trends in individual countries and become aware of the different forms of media consumption that aim to build bridges through music, cinema and cultural exchanges in the real and virtual worlds. Some case studies will be used through the semester, including Coke Studio, Himal Magazine , Aman Ki Asha initiatives , and SAFMA. </p><p>Students will be graded on one short assignment at the beginning of term, one class presentation to be done in groups, and 2 written assignments- one at mid-term, and one at end of term. </p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>see attached file. </p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Grading </p><p>Short assignment- 10 marks \u2013 week 3 </p><p>Mid-term assignment- 20 marks \u2013 week 6</p><p>Presentation- 20 marks-  weeks 8-9</p><p>Final Assignment \u2013 35 marks \u2013 week 13/14 </p><p>Participation- 15 marks. This will be assessed on attendance and interventions through the semester. </p><p>Deadlines must be met. Anything submitted late will result in a grade cut. First day late .5 mark, all subsequent days 1 mark cut for each day late. </p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>2 unexcused absences allowed. Anything further will result in a .5 mark grade cut per absence. </p></div></div><div><strong>Attachment</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><table><tbody><tr><td><a style=\"color:blue\" href=\"https://ams.ashoka.edu.in/UploadFiles/Content/ProgramCourseInfo/MS-2342[MS-2342-1]/9cd3049e-2455-4645-bd87-3c7c6d7e4665.pdf\" download=\"MS 2342- MEDIA AS PEACEBUILDING IN SA COURSE PLAN.pdf\">MS 2342- MEDIA AS PEACEBUILDING IN SA COURSE PLAN.pdf</a></td></tr></tbody></table></div></div>",
