            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Understanding URBAN POVERTY- 200 LEVEL<br><br><br>More than 25 percent of the urban population is below the poverty line. By 2030, urbanisation in India is projected to reach 50 percent. This intensified complex, urban issues including land, water and sanitation. The course will focus on looking at socio-economic disparities in Urban India. Key teachings will be navigating geographical landscapes, government bureaucracies and hierarchies of resources and trauma in urban spaces.<br><br>Through lectures, reporting and assessment of a wide range of issues like affordable housing, unequal distribution of resources-electricity, public spaces, unorganised workforce, gender gap and more importantly, a lack of representation and voice in framing of urban policies, students will be taught how to report on urban poverty in an ethical, comprehensive and impactful manner.<br><br><br>Week 1: Introduction <br><br>Week 2: Urban Landscape: Access to public transport, public spaces-parks, roads, shopping areas. Eviction in the name of development, thrown to the outskirts. Urban designs exclusively for the rich. <br>Week 3: Inequality in resource distribution: Electricity, drinking water, sanitation, drainage<br>Week 4: Right to Housing: Lack of affordable places, rent economy, high density area, land rights for the marginalised<br>Week 5:  Migration and reverse migration<br>Week 6:  Right to Education: Access to quality schools, colleges, affordable vocational studies centres, higher education<br><br>Week 7:  Living on the edge: Gender gap, caste gap, religious majoritarianism, regionalism<br>Week 8: Right to Health: Access to public healthcare and lack of infrastructure<br>Week 9: Political representation or the Lack of it: RWA, Wards, Assemblies<br>Week 10: Public Policies for the urban poor: Social security, kind of schemes and programs <br><br>Week 11: Workspaces: Unorganised labour: domestic work, unauthorised factories, sweatshops, contract workers, self employed<br>Week 12: Violence: From the state players, elite and the privileged. <br><br>Week 13: Revision<br><br><br><br> </p></div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Only two absences permitted in the 13 week long course. </p></div></div>",
