            "html_details":"<div><strong>Office timing</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>TIME TABLE: MONDAYS/WEDNESDAYS 2.50 to 4.20 pm </p><p>COURSE CAP 30 </p><p>Teaching Assistant  - Akanksha Mishra</p></div></div><div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>HISTORY OF THE IMAGE/ WAYS OF SEEING  (MAYA MIRCHANDANI + TISHA SRIVASTAV) - 200 level COURSE CODE: MS-2231(THEORY BUCKET) </p><p>Given the visual stimuli of our era, how do we begin to unpack ways of seeing and seeing through images. This media course will offer a theoretical and representational history of the imag e- in still and moving pictures. Their impact on social discourse, representation, and politics. What we are shown, what we choose to see, what we show ourselves. </p><p>Over a month each dedicated to the still image and moving image respectively, both theories and examples of visual representation will be discussed. In this photojournalism, popular cinema across era and continent will feature through student presentations, in-class exercises and online screenings.</p><p>Students interested in media, media theory, still photography and cinema will find this course gives them the foundation to inspect our image driven societies through a variety of perspectives.</p><p>Department of Media Studies is offering courses across four broad streams - Journalism, Film, Content Production and Communication Theory and Research. This course falls primarily in the last of those streams, but will feature all the other streams in small measure. This course has been designed keeping in mind that much of the Monsoon 2021 semester is likely online.</p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Students can expect to understand the history of the still photograph and the moving image</p><p>An introduction to the politics of representation through a variety of in-class exercises, screenings and student driven presentations on theoretical material.</p><p>Students interested in understanding media, media theory, still photography and cinema will find, this course gives them the foundation to inspect our image driven societies through a variety of perspectives</p><p>Students who have done Introduction to Mobile Photography, offered in Monsoon 2020, may find an overlap in a couple of readings across weeks. In another semester of this academic year, a practical version of an Introduction to Still Photography may be offered by the Media Studies Department. The History of the Image will equip you with thoughtful ways to integrate critical thinking with that, going ahead too.</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p> </p><p>Month 1 Still photography</p><p>Week 1 Class exercise &amp; introductory lecture</p><p>  Class 1 - Intro and Queries about the course/ Photojournalism Images guessing game - Tisha /Class 2 Maya Introduction to Photo Journalism </p><p>  Week 2 Maya  - Image as evidence </p><p>  Week 3 Berger Another way of seeing (Videos &amp; text)  Maya</p><p>  Week 4 History of imagery from painting/ landscapes/Early readings of Pinney/ Portraiture - Tisha</p><p> Submission of Assignment 1 submission 20 % of the total Grade</p><p> </p><p> Week 5 Western photographers/ Eastern photographers - Tisha</p><p>Week 6</p><p>            Class 1 Guest Lecture on Silver Grain to Pixel - Aditya Arya, Director of Museo Camera, Gurgaon</p><p>            Class 2  - Suresh Chhabria Lecture on Still to the Moving Image (Useful for transition to week 6 on the Moving Image</p><p>Mid term break 9 \u2013 17 October</p><p> Month 2 Moving Image - Week 7 \u2013 10</p><p>Week 7  Intro to the moving image in Hindi cinema - Tisha</p><p>Week 8 Image and politics/Quirky stories \u2013 3or 4 cinemas</p><p> Week 9 Moving Image as news \u2013 Maya</p><p> Week 10 Documentary \u2013 Global Maya</p><p>                Documentary India - Tisha</p><p>2nd assignment submission by Wednesday Week 10 (25 % of the total grade)</p><p> </p><p> Week 11 Case study</p><p> Week 12 Case study</p><p>Week 13 Image in social media &amp; new tech  - Guest lectures</p><p>Dec 8 Student Final submissions/ Faculty will submit grade by 10 November</p><p>Final submission to be given by 25 th November \u2013 1500 words or 3 min video or 10 photographs with 500 words (Question regarding Cultural critique will be shared)</p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Attendance &amp; participation 20 %</p><p>1st Assignment \u2013 20 %</p><p>2nd Assignment 25%</p><p>3rd Assignment \u2013 35%</p> </div></div>",
