            "html_details":"<div><strong>Office timing</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><ul><li>Office hours - By appointment (Please send an email to guhan.venkat@ashoka.edu.in).</li></ul></div></div><div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><ul><li>This course will be suitable for 3rd and 4th year Mathematics students. We aim to develop the foundations of Number theory from an algebraic perspective. Owing to its aesthetic nature, Number theory is often regarded as the queen of Mathematics and is a very active area of research. In a nutshell, the primary learning outcome for this course will be about the arithmetic of Algebraic Number fields.</li></ul></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><ul><li>The learning outcome for this course will be primarily about the arithmetic of Algebraic Number fields (viz. finite degree field extensions of the rational numbers). We will prove theorems regarding unique factorization of ideals, compute the decomposition of prime ideals in Number fields (eg. prime decomposition in Quadratic fields using Quadratic Reciprocity law), prove finiteness of class number, Dirichlet's Unit theorem. We shall compute the class numbers of some number fields. Time permitting, we shall also learn about local fields, L-functions, Adeles and Ideles. For a detailed Syllabus, have a look at the Course Description attached along with.</li></ul></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>The primary references/textbooks for the course are as follows :-</p><ol><li>Daniel A. Marcus, <strong><em>Number fields</em></strong> (Second Edition), Universitext, Springer 2018.</li><li> Ian Stewart and David Tall, <strong><em>Algebraic number theory and Fermat's last theorem</em></strong> (Third Edition), A K Peters, Ltd., Natick, MA, 2002.</li><li>Kenneth Ireland and Michael Rosen, <em><strong>A Classical Introduction to Modern Number Theory</strong></em> (Second Edition), GTM Vol. 84, Springer-Verlag 1990.</li></ol><ul><li>Apart from these three Textbooks, Keith Conrad's Expository papers (hosted on https://kconrad.math.uconn.edu/blurbs/) also make for an excellent reading!</li></ul><p>*All the 3 textbooks listed above can be accessed online via the ProQuest \"Ebooks central\" subscription</p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>The grading rubric for the course will be as follows :-</p><ul><li>Final examination (45%).</li><li>Mid-term examination (40%).</li><li>4/5 periodical assignments out of which the best three contribute towards 15% of the final score.*</li></ul><p>* - Students however are encouraged to turn in the solutions of all the assignments!</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><ul><li>There is no mandatory attendance requirement.</li></ul></div></div><div><strong>Attachment</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><table><tbody><tr><td><a style=\"color:blue\" href=\"https://ams.ashoka.edu.in/UploadFiles/CourseCatalogueFiles/44bbae5f-a30e-4c89-a9bd-e844759f5859.pdf\" download=\"course-description.pdf\">course-description.pdf</a></td></tr></tbody></table></div></div>",
