            "html_details":"<div><strong>Office timing</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Office hours are by appointment.</p></div></div><div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Combinatorics is a central field of mathematics, with applications to Computer Science, Physics, Chemistry and of course other areas in mathematics. In Algebraic combinatorics, we study combinatorial objects using algebraic tools. A conference in this area is attended by experts in representation theory, algebra, mathematical physics, enumerative combinatorics, special functions and computer science. In addition, the subject is showing up in knot theory and in other geometrical contexts. </p><p>We include an introduction to basic enumerative techniques. Students who have taken Introduction to Combinatorics/Discrete Mathematics may find some familiar objects, but the approach is likely to be different.  Similarly, people who have taken Linear algebra and the sequence Algebra I and II may see some familiar ideas applied in unfamiliar ways. </p><p>We will make use of the symbolic algebra package Sage to explore mathematical objects. </p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>The tentative syllabus is as follows:</p><p>Basic combinatorial numbers, generating functions and recurrence relations, symmetric functions, character theory of the symmetric group, Polya-Read theory. The main focus is on symmetric functions and their applications. </p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>The main book we will follow is as follows:</p><p>1. V Krishnamurthy, Combinatorics: Theory and Applications, East-West press. (Available on Amazon.in.)</p><p>This is an old book but surprisingly modern in its coverage of topics that are of current interest. It was used for first year courses in BITS, Pilani, so all required background is built up in the book. You will be assigned problems from this book.  However, this book used old notation so we will be providing notes to supplement the book. </p><p>2. Class notes (to be provided)</p><p>In addition, there is the symbolic algebra package Sage which you are required to download, install and use in this course. This is available at the following website. </p><p>3. www.sagemath.org.</p><p> </p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>The following is tentative</p><p>1. Assignments - 100</p><p>2. Midterm - 100</p><p>3. Final - 100</p><p>All the above will require work in Sage (a computer algebra system) and code submissions will be required. </p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Attending lectures is mandatory. That said, we wont cut marks in case you don't attend, and grading is based on work submitted. Attending lectures will help you keep up with the work.</p></div></div>",
