            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This course will focus on pricing: its theory, in different market structures like monopoly, oligopoly, and competitive markets, two-sided markets and intermediary pricing; between different demand segments in the form of price discrimination, bundling, quantity discounts, etc.; given uncertainty; price collusion and practices facilitating it; a look at pricing from behavioral economics; pricing in specific industries; and the use of price as a policy instrument to correct market failures and to create markets where none exist in order to improve resource allocation and/or to provide support or incentive for target products, suppliers or consumers.</p><p> </p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>The first part of this course aims to enable students to understand the considerations on which pricing decisions are theoretically based in various types of markets, and to learn how to apply them to different industries, cases, and problems. The second part of the course will help students get familiar with the use of price as a policy instrument and help them explore and analyze how governments and institutions do this to improve upon non-existent and imperfect markets.</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Course material will use recommended textbooks, and excerpts from journal articles, news and other media, and other sources.</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Attendance is important for this course. There will be short quizzes in class without any pre-announcement. Students will be graded on their responses in these quizzes, as well as on attendance taken randomly in class; together these will be considered as the students' performance on 'class participation'.</p></div></div>",
