            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Why do we need this object called \"money\"? Is it simply because it is necessary to carry out trades? If so, then in our simplistic view of the world, money would be a constraint. What about alternative trading arrangements like barter or credit? This course starts with a micro-founded approach to money using an overlapping generations model and discusses why money is not a constraint but an instrument that arises endogenously leading to welfare gains for the economy. This course further discusses why money is welfare improving vis-a-vis barter or credit, why fiat money and not commodity money, and then we go on to study the relationship between money and other institutions that issue/ use money - financial intermediation &amp; banks, a model of bank risk and bank panic (Diamond-Dybvig model), governments &amp; national debt, fiscal theories of price level &amp; inflation, pension systems, etc.</p><p> </p><p>The simple baseline model that you will learn in this course is the overlapping generations model of money by economist Paul Samuelson (1958). As the year suggests, this is a pretty old model, however, it is a model that is quite insightful and at the same time accessible to undergraduates. There are other sophisticated frictional models of money that are beyond the reach of a typical undergraduate and are usually offered as a Master\u2019s/PhD elective. </p><p> </p><p>This course is not about bitcoin/ cryptocurrencies. The OLG model is not the best model to study these issues. For those really interested in economic models of cryptos and possess mathematical prowess, the suggested papers are Budish (NBER Working Paper, 2018), Huberman et al. (mimeo, 2019), and the research papers on the webpage of Bank of Canada\u2019s fintech working group. These are beyond the scope of this course.</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Prerequisites</p><ul><li>A strong knowledge of high school-level math is essential.</li><li>Familiarity with the concept of \u201cmodels\u201d in economics from your 2nd-year Micro and Macro courses.</li><li>You should have successfully completed (i.e. not failed/ withdrawn) your 2nd-year Micro-I, Macro-I &amp; II core courses or equivalent.</li></ul><p> </p><p> </p><p>References:</p><ul><li>Champ, B., Freeman, S., &amp; Haslag, J. (2016). Modeling Monetary Economies. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press.</li></ul> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>There will be no curving.</p><p> </p><table style=\"width:500px;\" cellspacing=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" border=\"1\"><tbody><tr><td>Absolute numerical score</td><td>Letter Grade</td><td>Grade Points</td></tr><tr><td>91 - 100</td><td>A</td><td>4.0</td></tr><tr><td>86 - 90</td><td>A-</td><td>3.7</td></tr><tr><td>82 - 85</td><td>B+</td><td>3.3</td></tr><tr><td>77 - 81</td><td>B</td><td>3.0</td></tr><tr><td>73 - 76</td><td>B-</td><td>2.7</td></tr><tr><td>68 - 72</td><td>C+</td><td>2.3</td></tr><tr><td>64 - 67</td><td>C</td><td>2.0</td></tr><tr><td>59 - 63</td><td>C-</td><td>1.7</td></tr><tr><td>55 - 58</td><td>D+</td><td>1.3</td></tr><tr><td>50 - 54</td><td>D</td><td>1.0</td></tr><tr><td>40 - 49</td><td>D-</td><td>0.7</td></tr><tr><td>&lt; 40</td><td>F</td><td>0.0</td></tr></tbody></table> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>You are taking a third-year elective. Of course, you need to attend classes regularly!</p></div></div><div><strong>Attachment</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><table><tbody><tr><td><a style=\"color:blue\" href=\"https://ams.ashoka.edu.in/UploadFiles/CourseCatalogueFiles/be161fe1-7d4d-463a-b99f-fe04ea09ffd1.pdf\" download=\"ECO 3200_course info.pdf\">ECO 3200_course info.pdf</a></td></tr></tbody></table></div></div>",
