            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>One of our most haunting legal dilemmas is an ethical question: what can we do about wrongful beliefs about others? In North America, it is well known that African Americans and indigenous peoples are over-represented in the figures of those who are wrongfully convicted. In a course that is transdisciplinary, we turn this sociological observation on its head by beginning with The Apology by Plato. Wrongful beliefs about others give rise to genres that are central to western civilization, such as apologias, justifications, confessions, and complaints. We will read \u201cThe Gospel of Matthew\u201d and the work of Ren\u00e9 Girard to think about the problem of the scapegoat vs. the figure of sacrifice. Augustin and Rousseau will trouble how we understand uncoerced confession as the truth of our beings. Examining fictions by Nathaniel Hawthorne and Maryse Cond\u00e9 and real life witch hunt trials, we will see that since the soul is at issue in confession, the wrongfully convicted have become the flipside of victims. Caleb Williams will help us to understand that exonerees are the only ones who can understand victims. Aside from intellectual history, we will look at cases of wrongful conviction and level critiques of our own at present-day Innocence Projects. We will look to the work of Gayl Jones to explore the problem of representational excess, what it means to come to bear the burden of representation. </p></div></div>",
