            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p> </p><p>This class covers the development of long-form prose fiction in Greece and Rome, what has been called the \u201cancient novel.\u201dThese novels, which are characterized by a fascination with love stories, travel, and questions of cultural, ethnic, class, and gender identity, are packed with exciting tales of shipwrecks, pirates, mistaken identities, and miraculous transformations. Taken together, they represent the expansiveness and diversity of the ancient Mediterranean world, with settings in Ethiopia, Egypt, Syria, Asia Minor, Greece, Italy, and journeys to the Arctic and the moon. We will read all the surviving ancient Greek and Roman novels, focusing on one per week: Chariton, Chaereas and Callirhoe, Xenophon, An Ephesian Tale, Achilles Tatius, Leucippe and Clitophon, Longus, Daphnis and Chloe, Heliodorus, Ethiopian Story, Pseudo-Lucian, Lucius, or, The Ass, Lucian, A True History, Apuleius, Metamorphoses, or, The Golden Ass, Petronius, Satyricon, and the epitomes of Antonius Diogenes, The Wonders Beyond Thule and Iamblichus, A Babylonian Story. Selections from literature which influenced the development of the Greco-Roman novel, such as Homer\u2019s Odyssey, Euripides\u2019 escape tragedies (Helen, Iphigeneia among the Taurians, and Andromeda), and paradoxography, examples of later reception, particularly in Byzantine adaptations of the 12th c., and relevant scholarship, will accompany these readings. In the final weeks of the class, we will compare the Greek and Roman novels to those of East Asia, reading selections from Murasaki Shikibu, The Tale of Genji (11th c.), Luo Guanzhong, Romance of the Three Kingdoms (14th c.) and Shi Naian, Water Margin (14th c.).</p></div></div>",
