            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This course will consider the veritable obsession of Shakespeare and his contemporaries with the Orient \u2013 a capacious yet imprecise term that demarcates not just a geographical place (North Africa and Asia) and a religious location (the \u201cIslamic\u201d world) but also a set of over-the-top acting techniques (the histrionic \u201coriental\u201d excess of the medieval cycle-drama Herod and the early modern Tamburlaine), a temporal relation (the Orient as an earlier \u201cstage\u201d that precedes the English present), and a political nightmare (the spectre of the idolatrous Oriental Despot).  We will consider how \u201cstaging the Orient\u201d is less about representing a real-world referent than it is a theatrical mode of geo-poesis \u2013 which is to say, it is literally globe-making (as the name of Shakespeare\u2019s playhouse suggests).  The early modern theatre functioned as a laboratory for England\u2019s future projects of globalization, plotting modes of cultural and temporal relationality informed by various logics \u2013 outsourcing, extraction of surplus value, supersession, transnational accumulation \u2013 that are now part and parcel of the modern global economy. We will read a number of early modern plays (the Coventry Shearmen and Taylor\u2019s pageant of Herod the Great, Thomas Preston\u2019s Cambyses, Christopher Marlowe\u2019s Tamburlaine, Robert Greene\u2019s Selimus, Shakespeare\u2019s Second Henriad, Day Wilkins and Rowley\u2019s Travels of the Three English Brothers, Robert Daborne\u2019s A Christian Turn\u2019d Turk, Philip Massinger\u2019s The Renegado, Shakespeare\u2019s Antony and Cleopatra, Shakespeare\u2019s The Tempest, John Fletcher\u2019s Island Princess) as well as various other early modern writings engaged with or informed by theatre such as the antitheatricalist tracts of Stephen Gosson, William Prynne et al., and travel narratives about Persia and India by Thomas Roe and Thomas Coryate.  We will also consider theoretical texts such as Edward Said\u2019s Orientalism, Dipesh Chakrabarty\u2019s Provincializing Europe, Alain Grosrichard\u2019s In the Sultan\u2019s Court, and Hegel\u2019s Philosophy of History.</p><p> </p></div></div>",
