            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Between 1975 and 1990, microhistories starting with Emmanuel Le Roy Ladurie\u2019s Montaillou, followed by Carlo Ginzburg\u2019s The Cheese and the Worms and Ecstasies, Natalie Zemon Davis\u2019s The Return of Martin Guerre, Jonathan Spence\u2019s The Question of Hu, and Robert Darnton\u2019s The Great Cat Massacre and Other Episodes in French Cultural History, flourished, pre-dating the New Historicism within literary criticism. Yet these biographical case studies have a set of eighteenth-century literary and anthropological antecedents. Olaudah Equiano describes his \u201cInteresting Narrative\u201d as a \u201ctrifle,\u201d also known as a false or idle tale. As John Bugg observes this kind of contingent tale expands in geopolitical register in the works of Daniel Defoe, \u201cfor whom trifles can center imperial exchange: one may \u201cpurchase \u2026 for Trifles \u2026 not only Gold Dust \u2026 Elephants Teeth, &amp;c. but Negroes.\u201d In a world in which slavery is legal, one person\u2019s trifle is another person\u2019s human being.\u201d This course will explore a selection of secret histories, it-narratives, anecdotes, trifles, and animal tales that set the stage for understanding the role of conscious and animate personified things. We will think about the case form, scale, personhood, action, and identity. </p></div></div>",
