            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>The 1920s are often portrayed as a watershed decade for cultural history generally, and modernism specifically.The story goes that the political realignments, social upheavals, and economic booms that followed the Great War all engendered an international blossoming of the arts.This course aims to question, trouble, and complicate this fundamentally Eurocentric outlook by rendering an expansive panorama of one decade of cultural history at a global scale.Providing only the nodes, students are asked to make their own connections over the course of the semester and map new intellectual reticulations.This course will feature a number of guest lectures. </p><p> </p></div></div>",
