            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>How should we be thinking about a concept as elusive as violence? What is the relation between thinking and violence? What do South Asian literary texts teach us about violence? What is nonviolence? These are some of the questions that will guide our thinking about the question of violence in South Asian literatures. The course will introduce the students to modern South Asian literary texts that think about violence. We will focus not only on texts dealing with war, riots, torture and other forms of physical violence but also on those processes of slow\u2014and intangible\u2014violence that have come to define collective and individual life in South Asia. We will situate key texts, authors and genres from different regional languages in a wider historical context of political violence in South Asia. We will be reading literary texts by Intizar Hussain, Mohan Rakesh, Mahasweta Devi, Nirmal Verma, Ajay Navaria, Waryam Singh Sandhu, Indira Goswami, Akhtar Mohiuddin, Temsula Ao and Michael Ondaatjee. We will also be reading key theoretical texts on the question of violence by Carl Schmitt, Hannah Arendt, Walter Benjamin, Franz Fanon, M. K. Gandhi, Judith Butler and Jacques Derrida. We will also be screening and discussing films by Ritwik Ghatak, Govind Nihalani, Gulzar and Sudhir Mishra among others.</p></div></div>",
