            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>The objective of the course is a thorough engagement with the project of rationality as understood in economics using the methodological perspective of decision theory. Setting up the exercise in decision-theoretic terms has the advantage of disciplining us to make our claims in terms of (in principle) observable behavior. The course will begin by laying out what the substantive content of rationality in neo-classical economics entails, along with an appreciation of the \u201cgenealogy\u201d of this concept. This discussion will also focus on the Bayesian paradigm and the foundations of subjective probabilities, which are key organizing principles when we talk about rationality in environments featuring uncertainty. After that, we will look at the criticisms of rational choice theory. We will then focus on a set of topics and themes proposed as responses to some of the limitations of rational choice theory. Amongst them, prominent themes and questions include:</p><p>1.     Rational choice theory is too narrowly focused on the outcome of choices and doesn\u2019t pay enough attention to the decision-making procedure by which those choices are arrived at. By ignoring these procedural aspects of decision making, the theory ignores important details like cognitive limitations that decision-makers are faced with when making choices. We will, therefore, want to think about approaches that take these procedural aspects of decision-making more seriously. </p><p>2.     In keeping with our search for descriptively richer accounts of behavior, we will delve into the heuristics and biases program of Kahneman and Tversky. In this context, we will also discuss dual-process theories of cognition. </p><p>3.     We will discuss  Kahneman and Tversky\u2019s Prospect theory and the paradigm of reference-dependent preferences, more generally. We will ask, just like they did all those years ago, as to what the \u201ctrue carriers of value are\u201d?</p><p>4.     Neo-classical economics takes individual preferences as exogenous and given. But, in many contexts, aren\u2019t preferences endogenous? Aren\u2019t things like identity-based preferences, say, sexist preferences or casteist preferences, socially constituted and not exogenous? If so, how should we go about theorizing endogenous preferences? What about social influence and how it shapes our preferences and choices? </p><p>5.     What about decision-making in social and political contexts? Do the same principles underlying decision-making in a more \u201cprivate\u201d context carry over seamlessly to them? Are the fundamental decision-theoretic insights with which we analyze people\u2019s consumption decisions adequately when analyzing, say, their voting decisions?</p></div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>1. Class participation (20%)</p><p>2. Midterm (25%)</p><p>3. Final (25%)</p><p>4. Group assignments and research-related tasks (30%)</p><p> </p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Regular attendance is a necessary (although not sufficient) condition for scoring well in the 20% of the grade assigned to class participation. I do not do asynchronous teaching, although I do post lecture videos. Regular attendance is vital for you to do well in this course. I expect that you will attend all lectures and take responsibility for coming to them prepared. Regular attendance will be taken in all classes. Unexcused absences (apart from those necessitated by health reasons or other emergencies) are strongly discouraged. If you feel that you won't be able to attend the synchronous lectures because of a scheduling conflict, you should not take the course. </p></div></div>",
