            "html_details":"<div><strong>Office timing</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Class Schedule: Thursday and Friday: 2.50-4.20 p.m. </p><p>Office Hours: Friday: 1.30-2.30 p.m. </p></div></div><div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><strong>Course Overview:</strong></p><p>As natural geological formations, caves provided humans with the earliest surfaces for leaving behind enduring visual accounts. Their status between \u2018nature\u2019 and \u2018culture,\u2019 meant that they have long been associated with sacred spaces in Buddhism, Jainism and Hinduism. They also serve as a large corpus of art and architectural histories. While hugely labour-, time- and capital-intensive, what made caves popular across religious and political formations, and for a large period of human history? Delving into this, and allied questions, the proposed course will promote engagement with the histories of rock-cut art and architecture from the South Asian Subcontinent. Reflecting on the foundational relationship, between caves and the discipline of art history, students will deepen their understanding of issues of iconography, the relationship between religion, art and architecture, religious and philosophical formations such as monastic orders and their impact upon stylistic changes, artistic patronage and royal power, etc.</p><p>The course envisions advancing two tracks of study, viz. chronology and thematic concerns. The chronological component will introduce students to key sites and the attendant questions of architectural and iconographic developments. The sites considered will include: Bhimbetka, Lomas Rishi cave, Khandagiri/Udayagiri, Karle, Bhedsa, Kanheri, Ajanta, Badami, Elephanta, Mamallapuram, Ellora, among others.</p><p>Thematic concerns will include: historical methods and the \u2018discovery\u2019 of sites, the role of caves in fashioning neo-revivalist projects (e.g. Ajanta murals\u2019 constitutive role in forging an \u2018Indian\u2019 visual language) and as spaces of artistic transmission, through long-term 19th century projects such as the copying of its murals. Underscoring the many lives of these sites, one theme explored will be the conversion of cave shrines into \u2018monuments\u2019 under colonial governance and the consequent impact upon questions of public access; Elephanta in western India will be considered as a case-study. Taken together, these case studies and themes will equip students to carry out iconographic, historiographic and critical analyses of Indian art history.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>At the end of the course, students will learn:</p><ul><li>Key art historical skills, such as the reading of architectural plans, holistic analysis of sites, analyzing primary sources such as field reports and a close-study of images and iconography.</li><li>The process of building a \u2018context\u2019 for reading images by developing questions around iconography, historiography and socio-political developments.</li><li>A historically informed understanding of human interactions with the landscape and natural formations, and learning to problematize the nature/culture binary.</li><li>The ability to develop new, independent research pathways in disciplines such as art history, anthropology, sociology, religious studies, etc.</li></ul></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Preliminary Reading List:</p><ul><li>Brown, P. (1956). Indian Architecture, Bombay: D.B. Taraporevala and Sons.</li><li>Spink, W. (1958). On the Development of Early Buddhist Art in India. The Art Bulletin, 40(2), 95-104. doi:10.2307/3047760</li><li>Tarr, G. (1970). Chronology and Development of the Cha?ukya Cave Temples. Ars Orientalis, 8, 155-184. http://www.jstor.org/stable/4629258</li><li>Mitter, P. (1977). Much Maligned Monsters: History of European Reactions to Indian Art. Oxford: Clarendon Press.</li><li>(1994). Art and Nationalism in Colonial India: Occidental Orientations. New York: Cambridge University Press.</li><li>Dhaky, M.A. &amp; Meister, M. W. (1983 \u2013 1999). Encyclopedia of Temple Architecture, Vols. 1-10. New Delhi: American Institute of Indian Studies. [selected sections]</li><li>Huntington, S. &amp; Huntington, J. (1985). The Art of Ancient India: Buddhist, Hindu, Jain. Boston: Weather Hill.</li><li>Michell, G. (1990). The Penguin Guide to the Monuments of India. vol. 1, Buddhist, Jain, Hindu. New Delhi: Penguin.</li><li>Willis, M. (2009). The Archaeology of Hindu Ritual: Temples and the Establishment of the Gods. New York: Cambridge University Press.</li><li>Brancaccio, P. (2013). Living Rock. Buddhist, Hindu and Jain Cave Temples in the Western Deccan. Mumbai: Marg Publications.</li><li>Singh, U. (2004). The Discovery of Ancient India: Early Archaeologists and the Beginnings of Archaeology. Ranikhet: Permanent Black.</li><li>Guha-Thakurta, T.(2004). Monuments, Objects, Histories: Institutions of Art in Colonial and Postcolonial India. New York: Columbia University Press.</li><li>Lahiri, N. (2015). Marshalling the Past: Ancient India and Its Modern Histories. Ranikhet: Permanent Black.</li><li>Guha, S. (2015). Artefacts of History: Archaeology, Historiography and Indian Pasts. New Delhi: Sage Publications.</li></ul> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><strong>Course Deliverables: </strong></p><ul><li>Mid-semester presentation, accompanied by a report (Word Limit: 1000 words)</li><li>End semester research paper, between 2000-2500 words, including footnotes, bibliography.</li></ul><p>The course follows a continuous assessment mode with class participation carrying 10% of the credit as we read plans, identify images, iconographic departures, architectural innovation, and critically read texts.<br>In the first assignment, which will serve as mid-term evaluation, students will be expected to choose a site, theme, motif, to make a class presentation on the same. This needs to be accompanied by a report of a maximum 1000 words. Presentations are key for demonstrating your grasp over the subject as well as your critical reading of multiple sources. Each student will have approximately ten to fifteen minutes to make their presentation, and respond to questions/comments\u2014 this is a chance for the class to engage with your research. Together with the report, this presentation carries 40% of the credits.<br>In the second assignment students will choose to respond to one question out of two; these will be questions relating to methodology and/or historiography. Alternatively, they may develop a curatorial concept for a curated walk-through a specific site; issues of conservation will need to be taken into account, and site-specific solutions will have to be advanced.</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Two absences are permitted. However, being absent on the day/s of presentation will result in a grade-cut. </p></div></div>",
