            "html_details":"<div><strong>Office timing</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>12 noon to 5 pm</p></div></div><div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Course Description: </p><p>In an era which some commentators have described as the \u2018golden age of the documentary\u2019, comics \u2013 particularly non-fiction comics - have emerged as a persuasive new form of narrative art situated at the intersection of the visual, the textual, the spatial and the temporal. This course is designed to lead students through an overview of the history, semiotics and structures of comics to the techniques and methods of researching and creating non-fiction comics.</p><p> </p><p>The course will have theory and practice components. We will engage in reading and writing as well as drawing from life, taking photographs, collaging, tracing and digital image-making and manipulation. It is a project based course, and while each student will be required to complete an individual project, they will also be encouraged to interact/collaborate and share skillsets and resources with each other as far as possible.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Course Modules: </p><p>The course is divided broadly into two parts. In the first part (4 weeks), students will be introduced to some seminal works from the global and Indian comics universe \u2013 spanning various kinds of non-fiction genres, including documentary, history/oral history, witness accounts, biography/autobiography, reportage and commentary. The selection of works for study and discussion will be curated rather than extensive. For example, Art Speigelman\u2019s Maus will be explored in conjunction with Keiji Nakagawa\u2019s Barefoot Gen \u2013 the remarkable parallels of subject matter of both works contrasted with their sharp divergence of perspective providing a perfect opportunity for comparative readings of the different forms, styles, techniques, narrative devices and approaches of the artists. Similarly, the experimental Bhimayana \u2013 the graphic biography of B.R.Ambedkar, could be paired with the more conventionally structured Gandhi by Campfire comics. The presentations will be discussion-based and participatory. The examination of master works will provide the opportunity to delve below the surface and understand the governing principles and fundamental architecture of comics in general, while also noting the medium\u2019s constantly evolving nature.</p><p> </p><p>The second part of the course (9 weeks) will be practice oriented, focusing particularly on research as practice, and will be conducted in three stages. </p><p>1. Students will be asked to select an area of interest related to their concerns or engagements \u2013 for instance, the ongoing farmer\u2019s protests at the Delhi borders. After developing an initial understanding of the background, the student will be encouraged to research and document the visual landscape of the protest sites \u2013 from tractors to tents, charpais to kitchens, the fields, trees and seasons, the implements of protest. Mundane objects and precious objects, the faces, expressions and body languages of resistance will all become worthy subjects of the artist\u2019s gaze. Art research breaches boundaries of sociology, anthropology, history and geography, and its methods and tools are also cross disciplinary. Students will be required to use live drawing, photography and note taking, supplemented with audio and video recording. This kind of work sharpens the skills of close, empathetic observation and engagement. It also builds and strengthens visual memory and vocabulary \u2013 the bedrock of all visual art practice.  At the same time, the student will be asked to seek out and record the stories, opinions and voices of the protestors. This will simultaneously need to be backed up with secondary research from blogs, social media sites and other sources such as the farmer run publication Trolley Times. While the research process is often proactive and investigative, students will be encouraged to integrate periods of absorbtion/reflection \u2013 of becoming still and listening, seeing \u2013  acts of deep witnessing. These are also the pauses that allow for the internalization and distillation of experience, which is so crucial to an artist\u2019s process of creative transformation.</p><p> </p><p>2. The next stage will involve the process of cataloguing and consolidating the collected material/evidence and the sorting, classifying and discerning of patterns. The student will identify  key visual and narrative elements, extract details and begin shaping a graphic script based on images and texts. At this stage, the imagination will come into play - through brainstorming, lateral thinking and ideating. This may also involve group presentations and feedback sessions. Discussions on the continuities and disruptions of text and image relationships, the rythms of time and space in sequential images, page composition, layouts, pagination and other formal and structural elements of the comics medium will return \u2013 but now within the specific frame of the narrative at hand . The first draft of the student\u2019s visual story will result at the end of this.</p><p> </p><p>3. The final stage will be devoted to the execution of the stories  in the form of a 10 to 12 page work. Aspects of media, technique, style, skill and finish will be discussed alongside. Each student will be required to produce an individual project and encouraged to adopt techniques best suited to their individual approaches and intentions. Collaborative sharing of skill sets and resources will be encouraged.</p><p> </p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Learning Objectives: </p><p>At the end of the course, students will have developed the capacity to research, interpret, narrate and create comics stories on any subject that is of interest to them. They will have grasped the essentials of graphic strategies and techniques, and have the ability to conceptually handle text, image, time and space in ways that are relevant to conceptualising visual narratives of all kinds.</p><p> </p><p>Course Deliverables: </p><p>One completed non-fiction comic of at least 12 pages length - publishable as a stand-alone work in the format of a Zine or as part of an anthology of comics.</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Reading List: </p><p>About Looking John Berger</p><p>Contemporary Comics Storytelling by Karin Kukkonen</p><p>Comics and Narration by Thierry Groensteen</p><p>Disaster Drawn - Visual Witness by Hillary L. Chute</p><p>Documentary Comics Graphic Truth Telling in a Skeptical Age by Nina Mickwitz</p><p>First Hand \u2013 Graphic Non-Fiction from India Vol 1 and 2  Ed: Orijit Sen &amp; Vidyun Sabhaney</p><p>This Side, That Side \u2013 Restorying Partition Ed: Vishwajyoti Ghosh</p><p>Palestine - Joe Sacco</p><p>Safe Area Gorazde - Joe Sacco</p><p>Persepolis - Marjane Satrapi</p><p>Maus - Art Speigelman</p><p>Barefoot Gen - keiji Nakagawa</p><p>Munnu: A Boy From Kashmir - Malik Sajad</p><p> </p><p>Material Requirements</p><p>A4 size Sketchbook and A5 size journal/ diary</p><p>Soft lead pencils and erasers, Charcoal pencils, Brush pens, </p><p>Colouring mediums: Acrylic paints, Colour pencils, Sketch pens, Poster colours</p><p>General stationery: scissors, cutter, glue, stapler, tape etc.</p><p>Computer/ iPad with Graphics capabilities (if possible)</p><p>Access to digital printer</p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Grading Rubrics: </p><p>30% for quality and depth of research </p><p>20% for story idea </p><p>40% for detailing and visualisation </p><p>10% for participation, articulation and engagement in class/studio sessions </p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Attendance policy: </p><p>90% minimum attendance</p></div></div>",
