            "html_details":"<div><strong>Office timing</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Wednesday and Thursday 14.50 to 16.20</p></div></div><div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This course is application oriented with a focus on understanding and making use of data in biology. The systematic acquisition of data made possible by advances in genomics and proteomics technologies has created a gap between the available data and its analysis leading to insights from the data. In addition, the data from multiple sources can be used to generate hypothesis and answer important questions. Computational and theoretical approaches to understanding biological systems are an essential step in closing this gap. Since statistics plays, an important role in data analysis lectures on relevant topics of statistics are part of the course.  The major emphasis of the course is to be able to solve some of common problems using the approaches being taught in the class.</p><p>Lecture Schedule</p><p> </p><p>Sept 1                                    Introduction to biology and genomics AB    </p><p>Sept 2                           Biological data, databases and datamining   AB</p><p>Sept 8                                    R workshop 1  KG</p><p>Sept 9                          R workshop 2  KG</p><p> </p><p>Sept 15                                                 Concept of annotation                        KG</p><p>Sept 16                                    Sequence alignment  1                          KG</p><p>Sept 22                                                 Sequence alignment   2                         BC</p><p>Sept 23                                    Exercises On alignment                               BC</p><p>Sept 29                                                 Finding remote homologs and motifs 1  AB </p><p>Sept 30                                    Finding remote homologs and motifs  2 AB </p><p>                                               </p><p>Oct 6                                                      Protein and RNA structure analysis        AB      </p><p>Oct 7                                       Exam/quiz       </p><p>Mid Sem Break                                 </p><p>Oct 20                                                   Basic concepts in Randomness and Probability         VF SS</p><p>Oct 21                                     Basic Probability Distributions  VF SS</p><p>Oct 27                                                   Types of data; Populations and Samples          VF  SS</p><p>Oct 28                                     Hypothesis testing and Making Decisions - Large Sample Tests, Small Sample tests  1 VF  SS</p><p>Nov 3                                                     Hypothesis testing and Making Decisions - Large Sample Tests, Small Sample tests  2 VF  SS</p><p>Nov 4                                                     Basics of non-parametric approaches to hypothesis testing  VF  SS</p><p>Nov 10                                                  Concept of accounting for sources of variation -  Single-factor ANOVA   VF  SS</p><p>Nov 11                                                  Next generation sequencing and principles of NGS data analysis  1   BC</p><p>Nov 17                                                  Next generation sequencing and principles of NGS data analysis  2   BC</p><p>Nov 18                                    Principles of phylogenetic analysis 1  BC</p><p>Nov 24                                                  Principles of phylogenetic analysis 2  BC  </p><p>Nov 25                                    Gene expression analysis AB</p><p>Dec 1                                                     Identification of regulatory elements and Promoters   AB</p><p>Dec 2                                                     Exercises</p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Students will learn about different forms of biological data including next generation sequencing data generation and how it has revolutionized our current understanding of biology. Further, students will learn to about data handling, analysis and interpretation. They will be able to answer simple biological questions using data analysis. The biostatistics part of the course will introduce students to application of statistical theory to biological data. Students will learn the concept of various test and their application use real data.</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Bioinformatics: Sequence And Genome Analysis by David W. Mount</p><p> </p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Relative grading system</p><p>Assignments:                                      45%</p><p>Statistics exam:                                   25%</p><p>End-Sem bioinformatics exam           30%    </p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>None at present</p></div></div>",
