            "html_details":"<div><strong>Office timing</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>9.15 AM to 10 AM - Monday to Thiursday</p></div></div><div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p> </p><p><strong>Course Description:</strong>  The course aims to analyze the many meanings that make history and  memory intelligible. What is history? How does memory work?  Is memorialization selective or inclusive? These are some of the questions that will be examined through an exploration of  some  iconic persona and phenomena. On the one hand, three famous personalities will be explored \u2013 Alexander the Great, Emperor Ashoka and Mahatma Gandhi \u2013 in order to understand the elements that form the title of this course. On the other hand, the phenomena of war will be examined ranging from Massada in the Middle East to the American-Vietnam War in Southeast Asia in order to explore the contested terrain of history and memory. Apart from reading the works of historians, the course will involve analysing excerpts from literature and films. </p><p>Note: All reading material will be emailed to students.</p><p> </p><p><strong>I. Introducing History, Memory and Memorialization</strong></p><p>John H. Arnold. 200. History \u2013 A Very Short Introduction, Chapter 7. Oxford: Oxford University Press.</p><p>David Lowenthal.  1998. Fabricating Heritage. History and Memory (Volume 10, No. 1)</p><p>Anand Patwardan\u2019s film In Memory of Friends.</p><p><strong>II. Alexander\u2019s Life and Conquests in Asia, Alexander as a Persian King</strong></p><p>Brooke Allen.  2005. Alexander the Great: Or the Terrible. The Hudson Review (Volume 58, No. 2).</p><p>A.K. Narain.  1965. Alexander and India. Greece &amp; Rome (Volume 12, No. 2)</p><p><strong>III. Ashoka\u2019s life and times, Ashoka\u2019s afterlife in India and Southeast Asia</strong></p><p>Nayanjot Lahiri. 2015. Ashoka in Ancient India. Ranikhet: Permanent Black. Selected chapters. </p><p><strong>IV. Mahatma Gandhi: His life and Ideas; Memorialization in his lifetime and beyond</strong></p><p>Dennis Dalton. 1993 (2014 edition). Gandhi\u2019s Power \u2013 Nonviolence in Action. New Delhi: Oxford University Press. Selected chapters.</p><p>Shahid Amin. 1988. \u2018Gandhi as Mahatma: Gorakhpur District, Eastern U.P. 1921-22\u2019  Selected Subaltern Studies, New Delhi: Oxford University Press, pp. 288-348. </p><p>Film: Raj Kumar Hirani\u2019s Lage Raho Munna Bhai</p><p><strong>V: Fighting War : On the Battlefield and in Memory  </strong></p><p>Yael Zerubavel. 1994. \u2018The Death of Memory and the Memory of Death: Masada and the Holocaust as Historical Metaphors\u2019. Representations (No. 45, Winter).</p><p>Viet Thanh Nguyen. 2016. Nothing Ever Dies \u2013 Vietnam and the Memory of War.  Cambridge: Harvard University Press.</p><p>Film: Vietnam war: A Hollywood movie on the Vietnam war will be compared with a movie made by Vietnamese film makers </p><p> </p><p> </p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>The  idea is to make students understand and appreciate the interplay of history and memory .</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>See 'Overview' above, readings mentioned there. All reading material will be emailed to students</p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><strong>Grade Breakup</strong></p><p>I.              Discussion participation and presentations  50%</p><p>II.            Short Writing Assignment 30% </p><p>III.         Final Essay 20% </p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Attending lectures is mandatory. More than 5 absences will lead to you automatically failing the course.</p></div></div>",
