            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>\" Prose Fiction Workshop\" to be taught by Professor Amit Chaudhuri in a slightly unusual format. It will be an 8 day workshop  that meets for 3 1/2 hours each day - 4 days on a stretch, a day's break, and then again for 4 days starting from 16th August till 25th August.</p><p> </p><p>The eight-day course is designed to hone the skills of writers who already have a fair amount of competence in writing. It is also designed to encourage a discussion and conversation about the craft of writing and about critical and imaginative concerns. It is modelled on the Prose Fiction MA in Creative Writing at the University of East Anglia, and workshops will comprise a mix of detailed feedback on the participants\u2019 samples of writing general critical discussion. The eight-day UEA India international workshop , which serves as a precursor to this one and took place annually from 2013-17 in Calcutta, helped identify and nurture the skills of some of India\u2019s most interesting new writers who then went on to get published by major publishers in India.</p><p> </p><p>The course should enable the student to do at least two things: first, to develop a piece of writing that they are currently working on in response to workshop discussion and tutorial feedback, and initiate a new piece of work; second, to reflect upon their own work and those of other participants in a wider literary and cultural context.</p><p> </p><p>During the first four days, three participants will each submit, in alphabetical order, a 2,000-word sample of a piece of non-fiction \u2013 either new work or extracts from or examples of ongoing work. Samples they may have handed in earlier with their application shouldn\u2019t be submitted for the workshop.</p><p> </p><p>These will be read and discussed in detail by other students in the class for three to three and a half hours. The workshop tutor will offer their thoughts on each of the pieces too, as well as bring into the discussion relevant critical ideas if they think this appropriate. All students will have had their 2,000-word samples discussed by the end of the fourth day.</p><p> </p><p>Each day, after the workshop, the tutor will have a one-to-one meeting with the three</p><p>students who have been workshopped earlier that day. This will be a focused tutorial on their submission lasting thirty minutes each \u2013 so a total of one and a half hours.</p><p> </p><p>There will be no workshop on the fifth day.</p><p> </p><p>During the second cluster of four days, participants will bring to the table a short 1500-word piece that they have written during the course of the workshop. This piece may be a response to a text handed out earlier in the workshop. The pattern of workshopping and tutorials established in the first four days will be repeated exactly.</p><p>Participants are encouraged to make detailed notes about other participants\u2019 works, which they should respond to thoughtfully, constructively, and in detail. Criticism of samples is welcome as long as it is constructive. The introduction of critical and intellectual concepts to the discussion is welcome too, as long as it is pertinent to the discussion, and to issues and questions raised by the work being discussed. </p><p>The evening sessions and other activities will give participants the opportunity to engage with the tutor. Amit Chaudhuri will discuss his new books, Finding the Raga and Ramanujan, during a two-hour interaction with students. A separate one-hour interaction will involve a talk by a writer invited to speak at the workshop by Professor Chaudhuri.</p></div></div>",
