            "html_details":"<div><strong>Office timing</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>For appointments and discussion sessions, please drop an email at shagun.sinha@ashoka.edu.in.</p><p> </p><p>Slots for office hours - usually around 11 am to 12 noon/ 5 pm to 6 pm during weekdays - will also be opened on the LMS when the semester starts.</p></div></div><div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Credits: 4</p><p>Open to: All students across UG, PG, and graduate studies.</p><p> </p><p><strong>Introduction</strong></p><p> </p><p>The objective of \u2018Elementary Sanskrit-I\u2019 is to introduce interested learners to basic Sanskrit grammar.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The word 'Sanskrit' is synonymous with a continuous trail of intellectual traditions in language and literature which includes vedas, vedangas, epics, puranic traditions, etc. These intellectual traditions serve as storehouse of knowledge that waits to be decoded and explored which is precisely why they intrigue researchers even today. For example, there is a revived interest in scientific interpretation of the Vedas to exploit encoded methodologies of agriculture harvesting, linguistic analysis, and other similar areas. Institutions working in applied research in Indian psychology study and interpret the Sanskrit texts based on yoga. Similarly, Paninian grammar and formalisms have gained the particular interest of computational linguists and artificial intelligence researchers. In other words, Sanskrit language and literature serve to provide a glimpse to the future while joining dots from the past. </p><p> </p><p>Reading, writing and comprehension abilities in Sanskrit are essential for undertaking any of the aforementioned or related work in the language and this course teaches grammar from elementary/beginner level to pave way for developing the aforementioned abilities.</p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>The course will guide students to learn Sanskrit from the basic building blocks of grammar to some standard concepts in sentence formation and comprehension. After successful completion of the course, students will be able to read, write and understand basic sentences in Sanskrit.</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Handouts based on modules will be shared during the semester.</p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Evaluation will comprise of</p><ul><li>timely submssion of weekly assignments - qualifying. Submission punctuality will be the sole grading criterion for weekly assignments</li><li>conversational Sanskrit and end-semester presentation - 10% (conversational Sanskrit will be taught during the class.)</li><li>graded quizzes (40%), and</li><li>two examinations. (50%)</li></ul> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>1. <strong>Virtual Semester: </strong>As long as the semester is virtual, students may be allowed to watch recordings in case they have technical/internet-based issues(if any) in attending the classes. This should not be the norm though and leniency in this regard will be decided on a case-to-case basis.</p><p>2. <strong>On-Campus: </strong>If the semester is held offline at any point of time, students will <strong>not be allowed more than 5 absences</strong> throughout the semester. </p><p>3. <strong>Audit Policy: </strong>The course is open to audit/observer students with prior approval<strong>. </strong>Audit students will also be expected to be regular with attendance as well as assignments/exams. </p></div></div><div><strong>Attachment</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><table><tbody><tr><td><a style=\"color:blue\" href=\"https://ams.ashoka.edu.in/UploadFiles/Content/ProgramCourseInfo/SAN-1001[SAN-1001-1]/611da1b5-7b44-4b92-b160-d50b498bdce7.pdf\" download=\"CC_ElementarySanskrit_1.pdf\">CC_ElementarySanskrit_1.pdf</a></td></tr></tbody></table></div></div>",
