            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This course aims to introduce students to select issues in Indian politics. Conventionally the centre or the so-called national has been the vantage point for the study of Indian politics. This course, however, takes a different path. First, it turns the spotlight away from the centre to the states. Second, it uses a comparative lens as the framework for analysis. </p><p>The view from the centre not only masks key differences among states but sometimes gives us an inappropriate picture when the features and characteristics of certain regions become characteristic of India. At the same time, this course does not intend to emphasise the distinct nature of individual states and focus on state-specific stories. Subnational comparisons give us the right balance between the \u201call-India\u201d and the particular and thus enrich our understanding of political phenomena. </p><p>The course will underscore the usefulness of subnational comparative analysis to study issues like economic policymaking, party strategy, ethnic conflict management, leadership styles and dynastic politics among others.</p></div></div>",
