            "html_details":"<div><strong>Office timing</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>TBA</p></div></div><div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This course looks at the Indian \u2018state\u2019 \u2013 its history, components, problems and opportunities. The \u2018state\u2019 is a key concept in political science, and we begin with theories of state formation \u2013 world over and in colonial and newly independent India. We then look at the design and capacity of the Indian state \u2013 both at the top (in Delhi) as well as the bottom (how does the state in an Indian village look like?). We will then study problems of state and bureaucratic capacity, the role of the state in providing public goods such as education and health, as well as in transforming Indian society.</p><p> </p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>At the heart of this course are the compulsory readings \u2013 around 50 pages a class. You will read theories of state formation, as well as practical case studies of state failure (\u2018Why have some many children died in a Gorakhpur hospital?\u2019) and attempts to reform the state (\u2018Are AAP\u2019s primary education reforms in Delhi working\u2019?). You will also study the Indian state at the top (\u2018How does Parliament function?\u2019) as well as at the bottom (\u2018What does a Block Development Officer do?\u2019). I guarantee you fun readings, and the total freedom to choose any viewpoint or ideological position -- including (and especially) those that are opposed to mine. </p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>At the heart of this course are the compulsory readings \u2013 around 40 pages a class (80 pages a week). You will read theories of state formation, as well as practical case studies of state failure (\u2018Why have some many children died in a Gorakhpur hospital?\u2019) and attempts to reform the state (\u2018Are AAP\u2019s primary education reforms in Delhi working\u2019?). You will also study the Indian state at the top (\u2018How does Parliament function?\u2019) as well as at the bottom (\u2018What does a Block Development Officer do?\u2019). I guarantee you fun readings, and the total freedom to choose any viewpoint or ideological position -- including (and especially) those that are opposed to mine. </p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>GRADING BREAKUP</p><p>10% Class participation in the online discussion section<br>25% Response papers<br>25% Mid-terms exam<br>40% Final paper</p><p> </p><p>GRADING RUBRIC:</p><p>I grade on a curve. Usually 25% of class gets an A/A-; 50% gets B+/B/B-; and 25% gets below B-.</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Attendance is compulsory, unless you have a 'validated' excuse. </p></div></div>",
