            "document":"https://ams.ashoka.edu.in/UploadFiles/Content/ProgramCourseInfo/PHI-3630/PHI-4630[PHI-3630/PHI-4630-1]/dfd0acbd-5e4e-4ebb-987a-271ab5447a80.pdf",
            "html_details":"<div><strong>Office timing</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>By appointment and regularly at a time TBD by vote.</p></div></div><div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This course considers a range of philosophical questions about the foundations of morality, such as whether (or in what sense) morality is objective, the nature of moral discourse, and how we can come to know right from wrong. We will survey some popular answers to these foundational questions. We will also cover a few special topics, like the relationship between moral realism and aesthetic realism, whether it\u2019s possible to be too moral, and what (if any) light considering scientific and historical questions about our moral judgments and practices can shed on foundational questions about morality.</p><p><strong>offered by</strong>: Associate Professor Dr. Sharon Berry (not on the LMS yet): mailto: <strong>seberry@invariant.org</strong></p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This class aims to make students familiar with some of the most influential arguments and theories in contemporary (western) metaethics. It also aims to improve student skills at</p><p>\u2022 reading, interpreting and creatively responding to dense philosophical texts</p><p>\u2022 productive philosophical conversation</p><p>\u2022 developing and writing up arguments</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>All readings will be available for free on the course website.</p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><table style=\"width:100%;\" cellspacing=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" border=\"1\"><tbody><tr><td>10%</td><td><p>Reading response activities, e.g., comments on assigned texts in Perusal. Due 24 hours before class.</p></td></tr><tr><td>20%</td><td><p>Participation: Credit can be earned by participating in discussions in class or on the course website.</p></td></tr><tr><td>25%</td><td><p>Short Paper (3-4 pages). Your grade will be split as follows: \u202210% abstract/paper pitch<br>\u202230% first draft<br>\u202260% revision (graded to a higher standard)</p></td></tr><tr><td>35%</td><td><p>Medium Paper (4-6 pages). Your grade will be split as above.</p></td></tr><tr><td>10%</td><td><p>Tiny slideshow presentation (2-5 minutes) and subsequent Q&amp;A/discussion</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Extra Credit: There will be many opportunities to earn extra credit.</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Attendance during scheduled course meetings is not mandatory (see participation grades below) but strongly encouraged. All handouts and lectures from class will be available online.</p></div></div><div><strong>Attachment</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><table><tbody><tr><td><a style=\"color:blue\" href=\"https://ams.ashoka.edu.in/UploadFiles/Content/ProgramCourseInfo/PHI-3630/PHI-4630[PHI-3630/PHI-4630-1]/dfd0acbd-5e4e-4ebb-987a-271ab5447a80.pdf\" download=\"Metaethics_Syllabus.pdf\">Metaethics_Syllabus.pdf</a></td></tr></tbody></table></div></div>",
