            "html_details":"<div><strong>Office timing</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>By appointment over email. </p></div></div><div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Groups: Group structure and examples. Subgroups and cosets. Normal subgroups and Quotient groups. Lagrange, Euler and Fermat's  theorem. Homomorphism, Isomorphism, Automorphism. Group actions. Class equation, Cauchy's theorem, Cayley's theorem. Simplicity of alternating group. Sylow theorems.<br> <br>Rings: Rings, Integral domains and fields. Isomorphism, homomorphism and quotient fields. Ideals - prime and maximal. Euclidean domain, division rule. Polynomials, irreducibility and Eisenstein's criterion. Chinese remainder theorem. </p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>We will learn two new algebraic structures: </p><p>1) Group theory will enable us to see how symmetries are captured in these algebraic structures. </p><p>2) Ring theory will enable us to see structures in polynomials which we can exploit for answering many interesting questions. </p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>1) J. A. Gallian: Contemporary Abstract Algebra, Eighth Edition, BROOKS/COLE Cengage Learning, 2013</p><p>2) M. Artin: Algebra, Second Edition, Pearson Prentice-Hall of India, New Delhi, 2011.<br>3) D. S. Dummit and Richard M. Foote: Abstract Algebra, Third Edition, Wiley, 2005.     </p><p>4)   Yvette Kosmann-Schwarzbach: Groups and Symmetries: From Finite Groups to Lie Groups by  Springer, 2010.</p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Assignments - 20 points</p><p>Quiz  - 25 points</p><p>Midsem - 25 points</p><p>Final 30 points. </p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Attendance is not mandatory, however it is strongly recomended that you attend lectures. Regular absentees will be reported to OAA. </p></div></div>",
