            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>PFA syllabus attached. It has all necessary details. </p><p>This course will be very similar to the one offered last year with the same title. </p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>1. Convert different types of data to maps</p><p>2. Shapefile and raster transformations</p><p>3. Google Earth Engine for classification</p><p>4. By the end of the class, you should be able to do most spatial functions such finding best routes for tigers or roads, finding locations for PHCs, compile temperature etc data for the spatial unit of your choice, project climate zones in the future, map conflict, map the view of different users, quantify change in forest or water or urban area or agriculture or water pollution through time, predict floods, etc. You should have the basic skills to tackle any environmental or spatial question. </p><p>For those interested in remote sensing, or using satellite imagery for understanding changes on Earth, I have a remote sensing class in the spring for which this class is a prerequisite (this class only covers basic classification). </p></div></div><div><strong>Attachment</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><table><tbody><tr><td><a style=\"color:blue\" href=\"https://ams.ashoka.edu.in/UploadFiles/Content/ProgramCourseInfo/ES-1901/ES-6901[ES-1901/ES-6901-1]/c401b149-8089-4767-b9a6-5339f7a2d1c0.pdf\" download=\"Syllabus Intro to GIS and Remote Sensing.pdf\">Syllabus Intro to GIS and Remote Sensing.pdf</a></td></tr></tbody></table></div></div>",
