            "html_details":"<div><strong>Office timing</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Will be announced closer to the semester.</p></div></div><div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>This aim of the Calculus section will put more emphasis on applications of Calculus. But we will do things <em>rigorously</em>.</p><p>The course includes sequences, series which give an idea of how to handle infinitely many numbers and operate with them.<br>Using these concepts limits, differentiation and integration of functions is introduced. We will illustrate use of these concepts in real life problems. </p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Will learn about various classes of functions, learn about limits , differentiation, integration and performance these operations on a large class of functions.  Finally learn to apply these concepts to problems that come up in various other areas of study</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Suggested books:</p><p>1.   Essential Calculus - Early Transcendentals -  James Stewart </p><p>2. Calculus and analytical geometry - Thomas Finney </p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Will be combination of assignments/quizzes, mid term and final term. </p><p>Tentatively:</p><p>Assignment/ quizz component : 35% (the exact number of assignments or class quizzes will be shared before beginning of the semester)</p><p>Mid term : 25%</p><p>Final term : 40%</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Plan to attend the lectures. Lectures will help you read the book and understand the material and solve the problems. That said, attendance is not mandatory. In case we have in-person lectures, I may give quizzes in class. There may be additional quizzes in discussion sessions. No makeup quizzes are given. </p></div></div>",
