            "html_details":"<div><strong>Office timing</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Help will be available to those who ask for it. I will have office hours by appointment. You may also speak with me right before or after class. Some further hours may be blocked regularly depending on the requirement. </p></div></div><div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>The Calculus is a major achievement of humanity without which none of the developments in modern science, technology would have been possible. The course is a second look at the subject. It is an introduction to mathematics. It is about building the intuition, knowledge and skills required for studying mathematics and other mathematical subjects. It is an `enabling' course.</p><p>We will follow and read from Spivak's book, which has been described as the `best book on Calculus ever written'. If you read this book, and do many of the problems, you will learn what mathematics is all about, and be prepared to embark upon a scientific or mathematical career. </p><p>Mathematics is learnt by doing mathematics. Be prepared for a lot of doing. In addition to lectures and discussion sessions, expect to spend 8-10 hours outside of class every week working on the material.</p><p> </p><p> </p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>The Syllabus is as follows: </p><p>Number systems. Sequences and series. Functions of a real variable. Graphs of functions. Limits and continuity. Differentiation. Mean value theorem. L\u2019Hospital rule. Maclaurin and Taylor series. Curve tracing. Riemann integral. Definite and indefinite integrals. Fundamental theorem of calculus. Applications of differential and integral calculus in areas such as optimisation and mechanics.</p><p>Other than the above, there are many things in Spivak's book that we will discuss. </p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Textbook:</p><p>1. Spivak, Calculus (4th edition), Publish or Perish, 2008</p><p>2. We require the use of commonly available free or online software, such as graphing calculators (desmos.com) and symbolic algebra packages (Sage). </p><p>Some further books may be suggested for reference depending on the need later. </p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>The following is tentative. </p><p>1. Assignments/Quizzes: 200</p><p>2. Midterms 1 and 2: 200 </p><p>3. Final: 100 </p><p>Total: 500</p><p>More information will be available before the first day of class. In general, expect to solve a bunch of problems every week of the course. </p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Plan to attend the lectures. Lectures will help you read the book and understand the material and solve the problems. That said, attendance is not mandatory. In case we have in-person lectures, I may give quizzes in class. There may be additional quizzes in discussion sessions. No makeup quizzes are given.  </p></div></div>",
