            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Documentary Film Script and Synopsis | Life at Ashoka through the Pandemic</p><p>The main theme of this film is to explore the stories of students at Ashoka University who choose to continue to live on campus due to exceptional domestic circumstances. Primarily, the film delves into their backgrounds and encompasses the variety of reasons which prompt these students to reside at Ashoka instead of going back home to their families. </p><p>However, I would not like to limit it to merely their stories and also explore some of the challenges they face living in a closed environment (like that of campus currently) for exceptionally long periods. Potentially, we could explore the ways they have engaged themselves, how they have developed relationships with people around them, etc. Ideally, I would like to boil it down to whether they prefer living at Ashoka or if it\u2019s their only choice. </p><p>Here are some questions to further clarify the ideas behind this film\u2026 </p><p>(1) Why is this film being made? </p><p>The purpose of this film is twofold\u2026 </p><p>(a) The primary motive here is to give these students a voice. It essentially aims to help them by giving them a platform to speak up. Especially, in the case of students who belong to a background where they have been emotionally/physically abused. Hopefully, by providing them with a platform, we\u2019ll be able to help them be more proud of the challenges they are rising through. </p><p>(b) There is a notion within the Ashokan Community that the administration is not empathetic enough towards its students. Thus, by voicing these issues, it can potentially be a way to appeal to the admin to further help such students, not only current ones but in the future as well. </p><p>(2) Who is the targeted audience and what should their reaction to the film be? The primary Target Audience definitely would definitely be the Ashokan Community. However, if this film turns out well, it could have a great impact. There is no expected reaction that I am considering. However, by the end of this film, we aim for more people to recognise the challenges of Remote Learning especially for those who do not have the privilege of a conducive household. At the same time, for more privileged viewers, maybe they will actually be cognizant of what they have. </p><p>(3) What will be the film\u2019s technical conditions of use and style of this film?</p><p>I plan to make this film a combination of direct interviews, paired with montage sequences of the characters as well as stock shots pertinent to the relevant storyline. Ideally, I would like to use \u2018actuality\u2019 (having characters enact things that are intrinsic to them) and \u2018wallpaper technique\u2019 (usage of pictures to profile the characters of the movie) to use as the visuals for the film. Additionally, stock shots of the movie would be based on the interviews we record. For example, if someone tells us that one of the challenges they faced living here was the food, we could have a shot of the mess, so on and so forth. </p><p>The Characters </p><p>To make this documentary authentic, we would like to screen people and get to know them off-camera before interviewing them. This will help us get to know how comfortable they are sharing their stories and to what extent they would like to share. It would also help us to explain our purpose behind making this film in the first place. I would like to put out a casting call and screen the interviewees/characters of this film during the first week (see week by week breakup). </p><p>The Storyline </p><p>This is a brief storyline for the film, </p><p>(a) Initially, the storyline would seek to profile our characters and have the audience get to know them and where they come from. I would like to keep this as brief as possible. (b) Then we delve deeper into the challenges they have faced in life and explore the reason(s) which prompt them to stay here. </p><p>(c) After that, I would like to explore the challenges of living at Ashoka - this can encompass a variety of reasons but we would like to essentially centre it in the context of the Ashoka Administration. </p><p>(d) I would like to conclude this film with positive reinforcement of these characters and to portray them as potential changemakers of affirmative action. </p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>DEVELOPMENT: turn your idea into a workable script, storyboard and schedule.</p><p>PRODUCTION: develop skills to shoot original short documentary films and turn a zero-to-low budget to your advantage.</p><p>POST-PRODUCTION: learn basic editing techniques to enhance your original idea using iMovie, Premiere and other popular tools.</p><p> </p></div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>A weekly report of assignments through the semester will be an ascending base of developing skills in seeing, making a media product and maintaining a proper record of the process.</p> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Weekly Update </p><p>Week by Week Tentative Schedule </p><p>Week 1: Casting Calls, Screening and finalising people for interviews, Finalising color palettes for the film. </p><p>Week 2 and Week 3: Finalising initial script for the movie, start conducting interviews. Week 4 and Week 5: Analysing content acquired through interviews and filming stock shots for the same.</p><p>Week 6 and Week 7: First round editing, will go over the script and conduct another round of interviews based on feedback and analysis of original interviews. </p><p>Week 8 onwards: Post Production</p></div></div>",
