            "html_details":"<div><strong>Overview</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p> </p><p>Class timings Tue-Fri 11.50 am to 1.20 pm</p><p>The grammar tradition of Sanskrit is witness to many creations by acharyas at different points of time. P\u0101\u1e47ini is one of the most renowned acharyas of the tradition who in his creation/text, the A\u1e63\u1e6d\u0101dh\u0101y\u012b, compiled and organized different grammar and linguistic principles including those of syntax, distributional structure, phonetics, word formation, etc. Moreover, two widely studied characteristics of the text include scientific organization, and brevity of content. The brevity is made possible by various techniques, one of which is formalism.</p><p>The course, Introduction to Paninian formalism and linguistics, will present to students the formalism of the A\u1e63\u1e6d\u0101dh\u0101y\u012b' and some basic concepts of its linguistics. Besides A\u1e63\u1e6d\u0101dh\u0101y\u012b, some other supplementary texts will also be studied in parts to help the students get initiated into the system of P\u0101\u1e47ini.</p></div></div><div><strong>Learning Outcomes</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><strong>Objective</strong>: To get acquainted with P\u0101\u1e47ini's formalism, linguistics, and an overall system of his grammar through a\u1e63\u1e6d\u0101dh\u0101y\u012b and a few supplementary texts</p><p><strong>Credits</strong>: 4 credits</p><p><strong>Target</strong>: Open to all students</p></div></div><div><strong>Requirements (Reading List and other materials)</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>Pre-requisites:</p><ul><li>No prior background in Sanskrit is required</li><li>Familiarity with the devanagari script is expected</li></ul><p><strong>Note</strong>: Some Sanskrit language basics will be taught in the initial few weeks to enable better comprehension of the text. Students should be willing to learn them.</p> </div></div><div><strong>Grading Rubric</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p><strong>Grading Rubric:</strong></p><ul><li>3 graded quizzes (60%)</li><li>Class participation/Presentation (10%)</li><li>End semester examination (30%)</li><li>Class assignments (Weekly or fortnightly) \u2013 qualifying and compulsory</li></ul> </div></div><div><strong>Attendance Policy</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><p>1. <strong>Attendance</strong> Students may be allowed to watch recordings in case of absence due to medical or technical issues. No fixed rule for compulsory attendance applies in the virtual or offline semester. Missing classes should not be the norm though and leniency in this regard will be decided on a case-to-case basis. </p><p>2. <strong>Audit</strong> <strong>policy</strong>- the course will be open for audit students with prior approval. Examination and presentations are optional but assignments should be submitted regularly like registered students.</p><p> </p></div></div><div><strong>Attachment</strong><div class=\"cmsDescp\"><table><tbody><tr><td><a style=\"color:blue\" href=\"https://ams.ashoka.edu.in/UploadFiles/CourseCatalogueFiles/1d237f2c-21df-4ad1-a590-7872e3c70b10.pdf\" download=\"CC_formalism_m21.pdf\">CC_formalism_m21.pdf</a></td></tr></tbody></table></div></div>",
